08:31:40','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=event&#038;p=967',0,'event','',0),(969,16,'2015-02-02 10:00:20','2015-02-02 18:00:20','It’s Valentine season again, that wonderful time of year when so many husbands and wives attempt to recapture in one big moment all the missed little moments of the previous year—like one large deposit to balance countless small withdrawals. Of course, I’m only talking to myself. But then, maybe not.\n\nDon’t misunderstand me, I’m all for celebrating with my wife in a big way on special occasions—which reminds me, reservations! Even so, I’ve been learning the irreplaceable value, joy, and power of lots and lots of small deposits in marriage. I heard a news report last week of a man in the Midwest who has been saving his pennies. His grandfather told him, \"a penny saved is a penny earned.\" So…after more than 50 years, he finally hauled them all to the bank. Three truckloads and a few tons later, he walked away with over $65,000! From pennies!\n<h4>Business guru, Nido Qubien, made this profound observation: Most worthwhile achievements are the result of many little things done in a single direction.</h4>\nThe poet, W.H. Auden, penned this truth: Like everything which is not the involuntary result of fleeting emotion but the creation of time and will, any marriage, happy or unhappy, is infinitely more interesting than any romance, however passionate.\n\nSmall, frequent, consistent, intentional deposits really do add up. Here’s an idea. Why not make Valentine’s a lifetime theme rather than an annual event? Why not fill the next 12 months, or next 12 years, with pennies of countless \"I love you’s?\" Need a few ideas? Here’s a start.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>LOVING THINGS FOR HUSBANDS TO DO</strong>\n\nSay “I love you” several times a day.\n\nTell her often how beautiful she is.\n\nKiss her several times a day.\n\nSeek her advice when making decisions.\n\nShow sincere interest in what she does.\n\nBring her flowers unexpectedly.\n\nSmile at her often.\n\nPlan a surprise night out.\n\nAsk if there are things you can do for her.\n\nCommunicate with her intimately.\n\nShare with her what is on your heart.\n\nShow affection to her in public.\n\nTrain yourself to think of her needs first.\n\nShow her you are proud to be her husband.\n\nCompliment her on something each day.\n\nGive her details when she asks about your day.\n\nDon’t talk negatively to her, or about her to others.\n\nCall her during the day just to say, “I love you”.\n\nTell her she is your greatest claim to fame.\n\nListen to her talk  (without distraction).\n\nResearch and show genuine interest in the things she values.\n\nShow her you believe in her.\n\nPray for her every day.\n\nLet her hear you thank God for her.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<strong>LOVING THINGS FOR WIVES TO DO</strong>\n\nPray for him daily.\n\nShow him you love him unconditionally.\n\nTell him you think he’s the greatest.\n\nShow him you believe in him.\n\nDon’t talk negatively to him, or about him to others.\n\nTell him daily that you love him.\n\nGive him adoring looks.\n\nTake a genuine interest in his hobbies (do a little research on it).\n\nShow him that you adore being with him.\n\nListen to him when he talks with you, with undivided attention (even if you really are good at multi-tasking).\n\nHug him affectionately often.\n\nKiss him tenderly and romantically often.\n\nInitiate physical intimacy.\n\nDemonstrate your support for him in public.\n\nDo nice things for him he doesn’t expect.\n\nShow others you are proud to be his wife.\n\nEmphasize his strengths, not his weaknesses.\n\nAccept him; don’t try to mold him into someone else.\n\nRevel in his joys; share in his disappointments.\n\nShow him that your favorite times are with him.\n\nLeave “I love you” notes in unexpected places.\n\nTell him he’s you\'re greatest claim to fame.\n\nLet him hear you thank God for him.\n\n&nbsp;','Marriage: Think Small','','trash','closed','closed','','marriage-think-small__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=969',0,'post','',0),(970,36,'2015-03-16 10:51:44','2015-03-16 18:51:44','','The Spirit and Worship','','publish','closed','closed','','the-spirit-and-worship','','','2015-03-16 10:51:44','2015-03-16 18:51:44','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=970',74,'teaching','',0),(973,4,'2015-03-18 00:08:39','2015-03-18 08:08:39','<h1>Easter with Bridgetown Church</h1>\r\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\r\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\r\n<div class=\"column\">\r\n\r\nWe live in a world of constant struggle: good vs. evil, clean vs. dirty, broken vs. whole. Rather than pretend like this tension doesn’t exist we want to live in the place where heaven and earth meet, where mankind finds itself every day. Inspired by glimpses of glory, we wade through the difficulties because we have a promise in the future. Jesus will put the world to rights and that which is broken will be made whole.\r\n\r\nBridgetown Church is hosting Easter gatherings at the Crystal Ballroom in Downtown Portland.\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Easter Gatherings</h1>\r\nGather with us as we worship together, explore the story of Jesus, and celebrate the defeat of death.\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Dates:</strong> March 27\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Time:</strong> 9 AM, 11 AM, &amp; 6 PM\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Doors:</strong> 8 AM &amp; 5 PM\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Cost:</strong> None\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Location:</strong> Crystal Ballroom, 1332 W Burnside St., Portland, OR\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Childcare:</strong> Ages 0 - 5\r\nNo Childcare at 6 PM\r\n[/one_third][one_third_last]\r\n<h1>Pre-Gathering Prayer</h1>\r\nAll are welcome and encouraged to participate as we ask the Holy Spirit to work at the gatherings.\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Dates:</strong> March 27\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Time:</strong> 8 AM &amp; 5 PM\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Location:</strong> Balcony at Crystal Ballroom\r\n[/one_third_last]\r\n<h1>Social Media</h1>\r\n<span style=\"color: #525252;\">Spread the word on social media. Invite your friends and family to gather with us on Easter Sunday as we celebrate the defeat of death. Click images to enlarge.</span>\r\n\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 15px 0 0\"]\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/bt_easter_2016_gram_ocean.jpg\" target=\"blank\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2151\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/bt_easter_2016_gram_ocean.jpg\" alt=\"bt_easter_2016_gram_ocean\" width=\"1920\" height=\"2400\" /></a>\r\n[/one_third][one_third padding=\"0 15px 0 0\"]\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/bt_easter_2016_gram_hedge.jpg\" target=\"blank\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2152\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/bt_easter_2016_gram_hedge.jpg\" alt=\"bt_easter_2016_gram_hedge\" width=\"1920\" height=\"2400\" /></a>\r\n[/one_third][one_third_last padding=\"0 15px 0 0\"]\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/bt_easter_2016_gram_sky.jpg\" target=\"blank\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-2153\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/bt_easter_2016_gram_sky.jpg\" alt=\"bt_easter_2016_gram_sky\" width=\"1920\" height=\"2400\" /></a>\r\n[/one_third_last]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Easter','','publish','closed','closed','','easter','','','2016-03-15 14:22:33','2016-03-15 22:22:33','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=973',0,'page','',0),(981,20,'2015-02-09 14:17:34','2015-02-09 22:17:34','<p class=\"p1\"><i>Foster Parent’s Night Out (FPNO) is a monthly outreach to foster kids in partnership with DHS and multiple host churches across the Portland metro area.  Many Missional Communities are coming together to serve foster kids and their families through this event.</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">Lilly stands there, eyes transfixed on a little girl in pigtails running across a room full of energetic kids. She ignores the enormous colored posters, the crafting table covered with glue sticks and constructed Easter baskets, and the screaming delight of youth playing a game of tag. As a foster child, estranged from family and blood siblings, her eyes doubt the sight before her.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\"><i>Can it be?</i></p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">Her eyes follow the girl across the room. The small girl, laughing, pauses as she recognizes the newcomer. Lilly yells her name and races towards her. Heads turn as the two stand in the center of the room in a tight embrace. The younger one, pigtails buried in Lilly’s shoulder, shouts back, “No one told me my sister was going to be here!”</p>\r\n\r\n<div class=\"embed-container\"><iframe src=\"http://www.youtube.com/embed/7dBBMnciLRE\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p class=\"p3\">These rare, and heart-wrenching moments are taking place at Foster Parent’s Night Out, a DHS approved monthly event hosted by several local churches in Portland and surrounding counties.  “It wasn’t something I ever envisioned happening,” says Kristy, co-organizer of FPNO at Westside: A Jesus Church. During this year alone, she has witnessed two sibling reunions and knows of several half-siblings who get to spend a rare evening together. All because of one night a month devoted to giving foster parents a break, and providing a safe environment for their kids to enjoy.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">Chris and Kristy first discovered FPNO after attending a DHS training in Salem, OR. Sharing a common love for the fatherless with their Missional Community, they inquired about replicating a similar event closer to home. “We found out that the core eight couples in our Missional Community were, at one time, either foster kids, had foster kids living in their family, or were themselves adopted,” recalls Chris. “There wasn’t a person who hadn\'t touched by fostering.”</p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">From there, the idea caught momentum and people began to respond.  “Our Missional Community coordinates the plans for the FPNO event and then other Missional Communities surround us and help us pull the event off,” explains Chris. Since last November, Westside has consistently brought together 40-60 foster kids and over one hundred trained volunteers each month. While parents spend an evening to themselves, their kids eat a healthy dinner and take part in monthly-themed crafts and games.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">For foster parents, Joy and Rustin, FPNO cannot come soon enough. “We’ve gone to all of them. Our world shuts down. It is our one night and we are so excited when it comes!” says foster mom, Joy. With five kids, the Jenkinson’s home is a constant flurry of activity and meeting the challenges of each day leaves little time to reflect and communicate as spouses.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">Like a lot of families, Rustin and Joy do not have relatives in the area supporting them on a regular basis.  The consistent community FPNO brings has been an overwhelming blessing for families like the Jenkinsons.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p3\">“Every week there is some big change that is going to impact us one way or another.  FPNO helps us reconnect with each other,” Rustin says.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p4\">The impact of Missional Communities is uniting long-lost siblings and supporting exhausted parents in foster homes across Washington County. It’s creating a greater family. As one foster daughter explains it, she senses a support she has never experienced before, a cheering section of epic proportions, surrounding and encouraging her and the hundreds alongside her.</p>\r\n<p class=\"p4\"><em>To learn more about Foster Parent\'s Night Out and how to get involved, visit</em> <a href=\"http://fpno.org/\" target=\"_blank\">FPNO.org</a></p>','Foster Parent\'s Night Out','','publish','closed','closed','','foster-parents-night-out','','','2016-07-19 03:00:08','2016-07-19 11:00:08','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=981',0,'post','',0),(988,4,'2015-03-18 16:01:33','2015-03-19 00:01:33','','ajc_easter_2015_hero3','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_easter_2015_hero3','','','2015-03-18 16:01:33','2015-03-19 00:01:33','',973,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/ajc_easter_2015_hero3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(997,4,'2015-03-18 18:04:55','2015-03-19 02:04:55','','ajc_easter_2015_hero3','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_easter_2015_hero3-2','','','2015-03-18 18:04:55','2015-03-19 02:04:55','',973,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/ajc_easter_2015_hero31.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1004,4,'2015-03-19 11:22:15','2015-03-19 19:22:15','','ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_darkblue','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_darkblue','','','2015-03-19 11:22:15','2015-03-19 19:22:15','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_darkblue.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1005,4,'2015-03-19 11:22:19','2015-03-19 19:22:19','','ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_lightblue','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_lightblue','','','2015-03-19 11:22:19','2015-03-19 19:22:19','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_lightblue.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1006,4,'2015-03-19 11:22:23','2015-03-19 19:22:23','','ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_yellow','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_yellow','','','2015-03-19 11:22:23','2015-03-19 19:22:23','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/03/ajc_bt_easter_2015_insta_yellow.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0