','','ajc_bt_sweatshop_tile_','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_sweatshop_tile_-2','','','2015-05-08 09:15:37','2015-05-08 17:15:37','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/05/ajc_bt_sweatshop_tile_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1048,4,'2015-05-08 09:15:47','2015-05-08 17:15:47','','ajc_bt_sweatshop_hero_','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_sweatshop_hero_-2','','','2015-05-08 09:15:47','2015-05-08 17:15:47','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/05/ajc_bt_sweatshop_hero_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1049,4,'2015-05-10 11:23:53','2015-05-10 19:23:53','','ajc_bt_1thess_hero','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_1thess_hero-3','','','2015-05-10 11:23:53','2015-05-10 19:23:53','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/05/ajc_bt_1thess_hero2.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1050,4,'2015-05-10 11:25:58','2015-05-10 19:25:58','','ajc_bt_1thess_hero','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_1thess_hero-4','','','2015-05-10 11:25:58','2015-05-10 19:25:58','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/05/ajc_bt_1thess_hero3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1052,10,'2015-05-10 18:49:14','2015-05-11 02:49:14','','The People Of The Future','','publish','closed','closed','','the-people-of-the-future','','','2015-05-12 14:29:34','2015-05-12 22:29:34','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1052',67,'teaching','',0),(1057,4,'2015-05-12 10:05:32','2015-05-12 18:05:32','','ajc_web_hero_44','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_web_hero_44','','','2015-05-12 10:05:32','2015-05-12 18:05:32','',9,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2014/04/ajc_web_hero_44.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1081,34,'2015-02-19 15:08:31','2015-02-19 23:08:31','<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nIf you’ve been around our church for any amount of time you’ll notice that we often visit Genesis 1 as a starting point for many of our teachings... Why is that?\n\nWell, for one, the <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">Gospel </span>(or, the good news about the reality of who Jesus is) is often presented in a truncated, individualistic, and quite frankly, self-centered way. For the most part, the Gospel is delivered in bullet point format and focus’ heavily on <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">our </span>sin, Jesus’ death, burial, and resurrection (for <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">us</span>), and <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">us </span>going to \"heaven\" when we die. But therein lies the problem. That’s a telling of the story that begins in Genesis 3 (the fall), not chapter 1 (creation).\n\nSo we visit and re-visit the intro to the story we call the Bible over and over because it’s the foundation on which the greater story is placed—the very same story we find ourselves in. And, it’s in this story that we see a God who sets out on a <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">mission </span>to rescue <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">both </span>humanity <em>and</em> creation for h<span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">is </span>name’s sake; the Gospel.\n\nWhich leads us to a question, “What is the <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">Mission of God</span>?”\n\nWell, if we assume the Bible begins in Genesis 3 and wraps up in Revelation 20 (rather than 22 when God re-makes the world) then we see the mission of God being centered around <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">us</span>. But like any good story, if we miss the opening and closing scenes, we’ll miss the most important parts.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nCover to cover, we see <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">creation to re-creation</span>... a massively important framework to work from if we want to properly understand the rest of the story.\n\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Qoute-big.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-1090\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Qoute-big.jpg\" alt=\"Qoute big\" width=\"717\" height=\"403\" /></a>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">So where did we get off?</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\"> First: </span>A truncated view of the Bible leads to a truncated view of Gospel. And a truncated view of Gospel leads to a truncated view of the mission of God.\n\nAt some point, we condensed the story of the Bible down to a formula, and we missed the point.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Second: </span>Distractions—or put another way—things that keep us from <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">wanting </span>to see the mission of God, have pulled our attention away from the greater story we’re a part of.\n\n- <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">Consumerism </span>rather than being kingdom-minded.\n- <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">Individualism </span>rather than actually giving ourselves to community.\n- <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">Dualism </span>rather than grasping that <em>everything</em> we do is spiritual.\n\nBy now you may be asking, “Ok.. I get all that, but you haven’t defined what you’re talking about, what is the mission of God?”\n\nGreat question!\n\nUnfortunately, it’s not black and white, sorry... that desire for an either/or, yes/no, or “the quick application,” is residue from a modern lens that, thankfully, we’re moving past as a culture. That said, it\'s often helpful with these kind of questions, let’s start with what it’s not.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">What the mission of God ISN’T. </span>\n\n<strong>1. It’s not just m<span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">aking decisions </span>— saying some sinner\'s prayer</strong>\n\nI remember years ago praying with a guy in the mall by my house to \"receive Jesus.\" After we said “amen” I congratulated him, told him to have a nice day, patted him on the back, then left. Looking back on that interaction, I have no idea what happened in his life from that moment forward. While I’d like to believe he went from there with a passion to read the scriptures, a desire to learn to enjoy Jesus, and an excitement to find a few people he could be honest with, it probably didn’t turn out that way. It’s for that same reason that the mission of God can’t be distilled down to the <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">first </span>definable moment of following Jesus—the <em>journey</em> is just as important.\n\nIf making decisions was the point, then the best and most convincing speaker wins. But Jesus seemed to say that we’re all in this together and that this story belongs to all of us.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 3\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\n<strong>2. It’s not <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">detaching ourselves from the world around us </span></strong>\n\nOne of my greatest regrets in life was doing this very thing to a close friend. We basically grew up together, we went through the worst stuff together, and then I became a \"pastor.” When he asked me to officiate his wedding, I immediately asked him where he wanted to get married.\n\n“A church right?”\n\n“No, I was thinking at our house.”\n\n“Hmm, well... You’re not living together are you?”\n\n“Of course we are, I love her, that’s why we’re getting married.”\n\nAnd then I said it, “Sorry, I don’t think I can do your wedding then.”\n\nThe guy I grew up with, the guy who knew pretty much everything about me didn’t invite me to his wedding. Honestly, our friendship froze at that point. All because I didn’t want to put my stamp of approval on something that wasn’t <em>my</em> understanding of perfect. That moment didn’t exemplify the Mission of God; disconnecting from the world around us is not the answer, nor God’s desire.\n\n<strong>3. It’s not a <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">message of destruction,</span> but a message of renewal.</strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">What the mission of God IS. </span>\n\nThe mission of God, simply put, is <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">God\'s work of reconciling and restoring all of creation back to himself</span>. The amazing part is that he doesn’t just repair us, but calls <em>us</em> to be a part of the repairing.\n\nWhen the world lost sight of who God was, Jesus came to break down the dividing wall between us and God by dying for the consequence of sin for us so that we could make him a big deal in and through our lives.\n\nWhat’s even more incredible is that when Jesus birthed the church he gave us three things to help us in taking the mission of God forward.\n\n<strong>1. The ministry of reconciliation.</strong>\nGo show the world; <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">demonstrate </span>kingdom likeness.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 4\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>Therefore, if anyone is in Christ, the new creation has come: The old has gone, the new is here! All this is from God, who reconciled us to himself through Christ and gave us the ministry of reconciliation: that God was reconciling the world to himself in Christ, not counting people’s sins against them. </em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">2 Corinthians 5v17-19a</p>\n<strong>2. The message of reconciliation.</strong>\nGo tell the world; <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">share the story </span>of who Jesus is.\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>And he has committed to us the message of reconciliation. We are therefore Christ’s ambassadors, as though God were making his appeal through us. We implore you on Christ’s behalf: Be reconciled to God. God made him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in him we might become the righteousness of God. </em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">2 Corinthians 5v19b-2</p>\n<strong>3. The means to live out the ministry and share the message—The person of the Holy Spirit</strong>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><em>I am going to send you what my Father has promised; but stay in the city until you have been clothed with power from on high.</em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Luke 24v49</p>\n\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nJust <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">showing </span>is simply social justice. Just <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">telling </span>is hypocrisy.\n\nWe need <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">both</span>.\n\nThe Spirit gives us the ability to do both.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Two questions: </span>\n\n1. What’s been missing, if anything, from the Gospel you\'ve been speaking?\n\n2. How would you now communicate the Gospel to someone today?\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Prayer: </span>\n\nJesus, you’re the one who rescued me. And you’re the one who wants to rescue everyone. Help me see you today and show me how I can share your story with those around me.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>','The Mission of God','','trash','closed','closed','','the-mission-of-god__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1081',0,'post','',0),(1095,4,'2015-05-12 15:59:06','2015-05-12 23:59:06','An awesome night to hang out with friends downtown. Come have a good time, race through a scavenger hunt, and eat some ice cream. Meet us in the Bridgetown Church parking lot.','High School Hangout','','publish','closed','closed','','1431475146','','','2015-05-13 08:37:39','2015-05-13 16:37:39','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=event&#038;p=1095',0,'event','',0),(1097,4,'2015-05-13 14:34:41','2015-05-13 22:34:41','Refugees are victims of persecution that flee their homelands in search of hope, justice, and a safe place to raise their families. The unrest in Iraq and Somalia has brought refugees to our doorstep. Come learn how you can love and serve these refugees who now call Portland home.','Refugee Care Information Night','','publish','closed','closed','','1431556481','','','2015-05-28 13:15:46','2015-05-28 21:15:46','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=event&#038;p=1097',0,'event','',0),(1098,10,'2015-05-17 19:55:42','2015-05-18 03:55:42','','Jesus is Lord, Caesar is Not','','publish','closed','closed','','jesus-is-lord-caesar-is-not','','','2015-06-02 10:08:28','2015-06-02 18:08:28','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1098',66,'teaching','',0),(1100,4,'2015-05-20 09:51:44','2015-05-20 17:51:44','','IMG_6012','','inherit','open','open','','img_6012','','','2015-05-20 09:51:44','2015-05-20 17:51:44','',4,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2014/03/IMG_6012.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1101,8,'2015-03-02 11:38:38','2015-03-02 19:38:38','<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 1\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nThe intention for what you\'re about to read is profoundly simple.\n\nGod’s been at work in both creation and humanity since day one. Unlike some parents who leave after starting a relationship with their son or daughter, the God that created the universe has always longed—and still does—to be deeply connected to us on every level. Heart, soul, mind, and strength. Whole person. Because of that desire, he’s stayed close. <span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">Never once has he left us</span>.\n\nI believe the way in which God interacts with us is much greater, far more beautiful, and all around more <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">open </span>than many of us have been taught or come to assume. God is bigger than the capacity that our minds have to capture his entirety. This was true, is true, and will stay true of us until the resurrection. What <a href=\"http://www.thegodstoriesproject.com/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold; font-style: oblique;\">The God Stories Project </span></a>aims at is simply expanding our degree of willingness to accept the ways in which God speaks that we may otherwise dismiss.\n\nHere’s what I mean...\n\nIn Exodus 3, God speaks to a man named Moses in an incredibly odd and ,well, <em>unnatural</em> way. He ignites a desert bush (or tree), that—even though appears to be on fire—doesn’t deteriorate. This was God’s means of getting Moses’ attention in the moment so that he could tell Moses something important.\n\nHonestly, I think if we heard about that kind of interaction occurring today, we\'d think the one telling us the story was out of their mind. We suspect durg or alcohol abuse. <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">But that\'s what happened</span>. God revealed himself to this man by lighting up a desert bush and begins speaking to the guy. Apparently, God’s communication in this moment was something Moses could understand.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nOr how about the time, “The LORD appeared to Abraham...” in Genesis 18 as he was sitting out front of his tent? He looks up, sees three men standing nearby, and offeres them a bite to eat. A few minutes later one of these complete strangers tells Abraham that he and his wife, now well into their 90’s, will have a son this time next year.\n\nGod chose to reveal himself in the form of a stranger who, after eating lunch, shares a really odd message.\n\nOr how about the time God audibly woke a boy named Samuel up from his sleep in 1 Samuel 3?\n\nWhat would your first reaction be if a young person sent you a text saying they literally heard God speak to them last night, and it wasn’t through a verse, or a sunset, but by words that were as clear as if they were talking with someone face-to-face?\n\nHow would you respond internally?\n\nWhat would your immediate untrained thought be?\n\nIt’s <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">that </span>doubt and emotion that <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">The God Stories Project </span>aims to tackle head-on so that we can move further into enjoying this incredible God who longs for us to become more aware of his presence.\n\nIf God is constantly communicating with us<span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">, </span>then I wonder how often we miss his voice simply because his momentary communicative method doesn’t fit into our ‘<span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">this is how God speaks’ </span>box.\n\nThere’s a line in John’s Gospel where Jesus says, “Remain in my love...” (John 15v9)\n\nLater in Jude that same idea surfaces again, “Keep yourself in God’s love...” (Jude 1v21)\n\nJesus—the invisible Creator God made visible to humanity in bodily form—precedes the “Remain in my love” line by saying, “As the Father has loved me, so I have loved you” (John 15v9). He chooses to put <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">those </span>words in <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">that </span>order.\n\nWow. Really?\n\nDo I believe that Jesus loves me like the Father loves him? Because that sure releases a lot of life stress if I do. Jesus, God in flesh, says he took the full amount and capacity that exists within the Father to love <em>h</em><span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">im </span>and he gives that same heavy, full, and complete love to <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">us</span>. Maybe that’s why he goes on to say, “remain in my love”.\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 2\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nJesus says this. The invisible Creator God made visible to humanity in bodily form.\n\n<em>Selah</em>.\n\n\"Selah\" is used throughout the Scriptures and seen quite often in the Psalms. It is thought to mean, “pause” or “chew on it,” or, “meditate on what’s been said.” In this case, it takes us slowing down and thinking about what it actually means that Jesus is God made visible to better grasp the weight of what that means for us right now.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 3\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nStay in that place.\n\nAs if to say, “There’s nothing better out there. Nothing that can do for you what <em>my</em> presence does.”\n\nYeah but I’m easily distracted. How do I <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">remain in God’s love</span>?\n\nWe stay there by reminding ourselves of what he’s said about us in the Scriptures. It’s through reading and hearing the Scriptures that we learn what his voice sounds like.\n\nEven so, life is confusing. It’s hard to know what to believe. How do I <em>remain</em> in God’s love? We stay there by making room in our soul (mind, will, and emotions) for his words.\n\nA few chapters earlier in John’s Gospel, Jesus is talking to a group of people who thought they deserved to be close to God, on their own terms, because of their family history. But Jesus rebukes them and says, “You have no room for My word.” See, they thought they could be close to God while rejecting what God said. It was their misplaced confidence in the fact that God would only communicate with them in ways they expected, which led them to miss God <em>actually</em> speaking to them.\n\nIt’s easy to forget that God is a big God and we cannot—no matter how smart we think we are—confine God to a statement, concept, or idea. It’s about as effective as trying to contain an elephant with a fine thread. Good luck.\n\nThe Message puts it this way: “Make yourselves at home in My love.”\n\nWhat a picture! It’s as if Jesus is saying, “Plop down and get comfy in that place. Enjoy it. Make it yours. It’s warm, inviting, well lit. It’s <em>home</em>.”\n\nThen verses eleven through fourteen record Jesus’ next words.\n\n“I’ve told you these things for a purpose: that my joy might be your joy, and your joy wholly mature. This is my command: Love one another the way I loved you. This is the very best way to love. Put your life on the line for your friends. You are my friends when you do the things I command you.”\n\nIn other words, “Do you want to know how to love people? Look at <em>me</em>. Oh and by the way, if you do what I tell you (that is, remaining in my love) then we’re friends, because you’re at home in me.” This shouldn’t be confused with, “Do what I tell you or else! If you break any rule, tradition, or system, you might as well be as far from me as possible!”\n\nIn fact, check out the next words that come out of Jesus’ mouth:\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">“I no longer call you servants, because a servant does not know his master’s business. Instead, I have called you friends, for everything that I learned from my Father I have made known to you.” </span>\n\nNotice three things:\n<ol>\n	<li>Jesus calls us <em>friends</em>.</li>\n	<li>Jesus says he told us <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">everything h</span>e heard from his Father. Whoa.</li>\n	<li>Friends talk. Am I listening?</li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 4\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\nWhile both the John 15 and Jude 1 statements sit within a context—that is, they were written at a certain time, to a specific people, a part of a definable culture—there’s an important life-reality we need to grasp here. We’re to make an effort to stay in a close-knit, active awareness of God. Pragmatically, it looks like any healthy relationship would; honest, ongoing two-way communication.\n\nSo we listen, then we speak. Again and again and again.\n\nYou see, whether we like it or not, most of us hold onto a modern model of thinking. We prefer clear bullet points and reproducible, guaranteed formulas. That’s why a red flag (doubt) goes up when we hear about interactions people have had with God that go beyond simply reading the Scriptures. We identify those moments as loose and unstable, and we begin to think, “There\'s no way to know for sure.\"\n\nDon’t get me wrong, I hold the Scriptures in the highest regard. I memorized 2 Timothy 3v16 when I was a young kid and still believe it. But while I\'m far from assuming an <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">everything is relative </span>mindset, I do believe God is alive, active, and speaks to humanity often. The moments he does so may not always be the ones with a cup of coffee and my Bible in front of me. This is what pushes me to be aware of my tendency to box him in, to restrict how and when he <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">should </span>speak.\n\n—\n\nThe value of the stories collected and displayed through <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">The God Stories Project</span>, if coupled with the desire to know and experience more of God, could be the catalyst for a massively freeing moment in your life. My hope and prayer is that it is.\n\n<span style=\"font-weight: bold;\">A warning though: </span>One that the greedy consumer in me wishes we could avoid. While God is not silent, we do have the ability to obey or disobey what he says.\n\nSometimes our modern saturated minds will yell, \"When!? God, tell me the exact time and place to apply this!” So rather than another <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">word </span>from God, what if we\'re to enjoy or obey one he\'s already given?\n\nLonging for Him to speak is great, but his <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">speaking </span>may be intended for more than just sound or experience. It’s easy (and good) to want “more of God,” but how much of that “more” are we willing to <em>surrender</em> to?\n\nIf we\'re busy asking for <span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">more</span>, something we often excel at, then we run the risk of either missing the joy in what we’ve been given, or missing the obedience to what he’s said. This cycle can produce a prostitution of his words to us as simply another form of entertainment or emotional high.\n\nSo it’s important to ask yourself:\n<ul>\n	<li>What has he already said to me?</li>\n	<li>Would he say the Scriptures are outdated? Mined completely with nothing left to accept?</li>\n</ul>\nNo way.\nSo why do we think the things he spoke yesterday, last week, month, year, or decade hold nothing for us? May we grow in patience to listen,\nto receive, and to <em>obey</em>, as we live in what he\'s already said in the Scriptures, through Jesus, and to us through all the means he chooses.\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"page\" title=\"Page 5\">\n<div class=\"section\">\n<div class=\"layoutArea\">\n<div class=\"column\">\n\n—\nWelcome to <a href=\"http://www.thegodstoriesproject.com/\" target=\"_blank\"><span style=\"font-weight: bold; font-style: oblique;\">The God Stories Project</span></a><span style=\"font-style: oblique;\">. </span>\n\n<em><span style=\"color: #c0c0c0;\">The link provided is a convenience for informational purposes only; it does not constitute an endorsement or an approval by the A Jesus Church Family of any of the products, services, or opinions of the organization or individual. The A Jesus Church Family bears no responsibility for the accuracy, legality, or content of the external site or for that of subsequent links. Contact the external site for answers to questions regarding its content.</span></em>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>','Releasing the Framework','','trash','closed','closed','','releasing-the-framework__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1101',0,'post','',0),(1102,4,'2015-05-20 09:56:45','2015-05-20 17:56:45','','ajc_bt_web_hero_1','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_web_hero_1','','','2015-05-20 09:56:45','2015-05-20 17:56:45','',4,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2014/03/ajc_bt_web_hero_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1104,4,'2015-05-20 15:45:39','2015-05-20 23:45:39','<h1>Missional Community Primer</h1>\r\nThe purpose of this primer is to help you establish your missional community well. Becoming a thriving missional community is not easy. It takes a lot of work. But with hard work comes the knowledge that you have a family supporting you, becoming more like Jesus with you, and sharing the good news of Jesus alongside you. We want to walk you through the first several weeks of your new missional community. Each week you will watch a video from our friends at Soma, one of the leading advocates for missional communities in the nation.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/05/bt_mc_primer_digital_new.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Missional Community Primer</a> <a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/blueprint/\">Submit Blueprint</a> [/page_actions]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h1>Week One</h1>\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'http://player.vimeo.com/video/128505532\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last]<strong>Definition of a Growing Disciple</strong>\r\nWithin missional communities, our goal is to be disciples of Jesus who make disciples of Jesus. In order to succeed at that, the question becomes – what is a disciple and how do we grow as disciples?\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n<h1>Week Two</h1>\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'http://player.vimeo.com/video/128505534\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last]<strong>Disciple-making Environment</strong>\r\nMissional communities can be primary vehicles to make and grow disciples. How might we maximize the environment of our missional communities so we might see the greatest discipleship possible?\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n<h1>Week Three</h1>\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<div class=\"embed-container\"><iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/128505535\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last]<strong>Gospel Power</strong>\r\nThe Gospel of Jesus must be at the center of our missional community. We want to grow as a family of disciples on the mission of Jesus. Our foundation for that growth is the Gospel.\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n<h1>Week Four</h1>\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<div class=\"embed-container\"><iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/128505536\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last]<strong>Gospel-Motivated Living</strong>\r\nWhat we believe dictates what we do. If we want to live as disciples of Jesus on the mission of God then we must live saturated by the Gospel as individuals and in community.\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n<h1>Week Five</h1>\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<div class=\"embed-container\"><iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/128505539\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last]<strong>Everyday Rhythms (Part 1)</strong>\r\nWe do not want missional community to be a program, we want it to be an everyday effort of Jesus’ disciples living on mission and in family. How do we transform our everyday lives to work towards this goal?\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n<h1>Week Six</h1>\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<div class=\"embed-container\"><iframe src=\"http://player.vimeo.com/video/128515941\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></div>\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last]<strong>Everyday Rhythms (Part 2)</strong>\r\nGod has given us 24 hours in a day. How can we use our rescues and our time every day to make sure the Gospel of Jesus is moving forward in everything we do?\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n\r\n<em>These videos are created by Soma. Used by Permission. ©2014 Soma.</em>','Missional Community Primer','','publish','closed','closed','','primer','','','2016-05-04 14:35:32','2016-05-04 22:35:32','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1104',0,'page','',0),(1127,16,'2015-03-19 12:45:47','2015-03-19 19:45:47','The couple stands facing each other, holding hands, surrounded by a pastor, their family and friends, as they utter sacred words of binding love: \"for better or worse; for richer, for poorer; in sickness and in health, in joy and in sorrow...”\n\n<strong>Pop quiz: </strong>In which decade were these vows spoken?\n\nThe 30’s?\n\n60’s?\n\n90’s?\n\nAre vows like these relevant—even <em>possible—</em>today?\n\nIn an age of instant gratification, iPhone distraction, pharmaceutical cornucopia, luxury, contentment, and comfort, why would anyone <em>agree to that</em>? I read a statement recently that I happen to agree with:\n<h3><strong><em>The world is drunk on comfort.</em></strong></h3>\nToday, in the United States, we prefer our heated car seats, heated floors in heated homes; and in the summer, air-conditioned cars, homes, and offices. In those rare moments when we are forced into contact with the natural elements, it “feels” <em>unbearable</em>. We have little tolerance for that. These days, we are simply not accustomed to discomfort.\n\nYet, for most of human history—and in many corners of the world today—discomfort was, and is, normal life. It’s assumed. An unavoidable reality. Because much of life <em>is</em> uncomfortable. We experience discomfort from toil, injury, accidents, and loss. Discomfort from illness, anxiety, anger, sadness, doubt, and shame. Discomfort has always been <em>expected</em>.\n\nBut not here, not today. Now we expect comfort, not the least of which is in our relationships. And when it doesn’t happen we complain.\n\nLoudly.\n\nIn court even.\n\nYet, in the midst of it all, we have this ancient institution, founded not upon <em>comfort</em> but upon <em>covenant</em>. An unyielding commitment through every <em>dis</em>comfort; a hallowed promise to abide, regardless. At its center, it is not a declaration of present love. It’s a promise of <em>future</em> love. It’s <em>not</em> a promise to <em>feel</em> warm and loving (as humans, we can’t promise this). Rather, it is a promise to <em>be</em> warm and loving and tender and faithful, regardless of the emotions, through thick and thin. It stubbornly insists love is not a <em>feeling</em>—rather, love is what gives us the strength to endure <em>all </em>feelings.\n\nHow did Paul put it?\n\n<em>“Love bears all things, believes all things, hopes all things, endures all things, love never fails.”</em>\n\nBut, wait! I know my limits! I’m only human. Where does this power come from—this ability to endure? Let’s take a brief look <strong><em>covenant</em></strong> and <strong><em>vows</em></strong>.\n\n<strong> </strong>In Ephesians 5, Paul describes the relationship between husbands and wives, and their direct correlation to Christ and the Church. Near the end, in verse 31, he pulls a word from Genesis 2:24, explaining how two become one. The man will, <em>“be united to his wife.”</em>\n\nThe word “united” (also translated “cleave”) means much more than a physical union. It’s a complete blending of two people into one. In the next verse, Paul calls this <em>“a profound mystery.”</em> The Greek word “<em>mystery</em>” is <em>mysterion</em> which means “<strong>oath,</strong>” a concept found throughout the entire Bible.\n\nCovenants are established by making an oath—an oath that creates kinship between two parties establishing a covenant. Covenant is the fundamental tool that God has designed to construct and order his relationship with man.\n<h3><strong>If you don\'t have an oath, you don\'t have a covenant.</strong></h3>\nWe see this remarkably in God’s covenant with Abraham, in Genesis 17. He speaks an <em>oath</em> to Abraham and his seed, as he establishes his <em>covenant</em> with them (and by extension, us).\n\nOnly in Christianity does God bind himself to man by swearing an oath. He willingly obligated himself to fulfill it regardless. And when we did not keep our part of the covenant, God kept his promise. The Groom remained unwaveringly faithful to his Bride. To do so, he became man and then became a curse, in our place, in order to make us his covenant family.\n\n<em>“God made Him who had no sin to be sin for us, so that in Him we might become the righteousness of God.” (</em>2 Corinthians 5:21.)\n\nCovenants, as opposed to a contract, are an exchange of persons. In establishing a covenant with God, faith in through his Son, Jesus, we make an oath, so to speak, as we declare our belief and pledge our lives to him. A covenant is established. Oneness with him.\n\nIn making this oath, as on our wedding day, we call upon the power of God—a mystery of calling upon the very presence of God, engaging him for help and power so that we can do what we are pledging to do.\n\n<strong>And so, as heaven looks on in reverent awe, the Father presides over their union, as a man and woman, hearts beating fast, step into covenant, each taking an oath, exchanging sacred vows:</strong>\n\nFor better or worse,\n\nfor richer, for poorer,\n\nin sickness and in health,\n\nto love and to cherish,\n\nfrom this day forward,\n\nuntil death do us part.','Are Marriage Vows Irrelevant?','','trash','closed','closed','','are-marriage-vows-irrelevant__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1127',0,'post','',0),(1132,41,'2015-05-11 12:50:54','2015-05-11 19:50:54','How does the Holy Spirit lead today?\r\n\r\nAnd not just today, but in our everyday. Day in, day out, does he guide us? And does he actually want to communicate with us? If so, how? This is something many of us who have followed Jesus for a while could answer, and probably flippantly, but these questions matter.\r\n\r\nIf the Holy Spirit has direction for your day, your work, your love-life, your friendships, your family, wouldn\'t you want to know?\r\n\r\nSo the question is, what does it look like to be led by God in the day to day?\r\n\r\nHere are 5 ways to better hear from the Spirit:\r\n<h3><strong>1. Become an apprentice of Jesus.</strong></h3>\r\nOften times following Jesus gets reduced to, “I believe in Jesus, I’m going to heaven when I die.” Or, “I believe in Jesus, I go to church every week.”\r\n\r\nAn apprentice learns a trade from a skilled employer. He imitates his master until he can perform like him. Going to Coava doesn’t make me a barista. I would need to be trained. I would need to learn from an experienced barista before I attempted my first latte art.\r\n\r\nJesus said, “everyone who hears the words of mine and puts them into practice is like a wise man who builds his house on a rock.” (Matt 7v24)\r\n\r\nWe must study scripture, learn from the life of Jesus, and put his teachings into practice in our own lives. How would Jesus live as a husband and father of three in Portland? How would Jesus live as a PSU student working part-time in a restaurant? Or as an employee at your company?\r\n\r\nLearn from Jesus.\r\n<h3><strong>2. Pursue holiness.</strong></h3>\r\nHearing from the Holy Spirit requires holiness.\r\n\r\nIs there static on the line? Is there anything hindering you from hearing the Holy Spirit?\r\n\r\nSin and addiction can hinder you from hearing from God. If you are stuck in any sin get help, confess your sins, get healing.\r\n\r\n“Let all bitterness and wrath and anger and clamor and slander be put away from you, along with all malice. Be kind to one another, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, as God in Christ forgave you.” (Eph 4v31-32)\r\n\r\nHave you been holding onto a grudge you know you need to let go of? Have you asked God to reveal your sin or are you afraid of what he will say?\r\n\r\nAre you living in an environment where God can speak? The music, the movies, the friends, or speech that you surround yourself with will effect you (Phil 4v8). Live a life that is “dedicated to him.”\r\n<h3><strong>3. Create space to listen.</strong></h3>\r\nDo you have regular time in your day to listen to God?\r\n\r\nIt is really easy to be distracted by our phones, twitter, instagram, and television. We are so constantly “plugged-in” that it has become uncomfortable to be a quiet room.\r\n\r\nFor many of us, we are afraid to listen to God for fear of what he will say. Often I am actually afraid, feeling condemned or guilty.\r\n\r\nBut God says, “approach with confidence!” The Father’s love is for you! God is for you.\r\n\r\nDraw close. Spend time. Go for a walk. Journal. Fast. Take off the headphones. Turn off the radio in the car.\r\n<h3><strong>4. Obey the little things you hear.</strong></h3>\r\nWhen the Holy Spirit speaks it is not always a life changing conversation.\r\n\r\nOften, God has small requests for our lives. If we want to create a strong connection with the voice of God, we must obey the little things we hear.\r\n\r\nPractice. Exercise produces results.\r\n\r\n“We ought not to be weary of doing little things for the love of God, who regards not the greatness of the work, but the love with which it is performed.” -Brother Lawrence\r\n\r\n“Faithful with the little, faithful with much.” (Luke 16v10)\r\n<h3><strong>5. Step out in faith.</strong></h3>\r\nWhen you hear the Spirit lead, follow. This may require risk at times. You may also have uncertainty of the results. But God has your best interest in mind. So take that step in faith.\r\n\r\nHow do I know if the Spirit is the one leading me?\r\n\r\nThe Holy Spirit’s voice will always align itself with scripture. As an apprentice of Jesus, you should be familiar with his teachings. So test what you have heard against scripture. The Holy Spirit will always be in agreement with the teachings of Jesus.\r\n\r\nConsider Wimber’s grid for knowing what is from God: He always wants us to share Jesus, pray for healing, and help the poor.\r\n\r\nThese five ways to better hear from the Spirit are an invitation, not obligation.\r\n\r\nWe get to hear the voice of God! There is more to life than living by your own plans. We get to hear God and be led by him.\r\n\r\nSo let’s not stop. Keep asking, praying, knocking. Keep pressing deeper. If God is showing you a new normal, don’t go back.\r\n\r\nAsk God to speak.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','5 Ways to Better Hear from the Spirit','','publish','closed','closed','','5-ways-to-better-hear-the-spirits-voice','','','2016-07-19 02:27:51','2016-07-19 10:27:51','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1132',0,'post','',0),(1137,8,'2015-04-14 13:16:47','2015-04-14 20:16:47','<strong>We all have questions.</strong>\n\nWhile some questions can be answered, others can’t — and still others are fuzzy at best.\n\nOne question that seems to comes up from time to time is, <strong>“Is one sin worse than another?”</strong>\n\nI think it\'s a valid question. One worth taking a few minutes to see what God says about it in the Scriptures.\n\nWhat\'s interesting to me is that when we step back and look at the question for what it is, we may find that we\'re unintentionally attempting to create <em>levels</em>.\n\nLet’s look at John 8v1—11:\n\n<em>Jesus went to the Mount of Olives. At dawn he appeared again in the temple courts, where all the people gathered around him, and he sat down to teach them. The teachers of the law and the Pharisees brought in a woman caught in adultery. They made her stand before the group and said to Jesus, “Teacher, this woman was caught in the act of adultery. In the Law Moses commanded us to stone such women. Now what do you say?” They were using this question as a trap, in order to have a basis for accusing him. But Jesus bent down and started to write on the ground with his finger. When they kept on questioning him, he straightened up and said to them, “Let any one of you who is without sin be the first to throw a stone at her.” Again he stooped down and wrote on the ground. At this, those who heard began to go away one at a time, the older ones first, until only Jesus was left, with the woman still standing there. Jesus straightened up and asked her, “Woman, where are they? Has no one condemned you?” “No one, sir,” she said. “Then neither do I condemn you,” Jesus declared, “Go now and leave your life of sin.”</em>\n\nThe guys in this story were clearly making their view point known on the topic by verbally identifying themselves as one’s who assumed their sin was less “bad” than this lady’s sin. Were they correct in thinking so?\n\nJesus seems to disagree, in-fact he identifies everyone there to be on the same <em>level</em>.\n\nWhoa.\n\nIt may be necessary to ask, “<em>Why</em> are we asking this question in the first place?” Is it possible that we’re asking it in hopes that we\'d <em>feel better about ourselves</em>? As if to say, “They’re worse than me, so that makes me a better person.” If so, that’s a <em>very</em> dangerous place to stand. Jesus makes <em>that</em> super clear. In doing so, the gift of grace, then righteousness (in effect, being right with God), is assumed to be derived <em>from me and others</em> rather than <em>from Jesus alone</em>.\n\nYou may be familiar with some of Jesus\' famous words in Matthew 5 — words like:\n\n<em>You have heard that it was said, \"You shall not commit adultery.\" But I tell you that anyone who looks at a woman lustfully has already committed adultery with her in his heart.</em>\n\nWhat\'s He saying?\n\nBasically, He says 1 = 1. Sin = Sin.\n\nNow of course, some sin, such as choosing to act on desires that are contrary to God’s best for us, have more consequence in the <em>immediate</em>. And there\'s definitely a ton more <em>effect</em>, if viewing from a moment in time looking forward, when <em>more</em> sin comes onto the scene in that moment. As an example, injustice is injustice. And greater injustice is greater injustice.\n\nI think we can all agree that <em>thinking</em> about wanting to slug someone in the face has less <strong>immediate</strong> consequence than <em>physically going through with the action</em>. But, ultimately every sin is \"less than the character of God” whether it\'s “little\" or “big.” In Colossians 1v13—14, Paul lays out that there are two kingdoms, the dominion of darkness and the Kingdom of God. Which is to say...<strong> there is no middle ground</strong>. Everything fits somewhere within. So off-ness from God is off-ness from God.\n\nLike a seed, a thought can grow into an action, which can turn into a habit, which can mature into an addiction. So, what we often do is try to define where each <em>sin</em> fits on the line.\n\n<strong>How we often think:</strong>\n\nThought (\"not that bad\") ------------ Action (\"really bad\")\n\nThinking within a framework of these kind of scales is extremely tricky. In-fact we often do so without even realizing it.\n\nBut to Jesus, all of humanity was far from God. Romans 3v23 says:\n\n<em>All have sinned and fall short of the glory of God...</em>\n\nWhich is to say we’re all in this together, every person on the planet at one time was lost; many still are. Now if you leave off there it makes for a pretty discouraging message, but the verse goes onto say:\n\n<em>...and all can be justified freely by his grace through the redemption that came by Christ Jesus.</em>\n\nSo there’s hope;<strong> there’s always hope in Jesus.</strong>\n\nIn the end, the issue isn’t “What sin is worse?”\n\nThat\'s not an issue for humanity to carry.\n\nWhat is in-fact ours to carry, is the question which leads to our response, “Am I right with/close to God through Jesus?”\n\n<strong>So, the short answer:</strong> All of humanity is <em>sinful</em> (far from God). But Jesus made a way for <em>humanity</em> to be made right with (or close to) Him again, no matter how \"big\" we consider our sin is.\n\n—\n\n<strong>As always, the goal isn\'t to know this stuff, but to live it.</strong>\n\nTake a minute to process through what all this means for your life today and tomorrow.\n\nIs there a grudge you\'re holding because of something someone did to you that you \"just can\'t forgive\"? Or do you find yourself judging people on the regular?\n\nIf the Spirit is speaking to you now, can I encourage you to take a deep breathe in and respond to Him?\n\nLife is messy, and this stuff can be really difficult; that\'s ok. We\'re all in this together; but never forget that God\'s way is always the best way.\n\nI hope this helps.','Is One Sin Worse Than Another?','','trash','closed','closed','','is-one-sin-worse-than-another__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1137',0,'post','',0),(1139,4,'2015-05-21 09:27:36','2015-05-21 17:27:36','','ajc_bt_web_vibe_1','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_web_vibe_1','','','2015-05-21 09:27:36','2015-05-21 17:27:36','',1104,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/05/ajc_bt_web_vibe_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1150,10,'2015-05-24 19:52:42','2015-05-25 03:52:42','','Living in the Tension Between Gratitude and Grief','','publish','closed','closed','','living-in-the-tension-between-gratitude-and-grief','','','2015-06-02 10:07:56','2015-06-02 18:07:56','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1150',65,'teaching','',0),(1155,10,'2015-05-31 21:02:21','2015-06-01 05:02:21','','The Model','','publish','closed','closed','','the-model','','','2015-06-02 10:07:31','2015-06-02 18:07:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1155',63,'teaching','',0),(1157,10,'2015-06-07 18:19:08','2015-06-08 02:19:08','','The Genius of an Autobiography','1 Thessalonians 2v1-16','publish','closed','closed','','the-genius-of-an-autobiography','','','2015-06-08 23:10:20','2015-06-09 07:10:20','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1157',64,'teaching','',0),(1160,25,'2015-04-16 11:08:17','2015-04-16 18:08:17','We live in a city populated with well-educated people who view existence through the lens of secular science and philosophy. In this way, culture tends to value intellectual thought and logic over faith.\r\n\r\nThe church used to be known as a hub for scholars and academics, learning about God through science and philosophy. However, in recent history, the church has gained a reputation of <em>solo fide,</em> or \"faith alone,\" in their understanding of the gospel. In response, culture now often dismisses the church as naive or ignorant. While faith is important to our relationship with God, we must also strive to know God with our minds. God wants us to love him not only with our hearts, souls, and strength, but with our minds as well.\r\n\r\nBridgetown wants to be a church that speaks with an educated voice. We want to be thoughtful and academic, challenging the traditional paradigm of Christian thought. The gospel is powerful and we want to use it accurately to communicate the message of Jesus.\r\n\r\nWe will now be regularly introducing recommended reading for you to follow along with. Our hope is that we would continually expand our minds and understanding of the Kingdom of God. This will allow us to become more effective in our mission to share the gospel in our city.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0802867618/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o08_s00?ie=UTF8&amp;psc=1 \" target=\"_blank\">How Not to be Secular</a>\r\nby James K. A. Smith[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Spirit-Disciplines-Understanding-Changes-Lives/dp/0060694424/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1423766824&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=the+spirit+of+the+disciplines\" target=\"_blank\">The Spirit of the Disciplines</a>\r\nby Dallas Willard[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0062334344/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o05_s00?ie=UTF8&amp;psc=1\" target=\"_blank\">Simply Good News</a>\r\nby NT Wright[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Kingdom-Conspiracy-Returning-Radical-Mission/dp/1587433605/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1423766991&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=kingdom+conspiracy\" target=\"_blank\">Kingdom Conspiracy</a>\r\nby Scot McNight[/page_actions]\r\n\r\nThese books are also available at the Bridgetown Book Store during the weekend gatherings.','Bridgetown Recommended Reading','','publish','closed','closed','','bridgetown-church-reading','','','2016-07-19 02:45:28','2016-07-19 10:45:28','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1160',0,'post','',0),(1174,4,'2015-06-14 12:35:50','2015-06-14 20:35:50','An opportunity to get away, relax, and enjoy great company. We will be tent camping with access to swimming pool and rec room. Activities will include hiking, surfing, fishing, and time to just hang out around the campfire in the evening.','Men\'s Cape Kiwanda Camping','','publish','closed','closed','','1434314150','','','2015-07-13 09:46:40','2015-07-13 17:46:40','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=event&#038;p=1174',0,'event','',0),(1176,10,'2015-06-14 17:59:22','2015-06-15 01:59:22','','The Parousia','1 Thessalonians 2v17 – 3v10 ','publish','closed','closed','','the-parousia','','','2015-08-18 12:45:19','2015-08-18 20:45:19','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1176',62,'teaching','',0),(1182,25,'2015-04-19 15:46:08','2015-04-19 22:46:08','When Bridgetown first began the tectonic shift from an <em>inward</em>-focused church to a collection of missional communities <em>outwardly</em> focused on the city of Portland, it was compelled by a relatively simple line of thinking: The end goal of God and his Kingdom is not the Church, but rather, <em>all</em> of Creation set free from the entropy of the Fall and brought under the healing reign of Jesus. The church is, of course, wrapped up in that pursuit, but what would it look like to <em>be</em> the church for the city in which we live, rather than calling our city into our church?\r\n\r\nBridgetown resolved, unapologetically, to be a collection of missional communities for the urban core of Portland, Oregon, but what we realized early on in that shift was that well-represented in our midst was a strong, faithful presence of missional communities doing life in Vancouver, Washington. A few years ago we began asking ourselves, \"what would it look like to plant a church in Vancouver?\"\r\n\r\nAfter several years of praying, searching, and planning, we are doing exactly that. We are planting a church in Vancouver, Washington.\r\n\r\nJosh &amp; Abi Porter will become our Vancouver Church Planters, leading the vision of the church. Josh is an accomplished musician and writer who has toured the world sharing the message of Jesus in unique ways. Abi is a successful lifestyle blogger who contributes to the Kingdom of God through creativity. They have been married for seven years and have a one-year-old son named Beck.\r\n\r\nOver the past few years, Josh and Abi have been dedicated servants within the Bridgetown Church family. Josh has worked on staff as the videographer and blog manager, occasionally teaching at Bridgetown weekend gatherings. Abi has served as a women\'s leader at events like Women\'s Night of Prayer. They are now embedded church planters working through the next steps of planting in Vancouver.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_image_261.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1248\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_image_261.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_image_26\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\r\n<h1>Contact</h1>\r\nIf you have any questions about the Vancouver Church Plant or would like to get involved, please contact Josh Porter.\r\n[page_actions][email address=josh.porter@ajesuschurch.org]Contact Josh Porter[/email][/page_actions]\r\n<h1>Vancouver Church Website</h1>\r\nFor all the information about the Vancouver Church Plant, including giving and a schedule for prayer meetings, visit their website.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/vancouver\">Vancouver Church Plant</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Vancouver Church Plant','','publish','closed','closed','','vancouver-church','','','2016-07-19 02:44:25','2016-07-19 10:44:25','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1182',0,'post','',0),(1189,10,'2015-06-21 18:26:52','2015-06-22 02:26:52','','Paul\'s Three Prayers','','publish','closed','closed','','pauls-three-prayers','','','2015-08-18 12:44:52','2015-08-18 20:44:52','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1189',61,'teaching','',0),(1191,4,'2015-06-24 15:23:14','2015-06-24 23:23:14','','IMG_0290','','inherit','open','open','','img_0290','','','2015-06-24 15:23:14','2015-06-24 23:23:14','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/06/IMG_0290.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1194,10,'2015-06-28 18:34:30','2015-06-29 02:34:30','','Let\'s Talk About Sex','','publish','closed','closed','','sanctification','