l sing together by candlelight and hear the story of Jesus followed by an identical gathering on Christmas Eve.\r\n\r\nChildcare only available on Christmas Sunday. Our regular gathering times will continue the following week.[one_third padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Christmas Sunday</h1>\r\n<strong>Date: </strong>Sun, Dec 20\r\n<strong>Time:</strong> 6 PM\r\n<strong>Doors:</strong> 5 PM\r\n<strong>Location: </strong>First Baptist Church\r\n909 SW 11th Ave. Portland, OR\r\n<strong>Childcare: </strong>Provided\r\n[/one_third][one_third_last]\r\n<h1>Christmas Eve</h1>\r\n<strong>Date: </strong>Thurs, Dec 24\r\n<strong>Time:</strong> 11 PM\r\n<strong>Doors:</strong> 10 PM\r\n<strong>Location: </strong>First Baptist Church\r\n909 SW 11th Ave. Portland, OR 97205\r\n<strong>Childcare: </strong>None\r\n\r\n[/one_third_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h1>Christmas Justice Initiative</h1>\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'https://player.vimeo.com/video/148129305\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\nEvery Christmas, we focus on a justice initiative to give back to people in need. <span style=\"color: #525252;\">The current refugee crisis has forced millions of people around the world to flee their homes, and the number grows daily. In partnership with Hear The Cry, we want to help refugees in Iraq, Somalia, and those arriving in Portland, restart their lives. Consider how you can help. </span>\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.hearthecry.org/projects/\" target=\"_blank\">Give to Refugee Care</a> [/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h1>Social Media</h1>\r\nSpread the word on social media. Invite your friends and family to gather with us as we celebrate the birth of Jesus. Click images to enlarge.\r\n\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_grey.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1438\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_grey.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_grey\" width=\"1920\" height=\"2400\" /></a>[/one_third]\r\n\r\n[one_third_last padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_red.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1439\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_red.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_red\" width=\"1920\" height=\"2400\" /></a>[/one_third_last]','Christmas','','publish','closed','closed','','christmas','','','2015-12-17 16:11:47','2015-12-18 00:11:47','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1413',0,'page','',0),(1427,4,'2015-11-18 15:34:40','2015-11-18 23:34:40','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_her','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_her','','','2015-11-18 15:34:40','2015-11-18 23:34:40','',1413,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_her.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1431,4,'2015-11-18 15:36:35','2015-11-18 23:36:35','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_hero','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_hero','','','2015-11-18 15:36:35','2015-11-18 23:36:35','',1413,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_hero.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1435,4,'2015-11-18 18:07:25','2015-11-19 02:07:25','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_hero','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_hero-2','','','2015-11-18 18:07:25','2015-11-19 02:07:25','',1413,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_hero1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1438,4,'2015-11-18 18:28:01','2015-11-19 02:28:01','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_grey','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_grey','','','2015-11-18 18:28:01','2015-11-19 02:28:01','',1413,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_grey.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1439,4,'2015-11-18 18:28:24','2015-11-19 02:28:24','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_red','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_red','','','2015-11-18 18:28:24','2015-11-19 02:28:24','',1413,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/11/ajc_bt_christmas_2015_insta_red.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1442,4,'2015-11-18 19:43:05','2015-11-19 03:43:05','Bridgetown Young Adults, travel this Spring with your church family to Haiti and provide for people in need. We want to see the Kingdom of God continue to break into this world as we pray for God\'s will to be done in Haiti as it is in Heaven.','Young Adult Haiti Mission Trip','','publish','closed','closed','','1447904585','','','2015-11-18 19:44:32','2015-11-19 03:44:32','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=event&#038;p=1442',0,'event','',0),(1444,10,'2015-11-22 21:25:42','2015-11-23 05:25:42','','Kavod','','publish','closed','closed','','kavod','','','2015-11-22 21:25:42','2015-11-23 05:25:42','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1444',35,'teaching','',0),(1456,10,'2015-11-29 21:12:19','2015-11-30 05:12:19','In a non-stop, 24/7 world of Wi-Fi and social media and VISA and travel and go-go-go, it’s easy to get sucked into the tyranny of the urgent and lose sight of our God given identity and calling. To live and work well, we need to learn the art of saying no.','Yes and No','','publish','closed','closed','','yes-and-no','','','2016-01-12 11:38:32','2016-01-12 19:38:32','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1456',34,'teaching','',0),(1459,22,'2015-06-03 17:21:25','2015-06-04 00:21:25','Imagine living in constant fear for your life, and for the lives of your family, that your only choice is to run.\r\n\r\nPortland is beautiful. People take such pride in living here. It is safe. It is unique.\r\n\r\nIt is home.\r\n\r\nNow imagine being forced to leave.\r\n\r\nThis is the harsh reality for millions of people all over the world. They have no choice but to courageously step into an uncertain future as they leave all that they know behind.\r\n\r\nRefugees are proven victims of persecution that flee their homes in search of safety.\r\n\r\nLong-term violence and other difficult living conditions brought on by conflict force them to leave their homes, their family, their friends, and all the belongings that can\'t be carried on their backs.\r\n\r\nThey have experienced trauma in war zones, undergone unimaginable persecution and tragedy, and know nothing but fear. Yet they cling to a distant hope where violence is replaced with peace.\r\n\r\nPortland is one of the top cities in the United States for receiving refugees.\r\n\r\nAbout one thousand refugees are placed here every year, with the majority coming from Iraq and Somalia. Due to this massive need in our city, refugee care has recently been added as a local initiative of <a href=\"http://hearthecry.org\" target=\"_blank\">Hear The Cry</a>.\r\n\r\nMost refugees arrive with next to nothing, knowing no one, and lacking cultural familiarity.\r\n\r\nUnderstandably, they\'re afraid and unsure of how to start their lives over.\r\n\r\nWhile they\'re provided with a small amount of funding for an apartment, food stamps, and other provisions, what they need most is the support of community. They need people willing to help them adapt to their new life, in a new city.\r\n\r\nConsider a family of eleven from the Central African Republic…\r\n\r\nViolence and unrest has led the family to a Chadian refugee camp. Four years pass when they finally receive the opportunity to come to the United States.\r\n\r\nTwo parents and nine kids board a plane for Portland, Oregon.\r\n\r\nFrom the plane window they get their first look at the new landscape they call home.\r\n\r\nThey are greeted by a small group of people carrying food, water, and hope.\r\n\r\nThe coming weeks are spent teaching the family how to use light switches, store food in a refrigerator, use running water, use kitchen appliances, and function on a daily basis with the amenities of American life.\r\n\r\nThe months and years that follow are filled with learning how to go grocery shopping, use public transportation, pay bills, speak English, and integrate into a new culture that is worlds away from familiarity.\r\n\r\nNow five years later, the family has adapted to life in the States. The parents have jobs and driver\'s licenses. The kids are receiving an education and planning for a bright future.\r\n\r\nOne boy plays basketball and wants to be an actor when he gets older.\r\n\r\nOne girl writes poems about Africa with a perspective that should be heard by the world.\r\n\r\nThe youngest two dream about becoming astronauts and the fastest runners in the world.\r\n\r\nBut most importantly, the family is safe.\r\n\r\nThey finally have the freedom and peace they have desired for so long. They know they are loved.\r\n\r\nAnd the people that helped them? They were able to make lasting friendships and step into a story greater than themselves.\r\n\r\nWith thousands of refugees living here and more arriving weekly, we have a unique opportunity to help them, honor them, restore their dignity, and love them well.\r\n\r\nYou can embody an extravagant type of love.\r\n\r\nImagine welcoming a family at the airport with signs and balloons, giving them a ride to their new home, and helping them in their first few crucial weeks.\r\n\r\nYou can offer a level of hospitality that will profoundly impact their new lives. \r\n\r\n<h2>Refugee Care Information Night</h2>\r\n<strong>Wed, June 10, 6:30 PM at Bridgetown, </strong><strong>909 SW 11th Ave. Portland, OR.</strong>\r\n\r\nThere are many ways to help, from donating furniture, to creating welcome boxes, or providing financially. Our vision is to see every refugee adapt to life here comfortably, experience God\'s love, and enter into the Kingdom of God.\r\n\r\nCome to the Refugee Care Information Night and learn how you can get involved with serving refugees in our city. If your missional community is looking for a mission, this is an incredible opportunity.\r\n\r\nWe pray that every refugee would be able to say, \"I was hungry and you gave me something to eat, I was thirsty and you gave me something to drink, I was a stranger and you welcomed me.” (Mathew 25v35)\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=megan@hearthecry.org]Contact for more information[/email][/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1461\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugee_2.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugee_2\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n<br />\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1462\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugee_3.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugee_3\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n<br />\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1463\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugee_4.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugee_4\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n<br />\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1464\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugee_5.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugee_5\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Refugees in Portland','','publish','closed','closed','','refugees-in-portland','','','2016-07-19 00:33:54','2016-07-19 08:33:54','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1459',0,'post','',0),(1468,37,'2016-06-09 10:39:43','2016-06-09 18:39:43','<h1><strong>The House of Learning</strong></h1>\nHouse of Learning equips followers of Jesus  to live life on mission, reach their communities, and to  better understand and interpret Scripture. Below is a selection of classes that we currently offer.\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://drive.google.com/folderview?id=0By45aTstha2JQnNZdE1KMHRZNTA&amp;usp=sharing\" target=\"_blank\">Bridgetown Class Files</a> [/page_actions]\n\n<hr />\n\n<h1>God &amp; Money</h1>\n[two_third padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]God &amp; Money is a two week biblically based financial class that teaches what God tells us about managing the blessings he gives us. During this class we will discuss the things of this world that distract and pull us away from God’s plan. We will describe God’s attitude towards providing for our needs and the abundance that we see when we follow his guidance. The goal of this class is to examine God’s plan and work together to apply this to our everyday lives in a way that affects every aspect of your Christian walk.[/two_third]\n\n[one_third_last]\nNew dates for this class coming soon.[/one_third_last]\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetownajc.org\">Class is Full</a>[/page_actions]\n\n<hr />\n\n<h1><strong>Emotionally Healthy Church</strong></h1>\n[two_third padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]In the church, as a general rule, we often teach people how to read the Scriptures, how to pray, how to repent of sin, have faith, do justice, preach the gospel, etc. But we don’t teach people how to navigate emotional pain. How to feel, and to feel well. Over the course of six weeks, the Emotionally Healthy Church class is designed to provide participants with steps to help reshape themselves from the inside out.[/two_third]\n\n[one_third_last]\n<strong>Date:</strong> Sundays, Oct 18 – Nov 22\n<strong>Time:</strong> 2:30 - 4 PM\n<strong>Location:</strong> First Baptist Church, Downstairs\n<strong>Cost:</strong> No Cost[/one_third_last]\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://ajesuschurchfamily.webconnex.com/bridgetown_houseoflearning\">Register for Classes</a>[/page_actions]\n\n<hr />\n\n<h1><strong>Problem of Evil</strong></h1>\n[two_third padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]The Problem of Evil is a four week class crafted to provide students with a biblical framework for understanding suffering, tragedy, and injustice. Along the way we will examine various theological understandings of the problem of evil as well as how these views have been applied throughout church history. Finally, we will discuss pragmatic ways to understand, process, discuss, and experience the problem of evil in our own lives, and in the lives of those around us.[/two_third]\n\n[one_third_last]\n<strong>Date:</strong> Sundays, Nov 1 – Nov 22\n<strong>Time:</strong> 2 - 4 PM\n<strong>Location:</strong> First Baptist Church, Chapel\n<strong>Instructor:</strong> Josh Porter\n<strong>Cost:</strong> No Cost[/one_third_last]\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://ajesuschurchfamily.webconnex.com/bridgetown_houseoflearning\">Register for Classes</a>[/page_actions]','House of Learning','','inherit','open','open','','35-autosave-v1','','','2016-06-09 10:39:43','2016-06-09 18:39:43','',35,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/35-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1473,10,'2015-12-06 21:35:34','2015-12-07 05:35:34','If we embrace this vision of work, the odds are we will make money. How do we keep from getting sucked into the vortex of work more, buy more, repeat? Through simplicity, generosity, and Spirituality.','Jesus and The Paycheck','','publish','closed','closed','','jesus-and-the-paycheck','','','2016-01-12 11:38:09','2016-01-12 19:38:09','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1473',33,'teaching','',0),(1475,4,'2015-12-07 12:08:19','2015-12-07 20:08:19','The current refugee crisis has forced millions of people around the world to flee their homes, and the number grows daily. In partnership with Hear The Cry, we want to help refugees in Iraq, Somalia, and those arriving in Portland, restart their lives. Consider how you can help. ','Christmas Justice Initiative','','publish','closed','closed','','1449518899','','','2015-12-07 12:09:25','2015-12-07 20:09:25','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=event&#038;p=1475',0,'event','',0),(1480,4,'2015-12-13 17:03:29','2015-12-14 01:03:29','Follow along with our five week Curriculum on how to Sabbath.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/sabbath.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Sabbath Curriculum</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\nAnother great teaching on Sabbath from Bridgetown Church includes \"Sabbath\" from <em>The Emotionally Healthy Church</em> teaching series. Listen along as we learn to make time for rest, health, and worship.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/teaching/the-emotionally-healthy-church/sabbath/\">Other Sabbath Teaching</a> [/page_actions]','Sabbath As Resistance','','publish','closed','closed','','sabbath-as-resistance','','','2015-12-16 17:12:14','2015-12-17 01:12:14','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1480',32,'teaching','',0),(1482,4,'2015-12-13 17:04:44','2015-12-14 01:04:44','','Sabbath','','publish','closed','closed','','sabbath','','','2015-12-13 17:04:44','2015-12-14 01:04:44','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1482',0,'page','',0),(1485,4,'2015-12-13 17:19:53','2015-12-14 01:19:53','','sabbath','','inherit','open','open','','sabbath-2','','','2015-12-13 17:19:53','2015-12-14 01:19:53','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/sabbath.pdf',0,'attachment','application/pdf',0),(1486,4,'2015-12-14 12:33:13','2015-12-14 20:33:13','','ajc_bt_web_sabbath_','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_web_sabbath_','','','2015-12-14 12:33:13','2015-12-14 20:33:13','',1480,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_web_sabbath_.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1487,4,'2015-12-14 15:54:55','2015-12-14 23:54:55','<h1>Alpha Course</h1>\r\nBridgetown Church is hosting Alpha, an open and informal dialogue about existence, the person of Jesus, and what it all means. We want to hear your thoughts and questions as we explore these themes together without the pressured atmosphere that usually comes with these conversations.\r\n\r\nAlpha is an opportunity to explore life and the Christian faith in a friendly, open, and informal environment. Each week, after a meal together, we will have a short talk and discussion groups in which you can share your thoughts and ask questions.\r\n\r\nFor more information about Alpha, please contact us.\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=bridgetown@ajesuschurch.org]Contact for More Information [/email][/page_actions]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_third]\r\n<h4>Next Alpha Course</h4>\r\nEach week we have a dinner, a short talk, and a discussion where you can share your thoughts.\r\n<strong>Date:</strong> Wednesday, Jan 13 – Mar 16\r\n<strong>Time:</strong> 6:30 – 8 PM\r\n<strong>Location:</strong> Bridgetown Office 1306 NW Hoyt St #412[/one_third]','Alpha','','publish','closed','closed','','alpha','','','2015-12-16 11:30:04','2015-12-16 19:30:04','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1487',0,'page','',0),(1488,4,'2015-12-14 15:53:26','2015-12-14 23:53:26','','20140210_1283_PS','','inherit','open','open','','20140210_1283_ps','','','2015-12-14 15:53:26','2015-12-14 23:53:26','',1487,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/20140210_1283_PS.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1489,4,'2015-12-14 15:54:09','2015-12-14 23:54:09','','20140210_1283_PS','','inherit','open','open','','20140210_1283_ps-2','','','2015-12-14 15:54:09','2015-12-14 23:54:09','',1487,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/20140210_1283_PS1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1505,4,'2015-12-15 13:07:07','2015-12-15 21:07:07','<h1>Year of Biblical Literacy</h1>\r\nTruly knowing your Bible through the practice of reading has become a lost art, and it seems we are becoming illiterate toward the narrative of God. In 2016, participate with us in the \"Year of Biblical Literacy.\" Follow the Bible Reading Plan and work through the entire biblical narrative one day at a time. Along the way, there will be short animated videos to help you understand the structure and themes of the Bible. The Year of Biblical Literacy is a collaborative effort between <a href=\"https://jointhebibleproject.com/#\">The Bible Project</a>, <a href=\"http://www.realitysf.com/\">Reality SF</a>, and Bridgetown Church to teach a new generation to know and love the Scriptures. It is made of four parts: reading the bible, watching videos, listening to teachings and lectures, and talking with community.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_half padding=\"0 25px 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Read</h1>\r\nThe Bible Reading plan is about learning the Scriptures through a daily commitment to opening your heart and mind to God. This is a discipline essential to all disciples of Jesus. The Bible Project has created a unique and powerful experience, called Read Scripture, to help us engage with the text throughout the year.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bible/read/\">Bible Reading Plan</a>[/page_actions]\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last padding=\"0 0 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Watch</h1>\r\nThe Bible is a very profound and prophetic book that is telling one complete story from beginning to end. It is also a very long book, which can make it confusing and intimidating. The Bible Project is all about exploring the entire biblical narrative by breaking it up into short animated videos that help you understand the structure and themes of the Bible.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bible/watch/\">Bible Videos</a>[/page_actions][/one_half_last][one_half padding=\"0 25px 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Listen</h1>\r\nAs a church, we will also be working through a series of teachings and lectures. These teachings will focus on the meta-narrative of scripture including Jesus, the authority of the Bible, the story of Israel, the prophets, the Kingdom of God, and the mission of the Church.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bible/listen/\">Teachings &amp; Lectures</a>[/page_actions]\r\n[/one_half][one_half_last padding=\"0 0 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Talk</h1>\r\nAlong the way, we encourage everybody to discuss Biblical Literacy with their communities. Jesus and his disciples learned together in community and we want to do the same. We have compiled some questions to help guide you together through the year of studying.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bible/talk/\">Discussion Questions</a>[/page_actions]\r\n[/one_half_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 25px 0 0\"]\r\n<h1>Midweek Lectures</h1>\r\n<h5 class=\"name\" style=\"color: #030303;\">Midweek Lecture: The Church and Popular Culture</h5>\r\nWhy does the Western church look so much like the world? Cultural relevance is important to the church but it can’t lose its identity. Mark Sayers will discuss the historical witness of the church and how we can continue that same countercultural impact today.\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Dates: </strong>May 23\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Time: </strong>6:30 – 8:30 PM\r\n<strong style=\"color: #030303;\">Location: </strong>First Baptist Church\r\n[/one_third][one_third_last]\r\n\r\n[/one_third_last]\r\n<p class=\"desc\" style=\"color: #525252;\"></p>','Year of Biblical Literacy','','publish','closed','closed','','bible','','','2016-05-02 10:06:50','2016-05-02 18:06:50','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1505',0,'page','',0),(1509,4,'2015-12-15 13:15:08','2015-12-15 21:15:08','<h1>Bible Reading Plan</h1>\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'https://www.youtube.com/embed//7hUs4TXRuVk\' frameborder=\'0\' allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\r\nThe Bible Reading plan is about learning the Scriptures through a daily commitment to opening your heart and mind to God. This is a discipline essential to all disciples of Jesus. <a href=\"https://jointhebibleproject.com/\" target=\"_blank\">The Bible Project</a> has created a unique and powerful experience, called Read Scripture, to help us engage with the text throughout the year.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/yobl_bible_reading_plan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Bible Reading Plan (Digital)</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2016/01/TBP_ReadingPlan.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Bible Reading Plan (Print)</a>[/page_actions]','Read','','publish','closed','closed','','read','','','2016-02-16 10:09:18','2016-02-16 18:09:18','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1509',0,'page','',0),(1511,4,'2015-12-15 13:17:25','2015-12-15 21:17:25','<h1>Bible Videos</h1>\r\n<span style=\"color: #525252;\">The Bible is a very profound and prophetic book that is telling one complete story from beginning to end. It is also a very long book, which can make it confusing and intimidating. The Bible Project is all about exploring the entire biblical narrative by breaking it up into short animated videos that help you understand the structure and themes of the Bible.</span>\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'https://www.youtube.com/embed//8Tbcofs6l3o\' frameborder=\'0\' allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://jointhebibleproject.com/?\" target=\"_blank\">More about \"The Bible Project\"</a>[/page_actions]','Watch','','publish','closed','closed','','watch','','','2016-01-01 08:53:28','2016-01-01 16:53:28','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1511',0,'page','',0),(1512,20,'2015-07-27 15:38:27','2015-07-27 22:38:27','&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLast year, Dustin and his wife Michelle found out they were pregnant—again.\r\n\r\nWith a four-month old child and now another on the way, they had the thought that many young couples do: Should we move near our family? They wanted to raise their children within a community that could help and support them as parents, and both of their families lived in southern California. “It just made sense,” Dustin says.\r\n\r\nThe decision wasn’t easy.\r\n\r\nDustin and Michelle had found a second family in their missional community, which had managed to build a foundation for the strange and wonderful vision that assembled the crew in the first place: turning a bunch of strangers into a tight family that actually shared everyday life together.\r\n\r\nThey shared countless meals, watched each other get married, got houses in the same neighborhood, and served their neighbors together.\r\n\r\nSo in June 2014, when they decided to relocate, their community showed up to help them move too.\r\n\r\nIn southern California, they settled into the house they bought. This was a new chapter. They unpacked their boxes and decorated the rooms. They were now just a car ride away from their families. Yet even with its glorious sunshine and proximity to family, California was lacking something vital. Dustin and Michelle missed their community. “It was really hard to find a church that embraced what community living is like,” Dustin says. “I think a lot of the American church is still catching up to that.”\r\n\r\nIt wasn’t just any kind of community that they missed, but their community.\r\n\r\n“Within a few months, my wife and I realized that we needed to move back,” Dustin says. They thought about the way they wanted to raise their kids, and they knew they wanted to do it in the midst of the thriving family of friends and neighbors who had already become closer than most relatives. These people knew each other. They had become uniquely involved in each other’s lives. They just hadn’t realized how powerful the bond was until they left.\r\n\r\nSo they put their house on the market, sold it a month later, and moved back to their old neighborhood in Beaverton, just a half mile from where they used to live. “We hit the ground right where we left off,” Dustin says. “It’s been a wild ride but were so glad we’re back.”\r\n\r\nAfter returning to Oregon, the very next week was dedicated to family night where Dustin’s missional community does an event called “Shake the Block.” This night involves opening up the garage and serving milkshakes for neighbors in the Bethany area. They play a movie for the kids and free up the adults for a little while. In the midst of these nights, they have been praying for Jesus to open the door for amazing conversation. Jesus says to “love thy neighbor,” so why not just start there, and with milkshakes?\r\n\r\n“It takes time,” Dustin says. “If you can have missional community in a setting where you’re completely honest and open and vulnerable, it opens the dialogue for the Holy Spirit to do some amazing things. You become family. You’re not blood, but you’re family.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','When Friends Become Family','','publish','closed','closed','','when-friends-become-family','','','2016-07-19 00:26:20','2016-07-19 08:26:20','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1512',0,'post','',0),(1513,4,'2015-12-15 13:18:29','2015-12-15 21:18:29','<h1>Teachings &amp; Lectures</h1>\r\nAs a church, we will also be working through a series of teachings and lectures. These teachings will focus on the meta-narrative of scripture including Jesus, the authority of the Bible, the story of Israel, the prophets, the Kingdom of God, and the mission of the Church.\r\n\r\nThe Midweek Lectures will be our opportunity to explore the difficult areas of the Bible that are confusing or challenging. We want to create a space to thoroughly discuss the Scripture and ask questions.','Listen','','publish','closed','closed','','listen','','','2016-01-14 17:35:20','2016-01-15 01:35:20','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1513',0,'page','',0),(1515,4,'2015-12-15 13:20:22','2015-12-15 21:20:22','<h1>Discussion Questions</h1>\r\nWe encourage everybody to discuss Biblical Literacy with their communities. Jesus and his disciples learned together in community and we want to do the same. We have compiled some questions to help guide you through the year of studying as you learn and grow together.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Jun 26 – Jul 2</h7>\r\nJeremiah 37 – Lam 3\r\nPsalm 23 – 29\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nHow does walking through the details of Israel’s exile and trying to wrap your mind around the felt experience help shine new light on what you’ve been reading?\r\n\r\nHave someone read Psalm 137, a psalm written in exile, aloud. How does a sufficient understanding of the sheer agony of exile help you understand and even empathize with the brutally honest prayers of this psalm?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Jun 19 – 25</h7>\r\nJeremiah 10 – 36\r\nPsalm 16 – 22\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nIs there any way in which your faith imitates the faith of those whom Jeremiah was challenging at the temple?\r\n\r\nIs there any hypocrisy in your faith/religion that warrants rebuke?\r\n\r\nThroughout the book of Jeremiah, the prophet explains that Israel and Judah have been punished for three interconnected reasons: 1) Committing idolatry; 2) Breaking the terms of the covenant; and 3) Doing evil and injustice rather than righteousness and justice. Jeremiah summarizes the foolishness of the people by saying, “They do not know the way of the Lord, the requirements of their God” (Jeremiah 5:4). In what way do the harsh and challenging words of Jeremiah offer you an invitation to reassess what it is that God requires of you?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Jun 12 – 18</h7>\r\nEcclesiastes 5 – Song of Songs 8\r\nJeremiah 1 – 9\r\nPsalm 9 – 15\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nEcclesiastes, and especially the beautiful poem about dying in chapter 12, invite readers to reflect on the seeming futility of life and inevitability of death. How might thinking about these things invite us into interaction and dialogue with God?\r\n\r\nWhen you read Ecclesiastes, do you find its nihilism depressing, strangely comforting, or both?\r\n\r\nHow might “meaningless, meaningless” coexist with the rest of the story of Scripture, which says our lives are deeply meaningful to God? How have you seen this tension lived out as you reflect on your own life?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Jun 5 – 11</h7>\r\nProverbs 13 – Ecclesiastes 4 \r\nPsalm 2 – 8\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nHow can Jesus’ life and teachings help show us the connection between faithfulness to God and wisdom for living well?\r\n\r\nAre there any gospel stories, parables, or attributes of Jesus that reveal both His faithful reverence for God and His incredible wisdom?\r\n\r\nThe Book of Proverbs is basically Israel’s collection of wisdom sayings that takes the form of advice that a father would give to his son. Consider advice for a moment. What kind of advice do you tend to take in, where do you consume advice, and how much of it do you consume?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>May 29 – Jun 4</h7>\r\nJob 38 – Psalm 2\r\nProverbs 1 – 12\r\nPsalm 145 – 150 & 1\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nCan we love God for God, and not for all his blessings? What about when the blessings go away?\r\n\r\nDoes the story of Job bring comfort and relief?\r\n\r\nHave you ever voiced your anger, pain or doubt to God in times of deep suffering in your life? If yes, what was God’s response to you? If you have not, what would it have been like to direct your anguish to God?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>May 22 – 28</h7>\r\nJob 12 – 37\r\nPsalm 138 – 144\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nHow do you think Job must have been feeling?\r\n\r\nWhat does the book of Job tell us about God?\r\n\r\nWhat does the book of Job tell us about Satan?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>May 15 – 21</h7>\r\nMicah 5 – Zephaniah 3\r\nJob 1 – 11\r\nPsalm 131 – 137\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nThinking back to how most prophets in the Old Testament are portrayed, why is Jonah’s immediate disobedience in v1­-3 so surprising? 	\r\n\r\nHow is Jonah’s character consistent with the character of Israel and its leaders/people throughout the Old Testament? 		\r\n\r\nLike Jonah, are there people or people groups you feel do not deserve God’s grace, mercy, and love? Why do you feel they don’t deserve it?	\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>May 8 – 14</h7>\r\nHosea 11 – Micah 4\r\nPsalm 124 – 130\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nRead Hosea 11:1-12. What does this chapter show you about the fatherly heart of God over Israel?\r\n\r\nWhat is it like for you to engage with such an emotional God as depicted in Hosea? Does it bother you or comfort you to consider God experiencing heartache, jealousy, and humiliation? \r\n\r\nDo you typically interact with God on such emotional terms, or do you find that your relationship tends to assume a pattern where you and/or God are simply calm, cool, and collected?\r\n\r\nHosea married a promiscuous woman not merely as a symbol for what Israel was to God — unfaithful to their covenant — but to actually experience what this felt like for God. Have you ever had an experience where you felt God’s disturbed yet gracious heart toward you and your people? How did you feel in that moment, and what did it bring up in you?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>May 1 – 7</h7>\r\nIsaiah 52 – 66\r\nHosea 1 – 10\r\nPsalm 119v97 – 123\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nMuch of Isaiah speaks about the nature of being the “servant of the Lord,” typically referring to Israel’s identity and vocation, as well as a “suffering servant.” Consider Israel’s calling to help God redeem the broken world through living as a holy priesthood and leading the nations to God. How do you think the experience of suffering in exile helped shape this understanding of a suffering servant (Isaiah 52-53)?\r\n\r\nHow do you think Jesus’ understanding of Israel’s identity and His own unique vocation as the true Israel and Israel’s true king was shaped by these texts in Isaiah?\r\n\r\nAn ancient Israelite like Isaiah felt a kind of guilt on behalf of his sinful community and expected the entire nation, himself included, to suffer the consequences unless the nation as a whole repented. Have you ever felt like you’ve suffered the consequences of your community’s sin? How did this make you feel?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Apr 24 – 30</h7>\r\nIsaiah 28 – 51\r\nPsalm 115 – 119v96\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nHow can Israel’s history and the prophets teach us to think about and respond to evil and injustice in our society or community that we haven’t personally committed but have potentially benefitted from? In other words, what should we do with sin that we haven’t overtly committed, but that we are complicit to just by the nature of the community to which we belong?\r\n\r\nHow does it make you feel to think about owning your community’s sin? Are you able to embrace this idea, or do you feel resistant to it?\r\n\r\nWhere does your mind immediately go when you think of your community’s sin? Your family, your city, your nation, company, community group, subculture?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Apr 17 – 23</h7>\r\n2  Kings 23 \r\nIsaiah 1 – 27\r\nPsalm 108 – 114\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nReflect back on your readings in 1 and 2 Kings. What stood out to you most from story after story of kings “doing what was evil in the eyes of the Lord”?\r\n\r\nAs you read through the stories, did you find yourself hoping for God to bring judgment upon Israel and punish them for their sins, or for God to continue to show them patience and mercy?\r\n\r\nHow would it have felt, emotionally and physically, to have been a Jew living in Jerusalem during this exile?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Apr 10 – 16</h7>\r\n2 Kings 1 – 22\r\nPsalm 101 – 107\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nRead 1 Kings 10:14-29. Considering Moses’ warning in Deuteronomy 8 and Samuel’s warning in 1 Samuel 8, what kind of attitude should we have toward this new era of “progress” and prosperity established under Solomon?\r\n\r\nShould we celebrate this prosperity as the blessing of God or be concerned that it is the result of a new kind of Jewish pharaoh figure? \r\n\r\nIf you put yourselves in the shoes of an ancient Jew, who would you prefer as your king: David or Solomon? Would you want the prayerful musician-king who humiliates himself by worshiping God in his underwear, or the kind of global political and economic powerhouse who establishes you and your people above the other nations and exacts from them such wealth that “silver becomes like just another stone,” no matter what the cost?\r\n\r\nReflect on the parts of your life where you are currently experiencing prosperity. Ask the Holy Spirit to give you brutal honesty and clarity as to the nature of your prosperity. Do you think you have gained prosperity because you and your part of society have faithfully followed the commands of God to live humbly, justly, mercifully, and lovingly?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Apr 3 – 9</h7>\r\n1 Kings 1 – 22\r\nPsalm 94 – 100\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nReflect back on your readings in 1 & 2 Samuel. What kind of actions and choices justified the Scriptures’ assessment of David as a righteous man and leader?\r\n\r\nThink about the fact that Israel’s most exalted king, whose life is given more detailed attention than any other Old Testament character, is also the person who created about half of the Psalms (such as the praise song of Psalm 18). What connection can you make between the internal character and heart expressed in the prayers of the Psalms and the external character and heart illustrated in David’s life and actions? \r\n\r\nHow do you relate to this idea of being sinful but ever in pursuit of holiness?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Mar 27 – Apr 2</h7>\r\n2 Samuel 1 – 24\r\nPsalm 87 – 93\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nOne of the hermeneutic guidelines for reading Biblical narrative is to pay attention to the pace of the story, especially noticing when it slows down dramatically to zoom in on a particular time or event. Typically, this indicates a particularly important chapter of the story. Why do you think the narrative slows down so much in Ruth & 1 Samuel after racing through hundreds of years of history in Judges?\r\n\r\nRead Deuteronomy 17:14-20 again. What kind of king is Israel supposed to have? Do you think Samuel embodies well the type of king Deuteronomy 17 describes?\r\n\r\nGod calls us, like Israel, to live differently (or as holy) from the world and the culture around us. With this in mind, in what ways can you identify with Israel’s rebellious desire to instead follow the ways of the world?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Mar 20 – 26</h7>\r\n1 Samuel 9 – 31\r\nPsalm 80 – 86\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nIn Ruth, we see that God cares for us deeply. How is God involved in the day-to-day joys and hardships of your life? \r\n\r\nRuth tells the story of a family this is hurting and broken, but in their faithfulness to God they are restored and made whole. Have you experienced similar restoration through God?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Mar 13 – 19</h7>\r\nJudges 9 – 1 Samuel 8\r\nPsalm 73 – 79\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nAs you read the book of Judges, what do you think the author’s intent was in chronicling this era of Israel’s history the way that he did?\r\n\r\nWere there any parts of Judges 19 that shocked, provoked, surprised, confused, disturbed, or confronted you?\r\n\r\nWhy do you think the author of Judges includes this violent, horrific story? What point might the author of Judges be trying to get across to his/her readers?\r\n\r\nIs it disorienting to read such a gruesome and awful story in the Bible? What questions does it bring up in you about God, Israel, human nature, or the Scriptures?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Mar 6 – 12</h7>\r\nJoshua 5 – Judges 8\r\nPsalm 66 – 72\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nAt this point in the reading, you have completed the Torah (Gen – Deu). What were the major themes, ideas, emotions, or experiences you remember from reading the Torah?\r\n\r\nHave someone recap the book of Joshua. What has happened so far and what are the main events and themes of the book?\r\n\r\nIsrael was called to obey God’s commands so that the other nations could see what God is like. In what ways can you, as a community, display the character of Jesus to people around you?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Feb 28 – Mar 5</h7>\r\nDeu 17 – Joshua 4\r\nPsalm 59 – 65\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nThe people of God were led out of the wilderness and into the promised land. Can you recognize a time in your life where God has led you out of a figurative “wilderness” and into the “promised land?”\r\n\r\nDeuteronomy is Moses recapping the past 40 years since the Exodus to the now grown up children of Israel. Imagine you are listening to Moses give this final address. All you have known is life wandering in the wilderness. You have heard stories from your parents of what God has done for your people, you have heard the Law. What is Moses trying to remind you and the rest of Israel of?\r\n\r\nGod protected and blessed the Israelites even when they were in rebellion. Looking back, when was there a time when you were not following God yet he continued to bless you?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Feb 21 – 27</h7>\r\nNumbers 35 – Deu 16\r\nPsalm 52 – 58\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nHow would you summarize Numbers in a sentence or two?\r\n\r\nIs there any part of the blessings that God gives Israel through Balaam that you find particularly beautiful, rich, or interesting?\r\n\r\n“Love the LORD your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your strength.” –Deu 6v5. Take a moment to meditate on this scripture and express your love to God in prayer together.\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Feb 14 – 20</h7>\r\nNumbers 17 – 34\r\nPsalm 45 – 51\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nIn Numbers, God’s holy presence is their leader and guide as they travel through the desert. As followers of Jesus, how have you allowed the Spirit to lead you this week?\r\n\r\nWhen the spies saw the Promised Land they feared for their lives and wanted to return to captivity in Egypt. How can fear tempt us to return to what God has saved us from?\r\n\r\nWhile God remains faithful to his people and his promises he will honor your choices and let you live in rebellion if you choose it. Take a moment in listening prayer to ask to God how you may be misaligned with the way of Jesus. \r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Feb 7 – 13</h7>\r\nLeviticus 24 – Numbers 16\r\nPsalm 38 – 44\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nCan anyone offer a one-sentence summary of Leviticus? To help you answering, think about: “If the author of Leviticus wanted his hearers to come away with one thing, what would it be? Why did he work so hard to keep and record and pass along this text?”\r\n\r\nIf you try to imagine being a part of Israel at this time, how would you have responded to some of these commands? Do you think you would have obeyed? Would you have loved them or hated them?\r\n\r\nA number of the Israelite’s rebellions were born from their lack of trust in God. Can you relate to their experience? How has your trust in God been challenged? \r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>Jan 31 – Feb 6</h7>\r\nLeviticus 5 – 23\r\nPsalm 31 – 37\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nWhat parts of the story simply don’t make sense or have been frustrating to read? (Note: In discussing these together, try to balance helping each other wrestle with difficult texts along with becoming comfortable with discomfort and imperfect understanding. It’s okay and even necessary to admit when we don’t grasp a part of the Scriptures and to not get too hung up. Keep reading.)\r\n\r\nJust as the animals sacrificed in Leviticus, Jesus is our “sacrificial lamb” that takes away our sin, making us holy. What practical steps can we take to remain holy?\r\n\r\nIn Leviticus, the people of God used ritual sacrifices to essentially say, “Thank you” and “I’m sorry.” How can we express these same sentiments in our relationship with God?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>January 24 – 30</h7>\r\nExodus 22 – Leviticus 4\r\nPsalm 24 – 30\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nThe people of God have a terrible pattern of sin and self-destruction. In what ways can you identify with this pattern in your life?\r\n\r\nUnlike the people of God in Exodus, we now have direct access to the presence of God because of the work of Jesus on the cross. In what ways can we help each other to embrace this new reality?\r\n\r\nGod continues to be faithful to his promise to Abraham (Gen 12v1-2) and make the people of God a blessing to the nations. In what ways can we be a blessing to our city and the nations?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>January 17 – 23</h7>\r\nExodus 1 – 21\r\nPsalm 17 – 23\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nMoses, a man who seems to have trouble with anger and doubt, is called by God to be the deliverer of Israel. In what ways do you relate as an imperfect person who is called by God?\r\n\r\nAt this point in the story, Israel is enslaved and God appears to be absent. When have you felt disappointed with life and God’s role in it and felt frustrated or hurt by his absence?\r\n\r\nJust as God freed his people from slavery in Egypt, Jesus has set you free. In what ways have you experienced this freedom?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>January 10 – 16</h7>\r\nGenesis 32 – 50\r\nPsalm 10 – 16\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nWhat parts of the story simply don’t make sense or have been frustrating to read? (Note: In discussing these together, try to balance helping each other wrestle with difficult texts along with becoming comfortable with discomfort and imperfect understanding. It’s okay and even necessary to admit when we don’t grasp a part of the Scriptures and to not get too hung up. Keep reading.)\r\n\r\nGenesis begins with the people of God living with him in the garden, but ends with the death of Joseph and the people of God facing slavery in Egypt. What do you think you, as a reader, are meant to be feeling?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\r\n\r\n<h7>January 3 – 9</h7>\r\nGenesis 1 – 31\r\nPsalm 1 – 6\r\n\r\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\r\n\r\nIn Genesis 1 – 2, what struck you as significant about God’s original intention for humankind and creation?\r\n\r\nIn Genesis 3 – 11, in what ways do you identify with the continual failures of humankind’s ability to live up to God’s original plan?\r\n\r\nTo Abraham, God made an unconditional promise to make the world right and good again. What hope does this promise to Abraham give for you and your community?\r\n\r\n[/three_fourth_last]','Talk','','publish','closed','closed','','talk','','','2016-06-29 08:57:20','2016-06-29 16:57:20','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=1515',0,'page','',0),(1517,4,'2015-12-15 13:25:31','2015-12-15 21:25:31','','Discussion Questions','','publish','open','open','','1517','','','2015-12-30 16:10:58','2015-12-31 00:10:58','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1517',4,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1518,4,'2015-12-15 13:25:31','2015-12-15 21:25:31','','Teachings & Lectures','','publish','open','open','','1518','','','2015-12-30 16:10:58','2015-12-31 00:10:58','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1518',3,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1519,4,'2015-12-15 13:25:31','2015-12-15 21:25:31','','Bible Videos','','publish','open','open','','1519','','','2015-12-30 16:10:58','2015-12-31 00:10:58','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1519',2,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1520,4,'2015-12-15 13:25:31','2015-12-15 21:25:31','','Bible Reading Plan','','publish','open','open','','1520','','','2015-12-30 16:10:58','2015-12-31 00:10:58','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1520',1,'nav_menu_item','',0),(1540,27,'2015-08-05 09:24:11','2015-08-05 16:24:11','I want to be known as a holy and blameless son; one who loves because he knows he is loved.\r\n\r\nI want to live within the tension of the now and not yet of the Kingdom of God, saturated with an indescribable and unquenchable hope.\r\n\r\nI want my whole life to look as it does during a seven-day trip to La Villa Esperanza in Managua, Nicaragua.\r\n\r\nSeven years ago I traveled to Nicaragua. I headed to La Villa Epseranza, a home for at-risk girls. Myself, a single dude with 2 brothers, no girlfriends, and zero knowledge of “female” somehow ended up on a trip to serve 16 girls, ages 5-16. These girl’s parents had given up day-to-day contact with them, sending them to “The Village of Hope” so they could escape the threat of some of the most intense poverty the world knows.\r\n\r\nSeven years and eight trips later and I’m officially obsessed. I go to The Villa because I’ve come to see glimpses of what God’s unconditional love looks like, not only towards these girls, but towards me. Now when I head to Nicaragua I see 25-30 girls, ages 12-23, who are not poor, broken, sinful, or stubborn, but who are blameless children of a living God. These girls are royal, and so am I. Their Father is King, and so is mine.\r\n\r\nOn Saturday I said goodbye to Massiel, our 14-year old, Nicaraguan little sister. My wife and I have known her for 3 years and I think she’s perfect. Yes, she struggles to receive my love often because she didn’t learn love growing up. Yes, it’s challenging to communicate with her in my poor Spanish. Yes, she is one of my best friends. And yes, one of my greatest joys is learning to give and receive love alongside her.\r\n\r\nMassiel is a child of God who is delighted in by her Father.\r\n\r\nFour years ago I was devastated to see Alondra, the most precious 12-year old girl, walk away from The Villa. She chose to leave because she wanted to experience the world on her own. I met Alondra on my first day at The Villa. Today, at 16, she is pregnant with her second child. The dad of her first born was 28-years old and was gone as quickly as he arrived. This is the difficult reality for a lot of young girls in Nicaragua.\r\n\r\nYet Alondra is a child of God who is delighted in by her Father.\r\n\r\nThe Villa exists within the tension of the now and not yet. On one hand we see injustice – girls who have been abused, broken, and disturbed by a life of pain and evil. On the other hand, I get to see Heaven and Earth meet every year when I’m there as two dozen girls get to re-learn who they are; beloved daughters of God. I get to stand in the tension of the now and not yet with the vibrant, unwavering hope that Jesus is coming back to put the world to rights.\r\n\r\nIn three months I’m having my first child – a daughter. Eighty percent of my family produces male offspring, and I’m having a girl.\r\n\r\nMy God is so kind that seven years ago, at the naïve age of 19, he let me go to Nicaragua and learn how much he loves me by teaching me what unconditional love looks like for one of his perfect daughters. In October, I get to lavish my own daughter with the same unconditional love my perfect Father has taught me through the girls at La Villa Esperanza.\r\n\r\nThis is why I go to Nicaragua ever year. They are some of the most beautiful girls the world has ever seen. Regardless of what the rest of the year has given me, God lets me wear his glasses for a week to be reminded of what identity looks like in his Kingdom.\r\n\r\nWe are the beloved.\r\n\r\nAlondra is a beloved child of God.\r\n\r\nMassiel is a beloved child of God.\r\n\r\nMy own baby girl is a beloved child of God.\r\n\r\nI am a beloved child of God.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nLearn more about La Villa Esperanza and other opportunities to serve those in need around the world with Hear The Cry.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://hearthecry.org\" target=\"_blank\">Hear The Cry</a> [/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Heaven and Earth in Nicaragua','','publish','closed','closed','','heaven-and-earth-in-nicaragua','','','2016-07-19 00:22:28','2016-07-19 08:22:28','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1540',0,'post','',0),(1552,22,'2015-08-11 16:57:04','2015-08-11 23:57:04','Haiti is about an hour and a half flight south of Florida in the heart of the Caribbean. It sounds like a dream to visit (um, the Caribbean!) but in reality there is a visible contrast that hits you as hard as the humidity.\r\n\r\nThe stunning terrain and palm trees that are surrounded by beautiful warm water is also home to the poorest people in the western hemisphere; a level of poverty that most of us could not even imagine! As you ride into town, your senses are overwhelmed by the number of people in the streets, the smells of cooking food, and the amount of trash that has inevitably taken a huge toll on the country.\r\n\r\nHowever, with just one look into the dark eyes of the Haitians, you quickly recognize the human connection and that these people are just like you and me.\r\n\r\nMen who want to care for their families, women who want to love their children and provide a better life than what they had, and kids who want to stimulate their minds and bodies with toys and play. Much <em>looks </em>different than the lives Americans live, but when you strip it down to the bones, you will see that the Haitians are strong, bold, courageous people who desire the same comfort and stabilities as you and as me.\r\n\r\nIf you drive a little further into the country you will find the oasis that is <em>MamaBaby Haiti, </em>an organization of midwives and volunteers whose mission is to create a safe place for Haitian women to receive free maternity care.\r\n\r\nMBH was founded by a group of midwives in 2010 after an earthquake devastated parts of the country. They quickly saw that women and babies were dying too often, and not because of illness or sanitation, but simply due to the fact that they did not have a safe and compassionate place to receive prenatal care and give birth.\r\n\r\nNormal pregnancies were ending gravely after women chose to stay home because of the costs and travel associated with trips to the hospital. Where there is severe poverty, mothers sometimes have to choose between food for their family or having a skilled attendant at their birth.\r\n\r\nMamaBaby Haiti believes this is not okay, and it is their core belief that no woman or child should ever die because of where they live.\r\n\r\nThe founders opened a free clinic to provide complete care to every woman and baby that walked through its doors. They were determined to save lives, one mama and one baby at a time.\r\n\r\nEvery day we are making strides toward thriving Haitian families. Four Haitian midwives run the organization with the help of eight Haitian support staff members, and a six person volunteer board in the States. We have big dreams for the future, full of healthy mamas and babies, micro-businesses for our families, sustainable gardening and farming, and of opening a midwifery school to train more Haitians to care for their own.\r\n\r\nThis is just a glimpse into what is happening at MamaBaby Haiti. Learn more.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.mamababyhaiti.org\" target=\"_blank\">MamaBaby Haiti</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em style=\"color: #525252;\"><span style=\"color: #c0c0c0;\">The link provided is a convenience for informational purposes only; it does not constitute an endorsement or an approval by the A Jesus Church Family of any of the products, services, or opinions of the organization or individual. The A Jesus Church Family bears no responsibility for the accuracy, legality, or content of the external site or for that of subsequent links. Contact the external site for answers to questions regarding its content.</span></em>','The Dangers for New Mothers in Haiti','','publish','closed','closed','','the-dangers-for-new-mothers-in-haiti','','','2016-07-19 00:19:57','2016-07-19 08:19:57','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1552',0,'post','',0),(1571,14,'2015-09-07 11:06:24','2015-09-07 18:06:24','Have you ever gone through a season when you’re not hearing from God? You pray, but the heavens are still. You read Scripture, but the words fail to connect with your life. You worship, but your heart feels cold. You’re desperate for the presence of God, but it feels like He’s a million miles away. If you’ve ever been there, you can relate to David when he wrote in Psalm 63:\r\n\r\n<em>You, God, are my God,</em>\r\n<em>Earnestly I seek you;</em>\r\n<em>I thirst for you,</em>\r\n<em>My whole being longs for you,</em>\r\n<em>In a dry and parched land</em>\r\n<em>Where there is no water.</em>\r\n\r\nSpiritual thirst, like physical thirst, is profoundly exhausting and disorienting. We were created to be in community with God. Part of being human is a longing to hear His voice.  But when that voice goes still, it can feel like spiritual vertigo: clarity is replaced with uncertainty, faith subverted by doubt.  How do we navigate seasons like this? In the words St. John of the Cross, how do we find God \"in the dark night of the soul?\"\r\n\r\nYou are not alone.\r\n\r\nWhile there are no simple answers, we have to begin with the truth that we are not alone. History is filled with countless, godly, women and men who went through similar struggles. David, Job, Habakkuk, Paul, Mother Theresa, CS Lewis, all described times of intense spiritual isolation.  This is important, because sometimes we assume that nobody can identify with our struggle; and so we withdraw. We put up walls. We pull back. But the more we remove ourselves from community, the stronger the sense of isolation becomes. In Scripture, the church is called \"the body of Christ.\" If we want to hear His voice, we need to be near His body. We need to surround ourselves with people who can be the voice of God in our lives.\r\n\r\nSometimes silence is God’s loudest way of warning us.\r\n\r\nOne of the most powerful things about silence is that it sensitizes us to the slightest sound. Silence amplifies things in our life that have been ignored or drowned out by noise. It’s for this reason that silence can be God’s most loving way of getting our attention. Silence can be a sign that something is deeply wrong in our hearts. In Psalm 66:18, David wrote, \"If I had cherished sin in my heart, the Lord would not have listened.\" In other words, what appears to be the absence of God is sometimes just the presence of sin. While this isn’t always the case, silence invites us to examine our hearts to see if something has gotten in the way.\r\n\r\nOther times, we are simply too busy to hear the voice of God. When God speaks, it’s usually a whisper (1 Kings 19:12); but in order to hear a whisper, we have to quiet the noise around us and within us. Could it be that He has been speaking, but we aren’t listening? The difficulty with trying to hear from God isn’t that He’s so far away, it’s that He’s so close. He is like the air we breathe, but we don’t notice.\r\n\r\nSometimes silence is God’s catalyst for spiritual growth\r\n\r\nJust as seasons of drought drive the roots of a tree deeper in search of water, spiritual drought can drive us deeper in our search for God. Seasons of silence can kindle in our hearts a greater yearning for the presence of God; it awakens within us a longing for faith that moves beyond the superficial into more authentic relationship.\r\n\r\nIt’s easy to love God when he seems close; but the true test of love is when we have to fight for love. It’s when our hearts ache for God, that we abandon superficial comfort and pursue radical trust and intimacy. It’s in this pursuit that we discover God in all kinds of surprising ways and places; and we may also discover a depth in our heart that didn’t exist apart from thirst. God steps back, and we step forward.  The view is great on the mountain; but fruit grows in the valley.\r\n\r\nGod’s silence is not His absence.\r\n\r\nSome of the most beautiful things that God does are done in silence. The famous dancer Isador Duncan once performed in front of an audience. When she was finished, she was asked to put into words her experience. She responded, “If I could put it into words, I wouldn’t have to dance it.” There are times in life when beauty is most clearly seen not through words, but through the graceful dance of silence. In John 13, Jesus washed the feet of His disciples. They didn’t understand what He was doing, but through this wordless act, they were made clean. What if God is silent because He is doing something deeper than words in your life? What if Jesus is washing your feet? What if this season is His way of preparing you for what is yet to come?\r\n\r\nGod’s silence is not His absence. In fact, His silence may be the very thing that causes you to encounter Him like you never have before.\r\n\r\n\"I know now, o Lord, why you utter no answer. You Yourself are the answer.\" –CS Lewis\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Why is God Silent?','','publish','closed','closed','','why-is-god-silent','','','2016-07-19 00:18:09','2016-07-19 08:18:09','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1571',0,'post','',0),(1575,20,'2015-09-15 16:50:24','2015-09-15 23:50:24','You have probably asked the question at some point in your life during a major transition, and it’s not always easy to answer.\r\n\r\n“Well, now what?”\r\n\r\nWestside couple Mike and Linda wondered just that after retiring in January of this year. While they prayed together in the mornings, they asked, “Tell us what you want us to do. We don’t just want to do nothing.”\r\n\r\nThey decided that a good way to begin seeking would be to get connected to a missional community, so they started looking for one.\r\n\r\nSoon, an ordinary day of shopping would give them an answer they weren’t expecting. They shared some of their story with a man named David who was helping them shop for a computer, explaining that they just retired.\r\n\r\n“What are you going to do with yourselves?” David asked.\r\n\r\nSo they shared their desire to serve, particularly through what their church called missional community. It just so happened that David was part of the same church and had been looking for a couple like them willing to pour into an existing community of young adults.\r\n\r\nMike and Linda were a little hesitant. It had been years since their five kids left the house and they didn’t know what to expect. But they went to visit the group that same night.\r\n\r\n“Initially I was a little skeptical. We didn’t know who was in the group or what our role was actually going to be,” Mike says. “But we didn’t really need to pray about it. We’d been asking God to show us what to do, and it was right there.”\r\n\r\nOn their way out to visit this mysterious group, it was raining and they had to drive down a long and dark dirt road to get to the place where they gathered. “Where are we going?” they asked, wondering what they had gotten themselves into.\r\n\r\n“I think some older adults have this idea about younger generations—that they’re going to be loud or disrespectful,” Linda says. But she was pleasantly surprised. “All of them were so welcoming.”\r\n\r\nAs they got to know each other, they realized they had a lot more in common than they expected. While Mike and Linda were often asked what they were going to do after retiring, these younger adults were being asked where they were going to attend college, or what they were going to do after they graduate.\r\n\r\n“We were all trying to figure out what to do with our lives,” Linda says.\r\n\r\n“There’s a lot of pressure on them,” Mike adds, recalling that he didn’t have a clue what to do after college. “I try to give them advice and help them not to worry so much.”\r\n\r\nNow Mike and Linda host the community at their house every week, making dinner for everyone ahead of time. They find freedom in knowing they don’t need to lead everyone. Instead they create an environment of hospitality and support them in whatever way they can, which usually looks like guidance here and there, and encouragement about where they are in life.\r\n\r\n“I’ve always wondered where the next generation of Christians will be coming from and who’s going to teach Jesus and the Bible, and I can see it in this group. I’m really proud of them,” Mike says. “We’ve told them this is a safe house. If you get in trouble, you can always knock on our door.”\r\n\r\nWhen asked how they have seen the group develop over the months, the couple explained that they already see the community growing spiritually, and they attribute this change to the time they spend together in prayer. “I’m amazed by the way they pray,” Linda says, encouraged by their energy and vulnerability with Jesus.\r\n\r\n“We didn’t think we were going to like it as much as we do.” Linda laughs. “They’re a lot more fun than our family!”\r\n\r\nAs generations mix within Missional Communities, it can look many different ways. If you’re curious about connecting with young adults, Mike and Linda encourage you not to be intimidated, and to visit their community to get a taste of what it could look like, then choose how to make it your own.\r\n\r\n“God has given us a lot,” Linda says. “And now we feel like we’re finally giving back. Not just to the young adults, but to God, because he gave to us.”\r\n\r\nAs they share their story, pulled pork is roasting in the kitchen for their weekly family night. They refuse to let their community settle for pizza every week and they enjoy loving people through good meals. “Were almost like a restaurant,” Mike says. “Except you don’t have to tip—unless you want to.”\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_unknown.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1589\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_unknown.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_unknown\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Why Embracing the Unknown Can Be Awesome','','publish','closed','closed','','why-embracing-the-unknown-can-be-awesome','','','2016-07-19 00:16:47','2016-07-19 08:16:47','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1575',0,'post','',0),(1594,25,'2015-09-16 16:54:37','2015-09-16 23:54:37','<p style=\"color: #525252;\">Bridgetown wants to be a church that speaks with an educated voice. We want to be thoughtful and academic, challenging the traditional paradigm of Christian thought. The gospel is powerful and we want to use it accurately to communicate the message of Jesus.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">Follow along with our Bridgetown Recommended Reading. Our hope is that we would continually expand our minds and understanding of the Kingdom of God. This will allow us to become more effective in our mission to share the gospel in our city.</p>\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/When-Church-Was-Family-Recapturing/dp/0805447792/ref=asap_bc?ie=UTF8 \" target=\"_blank\">When the church was a family</a>[/page_actions] by Joseph H. Hellerman\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/The-Mission-Gods-People-Biblical/dp/0310291127\" target=\"_blank\">The Mission of God’s people</a>[/page_actions] by Christopher J. H. Wright\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Great-Omission-Reclaiming-Essential-Discipleship/dp/0062311751/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1442344791&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=The+Great+Omission+by+Dallas+Willard\" target=\"_blank\">The Great Omission</a>[/page_actions] by Dallas Willard\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Slow-Church-Cultivating-Community-Patient/dp/0830841148/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1442344826&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=Slow+Church+by+C.+Christopher+Smith\" target=\"_blank\">Slow Church</a>[/page_actions] by C. Christopher Smith\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Bridgetown Recommended Reading','','publish','closed','closed','','bridgetown-recommended-reading','','','2016-07-19 00:13:29','2016-07-19 08:13:29','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1594',0,'post','',0),(1636,4,'2015-12-27 16:52:59','2015-12-28 00:52:59','','ajc_yobl_thumb_read_4','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_yobl_thumb_read_4','','','2015-12-27 16:52:59','2015-12-28 00:52:59','',1509,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_yobl_thumb_read_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1637,19,'2015-09-28 11:32:03','2015-09-28 18:32:03','The vision for Spokane started about six years ago on a bus. God spoke to Matt Karsh as he was riding through the city, and said “There is going to be a church here.” And from this simple beginning, the church began to grow.\r\n\r\nOver the last six years the vision has continued to gain momentum, and eventually we decided to go and visit the city. Immediately, we could see God at work there. The Holy Spirit is calling people to be a part of this church plant. We were encountering people hungry for something new, who are eager to see a fresh expression of church in their city. So we started to dream.\r\n\r\nAfter doing some research, we have come to learn that Spokane is filled with over 400,000 people who don’t know Jesus. Each of those individuals is what motivates us to plant a new church in Spokane. At the same time, our family of churches have become increasingly aware of the story being written in their midst, recognizing a strong call to continue planting churches in the Northwest and beyond. For the last few years we have been praying about what it would look like to plant a church in the city of Spokane, and we invite you to be a part of the work.\r\n<h1>Matt &amp; Abby Deisen</h1>\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_spokane_diesen.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1627\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_spokane_diesen.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_spokane_diesen\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe Spokane church plant will be co-pastored. Matt Deisen was an attorney who gave up practicing law when God called him into vocational ministry. He has served on the staff at Westside: A Jesus Church for the last two years as an embedded church planter. Abby has been serving as a leader at Westside for nearly a decade and is currently devoted to raising their son Moses.\r\n<h1>Matt &amp; Jenna Karsh</h1>\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_spokane_karsh.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1628\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_spokane_karsh.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_spokane_karsh\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMatt Karsh recently graduated from Western Seminary and has worked on staff at Sunset: A Jesus Church for the last three years. Jenna works in the school district and is studying to become a school counselor. Matt and Jenna are already living and working in the city of Spokane, getting to know the city and its people.\r\n<h1>Contact</h1>\r\nContact us if you have any questions about the Spokane Church Plant or would like to get involved.\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=mkarsh@ajesuschurch.org]Spokane Contact[/email][email address=mattd@ajesuschurch.org]Portland Contact[/email][/page_actions]\r\n<h1>Spokane Church Plant</h1>\r\n<span style=\"color: #525252;\">For all the information about the Spokane Church Plant, including giving and a schedule for prayer meetings, visit their website.</span>\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/spokane/\">Spokane Church Plant</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Spokane Church Plant','','publish','closed','closed','','spokane-church-plant','','','2016-07-19 00:06:00','2016-07-19 08:06:00','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1637',0,'post','',0),(1644,19,'2015-09-28 11:31:51','2015-09-28 18:31:51','<p style=\"color: #525252;\">Bend is all about a lifestyle. It’s about year-round outdoor adventure. It’s about cuisine and beer and coffee. Therefore, Bend is attracting a wave of millennials who want to experience a piece of Heaven on Earth. Over the last year, the leadership has been seeking God in prayer about what it might look like to plant A Jesus Church in Bend.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">According to a 2010 census, 74% of residents in Deschutes County do not adhere to a “religious” system of belief. Only 11% of residents identify themselves as Evangelical Protestant. But because of the rapid influx of Millennials (who are less likely to be connected to a faith community) moving into the heart of Bend, we believe the statistics today in west Bend are even more drastic.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">So, how is God calling the A Jesus Church Family to respond? Simply stated: to be the Church in Bend. God is calling us to be the family of God, on the mission of God, making disciples of Jesus in the heart of Bend. Our vision is to see an unified collection of Missional Communities who identify the pocket of Bend they are uniquely suited to share the Gospel of Jesus with, and who live together on mission there.</p>\r\n\r\n<h1>Andrew &amp; Grace Rothrock</h1>\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_bend_rothrock.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1630\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_bend_rothrock.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_bend_rothrock\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAndrew is an outdoor enthusiast and lifelong resident of Oregon with a deep love for the beauty and adventure in the Pacific Northwest. Grace grew up all over the states and abroad in a missionary family, and as an adult, landed in Portland with our family of churches back when we were called Solid Rock. Their pursuit of  becoming more like Jesus is what brought them together six years ago. They have a three year-old daughter named Isabel.\r\n\r\nAndrew and Grace are avid students of the Scripture and love to share life with other followers of Jesus. They are relocating from Central Oregon to Portland for a season to become embedded church planters at Westside, to train with the leadership, and build a team to join them in planting in April 2017.\r\n<h1>Contact</h1>\r\nIf you have questions or to learn more about how you can be involved in the Bend Church Plant, connect with Andrew Rothrock.\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=andrew.rothrock@ajesuschurch.org]Contact Andrew Rothrock[/email][/page_actions]\r\n<h1 style=\"color: #030303;\">Bend Church Website</h1>\r\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">For all the information about the Bend Church Plant, including giving and a schedule for prayer meetings, visit their website.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bend/\">Bend Church Plant</a>[/page_actions]</p>\r\n&nbsp;','Bend Church Plant','','publish','closed','closed','','bend-church-plant','','','2016-07-19 00:09:47','2016-07-19 08:09:47','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1644',0,'post','',0),(1645,4,'2015-12-27 17:12:01','2015-12-28 01:12:01','','ajc_yobl_thumb_watch_4','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_yobl_thumb_watch_4','','','2015-12-27 17:12:01','2015-12-28 01:12:01','',1511,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_yobl_thumb_watch_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1647,4,'2015-12-27 17:15:21','2015-12-28 01:15:21','','ajc_yobl_thumb_listen_4','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_yobl_thumb_listen_4','','','2015-12-27 17:15:21','2015-12-28 01:15:21','',1513,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_yobl_thumb_listen_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1649,4,'2015-12-27 17:15:37','2015-12-28 01:15:37','','ajc_yobl_thumb_talk_4','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_yobl_thumb_talk_4','','','2015-12-27 17:15:37','2015-12-28 01:15:37','',1515,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_yobl_thumb_talk_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1653,4,'2015-12-27 17:25:42','2015-12-28 01:25:42','','yobl_hero_2','','inherit','open','open','','yobl_hero_2-4','','','2015-12-27 17:25:42','2015-12-28 01:25:42','',1505,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/yobl_hero_23.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1683,10,'2015-12-30 00:27:03','2015-12-30 08:27:03','','Gods Name And Yours','','publish','closed','closed','','gods-name-and-yours','','','2016-01-25 10:12:42','2016-01-25 18:12:42','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?post_type=teaching&#038;p=1683',31,'teaching','',0),(1685,4,'2015-12-30 13:30:27','2015-12-30 21:30:27','','yobl_hero_2','','inherit','open','open','','yobl_hero_2-5','','','2015-12-30 13:30:27','2015-12-30 21:30:27','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/yobl_hero_24.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1691,4,'2015-12-30 14:52:20','2015-12-30 22:52:20','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_read','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_read','','','2015-12-30 14:52:20','2015-12-30 22:52:20','',1509,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_read.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1693,4,'2015-12-30 15:01:28','2015-12-30 23:01:28','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_watch','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_watch','','','2015-12-30 15:01:28','2015-12-30 23:01:28','',1511,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_watch.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1695,4,'2015-12-30 15:04:23','2015-12-30 23:04:23','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_listen','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_listen','','','2015-12-30 15:04:23','2015-12-30 23:04:23','',1513,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_listen.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1697,4,'2015-12-30 15:05:55','2015-12-30 23:05:55','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_talk','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_talk','','','2015-12-30 15:05:55','2015-12-30 23:05:55','',1515,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_thumb_talk.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1701,4,'2016-06-29 08:56:47','2016-06-29 16:56:47','<h1>Discussion Questions</h1>\nWe encourage everybody to discuss Biblical Literacy with their communities. Jesus and his disciples learned together in community and we want to do the same. We have compiled some questions to help guide you through the year of studying as you learn and grow together.\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Jun 26 – Jul 2</h7>\nJeremiah 37 – Lamentations 3\nPsalm 23 – 29\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nHow does walking through the details of Israel’s exile and trying to wrap your mind around the felt experience help shine new light on what you’ve been reading?\n\nHave someone read Psalm 137, a psalm written in exile, aloud. How does a sufficient understanding of the sheer agony of exile help you understand and even empathize with the brutally honest prayers of this psalm?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Jun 26 – Jul 2</h7>\nJeremiah 37 – Lamentations 3\nPsalm 23 – 29\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nHow does walking through the details of Israel’s exile and trying to wrap your mind around the felt experience help shine new light on what you’ve been reading?\n\nHave someone read Psalm 137, a psalm written in exile, aloud. How does a sufficient understanding of the sheer agony of exile help you understand and even empathize with the brutally honest prayers of this psalm?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Jun 12 – 18</h7>\nEcclesiastes 5 – Song of Songs 8\nJeremiah 1 – 9\nPsalm 9 – 15\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nEcclesiastes, and especially the beautiful poem about dying in chapter 12, invite readers to reflect on the seeming futility of life and inevitability of death. How might thinking about these things invite us into interaction and dialogue with God?\n\nWhen you read Ecclesiastes, do you find its nihilism depressing, strangely comforting, or both?\n\nHow might “meaningless, meaningless” coexist with the rest of the story of Scripture, which says our lives are deeply meaningful to God? How have you seen this tension lived out as you reflect on your own life?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Jun 5 – 11</h7>\nProverbs 13 – Ecclesiastes 4 \nPsalm 2 – 8\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nHow can Jesus’ life and teachings help show us the connection between faithfulness to God and wisdom for living well?\n\nAre there any gospel stories, parables, or attributes of Jesus that reveal both His faithful reverence for God and His incredible wisdom?\n\nThe Book of Proverbs is basically Israel’s collection of wisdom sayings that takes the form of advice that a father would give to his son. Consider advice for a moment. What kind of advice do you tend to take in, where do you consume advice, and how much of it do you consume?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>May 29 – Jun 4</h7>\nJob 38 – Psalm 2\nProverbs 1 – 12\nPsalm 145 – 150 & 1\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nCan we love God for God, and not for all his blessings? What about when the blessings go away?\n\nDoes the story of Job bring comfort and relief?\n\nHave you ever voiced your anger, pain or doubt to God in times of deep suffering in your life? If yes, what was God’s response to you? If you have not, what would it have been like to direct your anguish to God?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>May 22 – 28</h7>\nJob 12 – 37\nPsalm 138 – 144\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nHow do you think Job must have been feeling?\n\nWhat does the book of Job tell us about God?\n\nWhat does the book of Job tell us about Satan?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>May 15 – 21</h7>\nMicah 5 – Zephaniah 3\nJob 1 – 11\nPsalm 131 – 137\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nThinking back to how most prophets in the Old Testament are portrayed, why is Jonah’s immediate disobedience in v1­-3 so surprising? 	\n\nHow is Jonah’s character consistent with the character of Israel and its leaders/people throughout the Old Testament? 		\n\nLike Jonah, are there people or people groups you feel do not deserve God’s grace, mercy, and love? Why do you feel they don’t deserve it?	\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>May 8 – 14</h7>\nHosea 11 – Micah 4\nPsalm 124 – 130\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nRead Hosea 11:1-12. What does this chapter show you about the fatherly heart of God over Israel?\n\nWhat is it like for you to engage with such an emotional God as depicted in Hosea? Does it bother you or comfort you to consider God experiencing heartache, jealousy, and humiliation? \n\nDo you typically interact with God on such emotional terms, or do you find that your relationship tends to assume a pattern where you and/or God are simply calm, cool, and collected?\n\nHosea married a promiscuous woman not merely as a symbol for what Israel was to God — unfaithful to their covenant — but to actually experience what this felt like for God. Have you ever had an experience where you felt God’s disturbed yet gracious heart toward you and your people? How did you feel in that moment, and what did it bring up in you?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>May 1 – 7</h7>\nIsaiah 52 – 66\nHosea 1 – 10\nPsalm 119v97 – 123\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nMuch of Isaiah speaks about the nature of being the “servant of the Lord,” typically referring to Israel’s identity and vocation, as well as a “suffering servant.” Consider Israel’s calling to help God redeem the broken world through living as a holy priesthood and leading the nations to God. How do you think the experience of suffering in exile helped shape this understanding of a suffering servant (Isaiah 52-53)?\n\nHow do you think Jesus’ understanding of Israel’s identity and His own unique vocation as the true Israel and Israel’s true king was shaped by these texts in Isaiah?\n\nAn ancient Israelite like Isaiah felt a kind of guilt on behalf of his sinful community and expected the entire nation, himself included, to suffer the consequences unless the nation as a whole repented. Have you ever felt like you’ve suffered the consequences of your community’s sin? How did this make you feel?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Apr 24 – 30</h7>\nIsaiah 28 – 51\nPsalm 115 – 119v96\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nHow can Israel’s history and the prophets teach us to think about and respond to evil and injustice in our society or community that we haven’t personally committed but have potentially benefitted from? In other words, what should we do with sin that we haven’t overtly committed, but that we are complicit to just by the nature of the community to which we belong?\n\nHow does it make you feel to think about owning your community’s sin? Are you able to embrace this idea, or do you feel resistant to it?\n\nWhere does your mind immediately go when you think of your community’s sin? Your family, your city, your nation, company, community group, subculture?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Apr 17 – 23</h7>\n2  Kings 23 \nIsaiah 1 – 27\nPsalm 108 – 114\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nReflect back on your readings in 1 and 2 Kings. What stood out to you most from story after story of kings “doing what was evil in the eyes of the Lord”?\n\nAs you read through the stories, did you find yourself hoping for God to bring judgment upon Israel and punish them for their sins, or for God to continue to show them patience and mercy?\n\nHow would it have felt, emotionally and physically, to have been a Jew living in Jerusalem during this exile?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Apr 10 – 16</h7>\n2 Kings 1 – 22\nPsalm 101 – 107\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nRead 1 Kings 10:14-29. Considering Moses’ warning in Deuteronomy 8 and Samuel’s warning in 1 Samuel 8, what kind of attitude should we have toward this new era of “progress” and prosperity established under Solomon?\n\nShould we celebrate this prosperity as the blessing of God or be concerned that it is the result of a new kind of Jewish pharaoh figure? \n\nIf you put yourselves in the shoes of an ancient Jew, who would you prefer as your king: David or Solomon? Would you want the prayerful musician-king who humiliates himself by worshiping God in his underwear, or the kind of global political and economic powerhouse who establishes you and your people above the other nations and exacts from them such wealth that “silver becomes like just another stone,” no matter what the cost?\n\nReflect on the parts of your life where you are currently experiencing prosperity. Ask the Holy Spirit to give you brutal honesty and clarity as to the nature of your prosperity. Do you think you have gained prosperity because you and your part of society have faithfully followed the commands of God to live humbly, justly, mercifully, and lovingly?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Apr 3 – 9</h7>\n1 Kings 1 – 22\nPsalm 94 – 100\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nReflect back on your readings in 1 & 2 Samuel. What kind of actions and choices justified the Scriptures’ assessment of David as a righteous man and leader?\n\nThink about the fact that Israel’s most exalted king, whose life is given more detailed attention than any other Old Testament character, is also the person who created about half of the Psalms (such as the praise song of Psalm 18). What connection can you make between the internal character and heart expressed in the prayers of the Psalms and the external character and heart illustrated in David’s life and actions? \n\nHow do you relate to this idea of being sinful but ever in pursuit of holiness?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Mar 27 – Apr 2</h7>\n2 Samuel 1 – 24\nPsalm 87 – 93\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nOne of the hermeneutic guidelines for reading Biblical narrative is to pay attention to the pace of the story, especially noticing when it slows down dramatically to zoom in on a particular time or event. Typically, this indicates a particularly important chapter of the story. Why do you think the narrative slows down so much in Ruth & 1 Samuel after racing through hundreds of years of history in Judges?\n\nRead Deuteronomy 17:14-20 again. What kind of king is Israel supposed to have? Do you think Samuel embodies well the type of king Deuteronomy 17 describes?\n\nGod calls us, like Israel, to live differently (or as holy) from the world and the culture around us. With this in mind, in what ways can you identify with Israel’s rebellious desire to instead follow the ways of the world?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Mar 20 – 26</h7>\n1 Samuel 9 – 31\nPsalm 80 – 86\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nIn Ruth, we see that God cares for us deeply. How is God involved in the day-to-day joys and hardships of your life? \n\nRuth tells the story of a family this is hurting and broken, but in their faithfulness to God they are restored and made whole. Have you experienced similar restoration through God?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Mar 13 – 19</h7>\nJudges 9 – 1 Samuel 8\nPsalm 73 – 79\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nAs you read the book of Judges, what do you think the author’s intent was in chronicling this era of Israel’s history the way that he did?\n\nWere there any parts of Judges 19 that shocked, provoked, surprised, confused, disturbed, or confronted you?\n\nWhy do you think the author of Judges includes this violent, horrific story? What point might the author of Judges be trying to get across to his/her readers?\n\nIs it disorienting to read such a gruesome and awful story in the Bible? What questions does it bring up in you about God, Israel, human nature, or the Scriptures?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Mar 6 – 12</h7>\nJoshua 5 – Judges 8\nPsalm 66 – 72\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nAt this point in the reading, you have completed the Torah (Gen – Deu). What were the major themes, ideas, emotions, or experiences you remember from reading the Torah?\n\nHave someone recap the book of Joshua. What has happened so far and what are the main events and themes of the book?\n\nIsrael was called to obey God’s commands so that the other nations could see what God is like. In what ways can you, as a community, display the character of Jesus to people around you?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Feb 28 – Mar 5</h7>\nDeu 17 – Joshua 4\nPsalm 59 – 65\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nThe people of God were led out of the wilderness and into the promised land. Can you recognize a time in your life where God has led you out of a figurative “wilderness” and into the “promised land?”\n\nDeuteronomy is Moses recapping the past 40 years since the Exodus to the now grown up children of Israel. Imagine you are listening to Moses give this final address. All you have known is life wandering in the wilderness. You have heard stories from your parents of what God has done for your people, you have heard the Law. What is Moses trying to remind you and the rest of Israel of?\n\nGod protected and blessed the Israelites even when they were in rebellion. Looking back, when was there a time when you were not following God yet he continued to bless you?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Feb 21 – 27</h7>\nNumbers 35 – Deu 16\nPsalm 52 – 58\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nHow would you summarize Numbers in a sentence or two?\n\nIs there any part of the blessings that God gives Israel through Balaam that you find particularly beautiful, rich, or interesting?\n\n“Love the LORD your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your strength.” –Deu 6v5. Take a moment to meditate on this scripture and express your love to God in prayer together.\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Feb 14 – 20</h7>\nNumbers 17 – 34\nPsalm 45 – 51\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nIn Numbers, God’s holy presence is their leader and guide as they travel through the desert. As followers of Jesus, how have you allowed the Spirit to lead you this week?\n\nWhen the spies saw the Promised Land they feared for their lives and wanted to return to captivity in Egypt. How can fear tempt us to return to what God has saved us from?\n\nWhile God remains faithful to his people and his promises he will honor your choices and let you live in rebellion if you choose it. Take a moment in listening prayer to ask to God how you may be misaligned with the way of Jesus. \n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Feb 7 – 13</h7>\nLeviticus 24 – Numbers 16\nPsalm 38 – 44\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nCan anyone offer a one-sentence summary of Leviticus? To help you answering, think about: “If the author of Leviticus wanted his hearers to come away with one thing, what would it be? Why did he work so hard to keep and record and pass along this text?”\n\nIf you try to imagine being a part of Israel at this time, how would you have responded to some of these commands? Do you think you would have obeyed? Would you have loved them or hated them?\n\nA number of the Israelite’s rebellions were born from their lack of trust in God. Can you relate to their experience? How has your trust in God been challenged? \n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>Jan 31 – Feb 6</h7>\nLeviticus 5 – 23\nPsalm 31 – 37\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nWhat parts of the story simply don’t make sense or have been frustrating to read? (Note: In discussing these together, try to balance helping each other wrestle with difficult texts along with becoming comfortable with discomfort and imperfect understanding. It’s okay and even necessary to admit when we don’t grasp a part of the Scriptures and to not get too hung up. Keep reading.)\n\nJust as the animals sacrificed in Leviticus, Jesus is our “sacrificial lamb” that takes away our sin, making us holy. What practical steps can we take to remain holy?\n\nIn Leviticus, the people of God used ritual sacrifices to essentially say, “Thank you” and “I’m sorry.” How can we express these same sentiments in our relationship with God?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>January 24 – 30</h7>\nExodus 22 – Leviticus 4\nPsalm 24 – 30\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nThe people of God have a terrible pattern of sin and self-destruction. In what ways can you identify with this pattern in your life?\n\nUnlike the people of God in Exodus, we now have direct access to the presence of God because of the work of Jesus on the cross. In what ways can we help each other to embrace this new reality?\n\nGod continues to be faithful to his promise to Abraham (Gen 12v1-2) and make the people of God a blessing to the nations. In what ways can we be a blessing to our city and the nations?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>January 17 – 23</h7>\nExodus 1 – 21\nPsalm 17 – 23\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nMoses, a man who seems to have trouble with anger and doubt, is called by God to be the deliverer of Israel. In what ways do you relate as an imperfect person who is called by God?\n\nAt this point in the story, Israel is enslaved and God appears to be absent. When have you felt disappointed with life and God’s role in it and felt frustrated or hurt by his absence?\n\nJust as God freed his people from slavery in Egypt, Jesus has set you free. In what ways have you experienced this freedom?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>January 10 – 16</h7>\nGenesis 32 – 50\nPsalm 10 – 16\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nWhat parts of the story simply don’t make sense or have been frustrating to read? (Note: In discussing these together, try to balance helping each other wrestle with difficult texts along with becoming comfortable with discomfort and imperfect understanding. It’s okay and even necessary to admit when we don’t grasp a part of the Scriptures and to not get too hung up. Keep reading.)\n\nGenesis begins with the people of God living with him in the garden, but ends with the death of Joseph and the people of God facing slavery in Egypt. What do you think you, as a reader, are meant to be feeling?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]\n\n<hr />\n\n[one_fourth padding=\"0 20px 0 0\"]\n\n<h7>January 3 – 9</h7>\nGenesis 1 – 31\nPsalm 1 – 6\n\n[/one_fourth][three_fourth_last]\n\nIn Genesis 1 – 2, what struck you as significant about God’s original intention for humankind and creation?\n\nIn Genesis 3 – 11, in what ways do you identify with the continual failures of humankind’s ability to live up to God’s original plan?\n\nTo Abraham, God made an unconditional promise to make the world right and good again. What hope does this promise to Abraham give for you and your community?\n\n[/three_fourth_last]','Talk','','inherit','open','open','','1515-autosave-v1','','','2016-06-29 08:56:47','2016-06-29 16:56:47','',1515,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/1515-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(1704,4,'2015-12-30 15:22:01','2015-12-30 23:22:01','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_talk','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_talk','','','2015-12-30 15:22:01','2015-12-30 23:22:01','',1515,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_hero_talk.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1713,4,'2015-12-30 15:30:19','2015-12-30 23:30:19','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_talk','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_talk-2','','','2015-12-30 15:30:19','2015-12-30 23:30:19','',1515,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_hero_talk1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1717,4,'2015-12-30 15:34:11','2015-12-30 23:34:11','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_listen','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_listen','','','2015-12-30 15:34:11','2015-12-30 23:34:11','',1513,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_hero_listen.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1721,4,'2015-12-30 15:41:35','2015-12-30 23:41:35','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_read','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_read','','','2015-12-30 15:41:35','2015-12-30 23:41:35','',1509,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2015/12/ajc_bt_yobl_hero_read.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1726,4,'2015-12-30 15:52:38','2015-12-30 23:52:38','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_watch','','inherit','open','open','','ajc_bt_yobl_hero_watch-2','','','2015-12-30 15:52:38','2015-12-30 23:52:38','',1511,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content