r. Growing up, she remembers a lot of kids were bored and didn’t have activities to do, and she would see boys who lived in the streets of Nairobi harassing tourists all the time. So Wambui grew a heart to see things change for the youth in her village. She wanted to help the world change.\n\nWhen she grew up, Wambui moved to Oregon and started volunteering and working with different organizations such as Portland Rescue Mission and Cascade AIDS Project. “God was preparing me for what I am doing now,” Wambui says.\n\nToday, Wambui volunteers with a program called Books for the World through the <a title=\"Books for the World\" href=\"http://www.rotarybooksfortheworld.org\" target=\"_blank\">Beaverton Rotary Club</a>, in addition to owning her own catering company called Spice of Africa. Books for the World is part of the international service activities of Rotary International, and is dedicated to providing educational materials for developing countries so children can grow their literacy and language skills. The program makes use of supplies, textbooks, and other books that would otherwise be disposed of. Volunteers collect and sort books from educational facilities, libraries, school districts, and other sources to be packed and shipped to developing countries.\n\nWhen Wambui returned to Kenya for a visit, the village was the same as when she left. “So I decided to do something about it,” she said. She started an international missional community at Westside, with her friend Vawn McCollum, who also attends Westside, and a family was formed. Together, they started a project called “Feed the Village” and have been working to gather and pack supplies for the proposed library and community center. Their kids Makayla and Shayla volunteer as well, selling popcorn at markets and neighborhoods to raise much needed funds.\n\nGod has provided extravagantly in the community’s efforts to gather supplies for Kenya. In September Wambui’s Rotary team shipped 40,000 books to Gachie, Kenya to distribute the books to local schools in Gachie village. “How else could that be possible if it was not for God?” Wambui says. “To say the least I am amazed.”\n\nIn addition to the community library, an even bigger project is to economically uplift the community on a sustainable level by developing the community center where people can volunteer, learn, sell produce, join a sewing program, and ultimately bring money back to the village. So far there has been a great deal of support through donations of fabric and resources. “God has really blessed this project,” Wambui says.\n\nBeaverton Rotary volunteer; Wendi and Laura Cooksey will join and travel with Wambui and Makayla to set up the library and community center. While the Machua’s will be gone for 4 months, the Cooksey’s will be in Kenya for 3 weeks. The team has a wealth of donated fabric and is still raising money to develop the center, which needs tables, shelves, lamps, and chairs.\n\nTo support this project, you can pray for this team that leaves Thursday, December 3<sup>rd</sup>. “Ask for God to keep providing and go ahead of us,” Wambui asks. Originally planning to be in Kenya by now, Wambui postponed her trip to raise the money to release the shipment of 40,000 books that\'s still being held in customs in Kenya. If you\'d like to contribute to help get these books into the hands of those who need them, please consider donating to the <a title=\"community center fund\" href=\"https://www.gofundme.com/19bph4\" target=\"_blank\">Gachie Community Center Fund</a>!\n\nThe team is also looking for librarians and seamstresses to help them complete their projects in Kenya. Internet access will be unpredictable, but if you’re interested in joining the team for any length of time, you can send Wambui Machua an <a href=\"mailto:buifab@yahoo.com\" target=\"_blank\">email</a>.\n\nYou can read more about the community’s activities with “Feed the Village” and “Books for the World” on Wambui’s <a title=\"Spice of Africa\" href=\"http://spiceofafrica.com\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>.\n\n&nbsp;','Missional Community Supports Literacy and Economic Development in Gachie, Kenya','','trash','closed','closed','','missional-community-gathers-books-and-supplies-to-support-literacy-and-economic-development-in-gachie-kenya__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:28:40','2016-07-19 06:28:40','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1957',0,'post','',0),(1958,4,'2016-01-27 11:21:55','2016-01-27 19:21:55','','i_believe','','inherit','open','open','','i_believe','','','2016-01-27 11:21:55','2016-01-27 19:21:55','',1877,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2016/01/i_believe.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1960,4,'2016-01-27 11:27:35','2016-01-27 19:27:35','','spirit_disciplnes','','inherit','open','open','','spirit_disciplnes','','','2016-01-27 11:27:35','2016-01-27 19:27:35','',1877,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2016/01/spirit_disciplnes.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1962,4,'2016-01-27 12:03:58','2016-01-27 20:03:58','','saturate','','inherit','open','open','','saturate','','','2016-01-27 12:03:58','2016-01-27 20:03:58','',1877,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2016/01/saturate.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1964,4,'2016-01-27 12:10:55','2016-01-27 20:10:55','','celebration_discipline','','inherit','open','open','','celebration_discipline','','','2016-01-27 12:10:55','2016-01-27 20:10:55','',1877,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2016/01/celebration_discipline.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1966,4,'2016-01-27 12:13:41','2016-01-27 20:13:41','','how_not_to_be','','inherit','open','open','','how_not_to_be','','','2016-01-27 12:13:41','2016-01-27 20:13:41','',1877,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2016/01/how_not_to_be.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1968,4,'2016-01-27 12:15:53','2016-01-27 20:15:53','','simply_good_news','','inherit','open'