6.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'https://player.vimeo.com/video/112950972\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<hr />\r\n<h1>Christ is Born (EP)</h1>\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 30px 0 0\"]<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1822\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_album_christisborn.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" />[/one_third][two_third_last]On an unassuming night over two thousand years ago, God appeared; not as a heavenly warrior, or an intangible spirit, or a terrifying force of nature, but as a baby. A small, frail, human baby born to two teenagers in a cave. Through this child, the unknown God became known. The invisible God became visible. These songs are a celebration of that story.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/christ-is-born-ep/id1053951293\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on iTunes</a>[/page_actions][/two_third_last]\r\n<h1>Realms of Glory (Single)</h1>\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 30px 0 0\"]<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1887\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_realmsofglory_single.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" />[/one_third][two_third_last]Realms of Glory is a beautiful telling of the story of God and how he stepped into human history. It is written as a call to worship for all followers of Jesus to come and worship him.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/realms-of-glory-single/id947134754\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on iTunes</a><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Realms-Glory-Jesus-Church/dp/B00QN84NZG/ref=sr_1_5?s=dmusic&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1417991352&amp;sr=1-5&amp;keywords=A+Jesus+Church\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on Amazon</a>[/page_actions][/two_third_last]\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Credits</h3>\r\n<font size=\"3\">Evan Wickham: Vocals, Acoustic Guitars, Piano\r\nEric Lemiere: Drums, Guitars, Bass, Keys\r\nMichael Watson: Vocals\r\nWhitney DePaoli: Vocals\r\nMatthew Zigenis: Vocals, Guitars\r\nSandy Wickham: Vocals\r\nMadison Cunningham: Vocals\r\nKevin Kostanko: Drums\r\nAllison Bote: Piano\r\nPeter Hong: Guitars\r\nNick DePartee: Guitars\r\nHoratiu Titerlea: Guitars\r\nBen Peterson: Bass\r\nAnthony Maerz: Drums\r\n\r\nProducer: Eric Lemiere\r\n\r\nMixed / Mastered: Chris Greely\r\n\r\nSongs: Christ is Born and Realms of Glory written by Evan Wickham & Eric Lemiere.\r\n\r\nVideo Production: Josh Porter\r\nCameras: Garrett Holmes, Patrick Porter, Abi Porter\r\n\r\nGraphic Design: Tyler Hanns\r\n</font>','Christ is Born','','publish','closed','closed','','christ-is-born','','','2016-07-18 20:36:58','2016-07-19 04:36:58','',2408,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=2415',0,'page','',0),(2416,50,'2016-07-18 20:20:22','2016-07-19 04:20:22','','ajc_music_christmas_hero-1622x690','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_music_christmas_hero-1622x690','','','2016-07-18 20:20:22','2016-07-19 04:20:22','',2415,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_music_christmas_hero-1622x690.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2417,50,'2016-07-18 20:24:33','2016-07-19 04:24:33','','ajc_album_christisborn','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_album_christisborn','','','2016-07-18 20:24:33','2016-07-19 04:24:33','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_album_christisborn.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2418,50,'2016-07-18 20:26:19','2016-07-19 04:26:19','','ajc_realmsofglory_single','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_realmsofglory_single','','','2016-07-18 20:26:19','2016-07-19 04:26:19','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_realmsofglory_single.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2419,50,'2016-07-18 20:51:43','2016-07-19 04:51:43','<h1>Gloria</h1>\r\n[one_third padding=\"0 30px 0 0\"]<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1878\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_gloria.jpg\" width=\"1600\" height=\"1600\" />[/one_third][two_third_last]We are excited to release classic Christmas music with a modern sound. This is the collaborative effort of talented artist recapturing the beauty and sentiment of great Christmas music. Tracks also include new and original songs.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/gloria/id762971131\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on iTunes</a>[/page_actions]\r\n[/two_third_last]\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Credits</h3>\r\n<font size=\"3\">Bobby Strand: Vocals, Guitars, Piano & Keyboard, Drums & Percussion\r\nChris Greely: Vocals, Guitars, String Arrangements, Piano & Keyboard, Drums & Percussion\r\nMatthew Wilcox: Guitars, String Arrangements, Piano & Keyboard, Drums & Percussion\r\nTim Aylward: Vocals, Piano & Keyboard\r\nLindsey Strand: Vocals\r\nBrandon Mosser: Vocals\r\nPeter Hong: Guitars\r\nBen Peterson: Bass\r\nBrook Mosser: Drums & Percussion\r\nRyan Peterson: Drums & Percussion\r\n\r\nThe First Christmas Morning: Lyrics by Bobby Strand, Chris Greely\r\nGod’s Perfect Son: Lyrics by Bobby Strand, Chris Greely, Matthew Wilcox\r\n\r\nArrangements: Chris Greely, Bobby Strand, Matthew Wilcox, Tim Aylward\r\n\r\nStudio: Supernatural Sound, The Woods\r\n\r\nMixed / Mastered: The Woods\r\n\r\nCommunications Project Management: Fallon Lessler\r\n\r\nGraphic Design: Jordon Burnside\r\n\r\nProduction Design: Tyler Hanns\r\n</font>','Gloria','','publish','closed','closed','','gloria','','','2016-07-18 20:51:43','2016-07-19 04:51:43','',2408,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=2419',0,'page','',0),(2420,50,'2016-07-18 20:46:02','2016-07-19 04:46:02','','ajc_gloria-150x150','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_gloria-150x150-2','','','2016-07-18 20:46:02','2016-07-19 04:46:02','',2419,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_gloria-150x150.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2421,50,'2016-07-18 20:47:33','2016-07-19 04:47:33','','ajc_music_gloria_hero-1622x690','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_music_gloria_hero-1622x690','','','2016-07-18 20:47:33','2016-07-19 04:47:33','',2419,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_music_gloria_hero-1622x690.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2422,50,'2016-07-18 20:51:01','2016-07-19 04:51:01','','ajc_gloria','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_gloria','','','2016-07-18 20:51:01','2016-07-19 04:51:01','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_gloria.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2423,50,'2016-07-18 20:55:55','2016-07-19 04:55:55','<h1>Realms of Glory (Single)</h1>\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'http://player.vimeo.com/video/112950972\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\nRealms of Glory is a fresh and exciting Christmas single. \r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/realms-of-glory-single/id947134754\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on iTunes</a> <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Realms-Glory-Jesus-Church/dp/B00QN84NZG/ref=sr_1_5?s=dmusic&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1417991352&amp;sr=1-5&amp;keywords=A+Jesus+Church\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on Amazon</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n<h3>Credits</h3>\r\n','Realms of Glory','','publish','closed','closed','','realms-of-glory','','','2016-07-18 20:55:55','2016-07-19 04:55:55','',2408,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=2423',0,'page','',0),(2424,50,'2016-07-18 20:55:15','2016-07-19 04:55:15','','ajc_realms_hero_-1622x690','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_realms_hero_-1622x690','','','2016-07-18 20:55:15','2016-07-19 04:55:15','',2423,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_realms_hero_-1622x690.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2426,6,'2014-09-22 11:05:49','2014-09-22 18:05:49','Leaf through <a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com\" target=\"_blank\">our website</a> for a couple of seconds and you\'ll discover that we\'re big on this whole \"on Earth as it is in Heaven\" thing. Not only was this <a href=\"http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matt.6.9-Matt.6.10&amp;version=NIV\" target=\"_blank\">the prayer of Jesus</a> himself, this is the crux of our church family. With Jesus, we pray and work to the same end: To see God\'s will—that is, beauty, justice, generosity, and the like—done in our neighborhoods, in our cities, and in our world.\r\n\r\nThis is what we pray for, and this is what we work toward.\r\n\r\nSo... Why blog? In what way does something like a brief article on a website contribute to accomplishing God\'s ends on earth?\r\n\r\nThe mission of Jesus is quite an undertaking. And while the ultimate destiny of the cosmos—a world restored and made right by Jesus—does not hinge on a church staff, efficient communication, or a website, these small and imperfect factors can act as contributions to the greater good none the less.\r\n\r\nNot unlike the gift of a few bucks or a volunteer who sweeps a floor, many \"small\" pieces populate the whole. This blog will host a myriad of observations, discussions, passing thoughts, unraveled questions, and simple stories. A story about a <a href=\"http://youtu.be/7aERQc2LzFY\" target=\"_blank\">home for children in India</a>, or a story about a Missional Community <a href=\"http://youtu.be/SmnpNttMonQ\" target=\"_blank\">hosting a farmer\'s market</a> are both voices in the perpetually unfolding story of the Kingdom of God.\r\n\r\nThe <em>now</em> and the <em>not yet. </em>Where God\'s will <em>is</em> being done on Earth, and where it isn\'t. At least not yet.\r\n\r\nIn dialogue and discussion, we hope to learn, to grow, and to know Jesus better. In stories, the people of God set foot in Jesus\' redemptive story, and the renewal of all things. A blog is, of course, a very rudimentary, unspectacular thing. But stories, conversations, questions... These are wonderful, crucial things.\r\n\r\nIt\'s our hope that this simple blog might become a catalyst for things much bigger. For God\'s will done on Earth as it is in Heaven.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Why a church blog?','','publish','closed','closed','','why-a-church-blog','','','2016-07-19 05:52:03','2016-07-19 13:52:03','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=425',0,'post','',0),(2427,16,'2014-09-29 13:41:06','2014-09-29 20:41:06','<p style=\"text-align: center\">\"<em>Few delights can equal the mere presence of one whom we trust utterly.</em>\"</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">-George MacDonald</p>\nWhat will the story of your marriage be 50 years from now? How would you like it to be told? When is the last time you dreamed about that? Do you believe the Father has a big idea about your union? If you were asked to describe that “big idea” for your marriage, what would you say?\n\nYour story has a bigger context than you might imagine. Since before the first Garden to beyond the future one, your narrative sits beautifully within God\'s story. Did you realize that your marriage and the Gospel of Jesus are connected? When God invented marriage, he already had the saving work of Jesus in mind. Marriage has always been part of his big idea for wholeness and beauty, grace and justice, love and redemption, Gospel and Kingdom. God\'s aim is to reflect who he is to the world He loves. Marriage is a part of that.\n\nFor Abraham and Sarah, God called them beyond themselves, into his great narrative. It was about God being with them, his lasting covenant, a miraculous provision, more descendants than they could count, and all the nations who would be blessed forever. \"But that was <em>them</em>,\" you might be saying to yourself now.\n\nIf you could be transported out five decades from this day, to look back at this moment from fifty years into the future, what do you hope to see? Children, grandchildren, great grandchildren, their spouses, and children, loving each other, loving Jesus, blessing the nations? How would that feel?\n\nSolomon said<em>, “</em>The end of a matter is better than it’s beginning” (Ecclesiastes 7:8).\n\nI would argue, the most important day of your marriage is the last day. By God’s grace will the last day be a day to rejoice in a life lived together, and remembering the gift your spouse was to you in this life?\n\nSo here’s a suggestion: why not be intentional and <strong>reverse-engineer your marriage</strong>…from 50 years out? Take some time together this fall to ink your path; to “choose your ruts” for a life without regrets, a life not just with the two of you, but the three of you. Your story in Jesus\' story.\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">\"<em>Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and your plans will be</em> <em>established</em>.\"</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center\">–Proverbs 16:3</p>','A View From Then','','trash','closed','closed','','a-view-from-then__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:30:11','2016-07-19 06:30:11','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=443',0,'post','',0),(2428,19,'2014-09-24 17:29:35','2014-09-25 00:29:35','Every year, dozens of churches across the greater Portland area come together for seven days of prayer and fasting for our collective cities. Prayer, for the most part, we can wrap our minds around. We talk to God. We petition him for change in our neigborhoods, for suffering and injustice to be brought to an end, for healing, for hope.\r\n\r\nBut why fast?\r\n\r\nFasting is a way to tune into God’s heart and feel what he feels about the state of your city and your world.\r\n\r\nIn his excellent book <i>Fasting</i>, New Testament scholar Scot McKnight writes,\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">“<em>At the very core of fasting is empathy with the divine or participation in God’s perception of a sacred moment. When someone dies, God is grieved; when someone sins, particularly egregiously, God is grieved; when a nation is threatened, God is grieved. We could provide more examples. The point is this: fasting identifies with God’s perspective and grief in a sacred moment. Fasting enables us to identify with how God views a given event; fasting empowers us to empathize with God</em>.”</p>\r\nIn the Scriptures, there’s a time for fasting, and a time for <em>feasting</em>.\r\n\r\nThere are times in life when the only appropriate response is to eat and drink – a birthday, an anniversary, a wedding, Christmas day, etc.\r\n\r\nBut there are other times, when the only appropriate response is to go without food. When eating would be almost sacrilegious. The death of a loved one. The threat of war. The rise of sex trafficking.\r\n\r\nWhy Seven? Because when we see our cities, we realize there’s a lot to celebrate – to eat and drink over. And there’s a lot to grieve – to fast and pray over.\r\n\r\nThere’s so much that is not “on earth as it is in heaven”.\r\n\r\nAnd so we pray, and we fast.\r\n\r\nWe want God to flood our collective imagination with a vision not of what is, but of what could be. Of our city as it <em>could</em><em> </em>be. Of the word <em>as it could be</em>.\r\n\r\nWhat do you see when you open your imagination to the Spirit of God, and you dream in line with Jesus’ kingdom vision? Whatever you see, this week, pray towards that.\r\n\r\nAnd as a result, our hope is that God’s kingdom, his life-giving, healing presence comes to earth as it is in heaven.\r\n\r\n<strong>For more on fasting we recommend these excellent books:</strong> <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0875085555/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0875085555&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=joshdiescom-20&amp;linkId=2LS2QA3DOZRCTMCE\" target=\"_blank\"><em>God\'s Chosen Fast: A Spiritual and Practical Guide to Fasting</em></a>, by Arthur Wallis and <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0030EG10Q/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=B0030EG10Q&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=joshdiescom-20&amp;linkId=MYWKP3YA4YG6L76L\" target=\"_blank\"><em>Fasting: The Ancient Practices</em></a>, by Scot McKnight.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','A time to feast and a time to fast.','','publish','closed','closed','','a-time-to-feast-and-a-time-to-fast','','','2016-07-19 05:51:59','2016-07-19 13:51:59','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=449',0,'post','',0),(2429,20,'2014-10-01 09:00:46','2014-10-01 16:00:46','A small, young woman holds a cardboard sign outside Voodoo Doughnuts. She’s asking for money to buy a bus ticket. Instead of ignoring the woman, Jenna Forstrom points to the lit-up, big, red letters that spell out Union Gospel Mission just a few blocks away. They give out bus ticket vouchers, Jenna explains to the woman, encouraging her to go there and get her name on the list. Jenna invites the homeless woman to come to the Burnside Bridge in an hour or so, where a hot meal will be served. The young woman is grateful.\r\n\r\nThe popular doughnut shop is attached to Liberation Street Church where Night Strike leaders and volunteers meet up every Thursday evening. Night Strike is a humanitarian effort to reach out to the homeless and vulnerable in downtown Portland. After making peanut butter and jelly sandwiches, hot chocolate, and coffee, the group heads under the Burnside Bridge, where roughly 300 homeless guests wait for volunteers such as Jenna. Resources like sleeping bags, socks, and hygiene products are handed out to anyone who asks.  Guests can get their haircut, nails painted and feet washed as well, while other volunteers canvas the streets of Portland with prayer and “walkabout bags” of food, coffee and socks for those who have already staked their place for the night.\r\n\r\nThe weekly dinner—now is in its tenth year of existence—has also caught The Oregonian’s attention, highlighting that Night Strike provides a hot meal with dignity. “Loving people because people matter” is the foundation for Night Strike. It\'s when people choose to spend every Thursday evening to love people and to let them know they matter.\r\n\r\nWhen Jenna moved downtown, she saw a huge homeless population, but was unsure of how to get involved.  She then learned that Night Strike was happening just blocks from her apartment, and decided to go one night. Since that night, she has been volunteering (and is now on the leadership team). Jenna has been keeping track of outreach projects on her blog, <a href=\"http://beyondthebridgepdx.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Beyond the Bridge</a>.  The blog primarily focuses around fundraising for a mobile medical clinic to be used by Night Strike, a project Bridgetown Church has supported financially. Jenna always has her ears open to medical donations, doctors and nurses who want to give back and those you want to donate financially.\r\n\r\nOnce the A Jesus Church Family started communicating the idea of missional communities — mission, family, and discipleship — Jenna knew she couldn’t add more to her schedule each week. Her friends at Night Strike felt the same way.\r\n\r\nBut then they learned that this merge <strong><em>is</em></strong> missional community,\r\n\r\n“We were already on mission to the homeless and marginalized and attended Bridgetown. We became a missional community after the fact,” says Jenna.  “We were already doing what Bridgetown was talking about, just not calling it a missional community.  Now when we are talking to the Church we use the same language, it breaks down barriers for us.”\r\n\r\nAfter Night Strike is over, and Liberation Street Church has been cleared, Jenna and her friends head over to Fire on the Mountain, a local chicken wing joint. The rest of the night is spent hanging out and catching up.\r\n\r\n“Personally, I believe that everyone should be volunteering in some sort of capacity. Just like I believe that everyone should take good care of their bodies. So I look at Night Strike, as my weekly work out,” says Jenna, a former college athlete. “Yes, getting up the next day can be rough and sometimes you bring home baggage, but I feel like I was made for this work. I think God lights me up at Night Strike. And with the Holy Spirit, it hasn’t ever really been a burden. Plus, God calls us to serve the poor and carry one another\'s burdens so it just makes sense to me.”\r\n\r\nBut Night Strike isn\'t localized into Thursday nights per se.  During the summer and spring breaks, Jenna and her missional community lead middle through college-age groups around Portland for Walkabouts, giving them the opportunity to engage and serve with Portland’s homeless. On Saturdays during the summer, most of Jenna’s missional community volunteers with BTownKids, a low-income kids program.\r\n\r\n“We also just get together, hang out, text, share and check in on one another through the week,” Jenna says.\r\n\r\nIn other words, they do life together.\r\n\r\n“I think Satan is really good at telling people that if we act out in faith, we’ll get hurt. Night Strike is the perfect example of how untrue that fear is,” she says, “Then there are friendships that I’ve made under the Bridge. Plus, having volunteers and kids come up and have their worlds completely messed up (in a good way) after spending a night volunteering is always great.”\r\n\r\nNight Strike is about noticing when a guest arrives and handing them a hot cup of coffee. It’s giving them a bowl of soup and bread.  It’s about eye contact and conversation.  Listening and offering support, compassion and grace.  It’s realizing that a man has a cut on his hand, so you offer to clean it as you place his hand in a bowl of warm water and hunt down some gauze and medical tape.\r\n\r\n“God lives in community and we were designed to be in community,” Jenna says, “It only makes sense.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Written by Michelle Grimms</em>','Dignity for the Homeless','','publish','closed','closed','','dignity-for-the-homeless','','','2016-07-19 05:48:55','2016-07-19 13:48:55','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=489',0,'post','',0),(2430,8,'2014-10-08 09:00:24','2014-10-08 16:00:24','<h1 style=\"color: #000000;\"></h1>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Have you ever read through the story of Job? It’s a tough one to get through, much less enjoy. But even still, I was reading it again recently and felt like God wanted to remind our church, especially our young people, of three things. Each is a simple and elementary truth, a part of the reality we live in, but if forgotten can lead to a distortion of who we think God is and how we see ourselves.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Let’s be honest, things often happen that are so far outside of what we want that our default emotional response is to wonder “Why?”</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">We may find words slipping from our lips like,</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\"><em>\"Is this really happening? God where are you!?” </em>Convinced that God is hiding, absent, or unaware of what we’re going through.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Or, <em>”God, why is this happening?” </em>Demanding a response from the one who\'s apparently ruining our life plans, our security, and our comfort completely unaware of how it\'s affecting us.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Or, <em>”How could you let this happen!?”</em> we can angrily mumble assuming all blame rightfully belongs to him.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">No matter how we say it, most of us know at least a variant of what <em>those </em>moments feels like, “God, <em>why</em>?”</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I remember years back dating a beautiful girl named Hillary. I\'d saved up the cash for a ring, thought through every possible scenario of how to pop the question and then the Spirit spoke something very specific to me. I’ve learned that <strong>God speaks to us in ways we can understand </strong>and when he spoke, I listened, but listening and obeying are two completely separate things.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">He said, \"Nate, let her go\".</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">But I wasn\'t about to just let her go, she was everything to me. Looking back, I believe was the very issue he was addressing; idolatry. But as the next 18 months unfolded I found myself collapsing under the pain of doing life my way while knowing full well what obeying God looked like.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I\'d open the Scriptures and he\'d bring me back to what he wanted me to do.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I\'d be worshiping him through song and he\'d whisper the same thing He said months earlier.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I\'d ask for him to speak, hoping that He\'d say something different, something else, so that I could just move on from the haunting phrase, “let her go,” that one thing I wouldn\'t do.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I was disobeying God and I knew it. I could feel it.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">And what I quickly learned was that God wasn\'t about to give me something else until I followed through with what I\'d already been told to do.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">So finally after 18 months of running I hit a very low point. There was no longer any joy in reading the Scriptures, no \"fresh words\" from the Spirit, and no peace in pursuing Hillary, so we called it off. We cried (let\'s be honest, I cried like a baby, Hillary held it together pretty well) and all that comes along with a relational severing, but that pain of letting her go was so heavy that I let it trump staying in the love of God. The next year and half was by far the darkest time of my life.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I\'d cry all the time, uncontrollably; it didn’t matter where I was. At home, driving, parked in a random parking lot, and even at work.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">On a number of occasions I\'d fuel the sadness by breathing quick short breaths that eventually led to blacking out. Make no mistake, I was very much in that place of, \"<em>why</em> God?\" Deep down I was expecting that when I did what he said, some switch would flip and everything would be easy, but that\'s far from what happened, at least immediately. I waited and waited for God to say with a smile, \"well done! Now that you’ve obeyed, you can have her back!\" I was sure that\'s what God would do, but that\'s not what he said. In fact he was silent. For a long time.  For us, it took another 18 months apart, God teaching both of us a ton, and then bringing us back together, but that included a whole lot of asking, \"why?\"</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">I\'m not David, but I bet he felt a similar emotion when he wrote out Psalm 42:5.</p>\n\n<blockquote style=\"font-style: italic; color: #000000;\">Why, my soul, are you downcast? Why so disturbed within me? Put your hope in God, for I will yet praise him, my Savior and my God.</blockquote>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Whatever it is for you, a death of someone close, a loss, a need that seems endless... the list goes on, <strong>don\'t lose hope.</strong></p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">God gave humanity a book to help us know what he\'s like and to realign our thinking with reality. It\'s in this book that God gives us a picture of what he\'s like in his relationship with us; a Father. Among many reasons, I think it may be helpful for us to be reminded of three elementary truths about fathers, each of which gets twisted when we find ourselves in the “<em>God, why?”</em> place.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">First, in bullet points for all the type A people like me.</p>\n\n<h3 style=\"color: #000000;\"><strong>1</strong>. <strong>A father is older than their son/daughter</strong>.</h3>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Pretty basic right? But this is where we need to start. Remembering, for simplicity sake, that God has been around longer than us. This is key for a mainly psychological reason. We\'re his kids. Never loose that reality.</p>\n\n<blockquote style=\"font-style: italic; color: #000000;\">See what great love the Father has lavished on us, that we should be called children of God! And that is what we are! 1 John 3:1a</blockquote>\n<h3 style=\"color: #000000;\"></h3>\n<h3 style=\"color: #000000;\">2. A father knows more than their son/daughter.</h3>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Not only is a father older, but because he\'s older, He knows more. He has a perspective that his kids don\'t yet have and knows what\'s best even when they disagree with him as they draw a conclusion from their limited (and much younger) perspective.</p>\n\n<blockquote style=\"font-style: italic; color: #000000;\">You asked, ‘Who is this that obscures my plans without knowledge?’ Surely I spoke of things I did not understand, things too wonderful for me to know. Job 42:3</blockquote>\n<h3 style=\"color: #000000;\"></h3>\n<h3 style=\"color: #000000;\">3. A father\'s character doesn\'t change because of how we feel.</h3>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">A father\'s character doesn’t change based on the momentary understanding held by the child. If a son/daughter thinks something of their father then changes their mind, it doesn\'t change who their father is.</p>\n\n<blockquote style=\"font-style: italic; color: #000000;\">Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever. Hebrews 13:8</blockquote>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Now in story form… same points, but another way to grasp it.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">In our kitchen there\'s a sink under a big tall window. To the right of the sink are four leg level drawers. The second drawer from the floor is where we keep the knives. Now, let\'s say we have our friends over for tacos and they bring their son over who\'s recently learned to walk. As the four of us sit in the living room their son stumbles into the kitchen and makes his way to the drawers. There\'s a doorway between the two rooms which allows you to see from one room to another. The young boy unknowingly pulls open the knife drawer but can\'t see what\'s inside so begins to reach in. The knives have recently been sharpened and we don\'t have a knife block so they\'re neatly laid out in the drawer. If you don\'t watch where you\'re grabbing you\'ll get cut pretty bad (anyone want to buy us a knife block?) Now, the boy is seconds away from making contact, he\'s interested, not even quite sure what he\'s doing. Our friend, the father, looks up just as his sons hand disappears into the drawer and yells out, rushing through the doorway and with his arm around his son quickly rips him away from the drawer which causes immediate fear, confusion, and even anger in the boy.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Pause.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">What\'s the boy thinking?</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">What’s he feeling?</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">From his perspective, his entire world just changed in an instant and it wasn’t a comfortable shock either, in-fact it’s probably the last thing he’d have expected much less wanted to happen.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">If he could put words to the moment they may sound something like, \"What\'s going on?\" \"It hurts to get pulled away,\" and ultimately the question, \"<em>w</em><em>hy</em> is this happening!?\"</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">We know the dad is older, the dad is smarter, and even if the boy assumes his dad is a jerk in that moment it doesn\'t change the fact that he\'s not one. Rather, he loves his son enough that he\'s willing to not explain something in the moment in order to save him from something far worse. No wonder Jesus teaches us to relate to God as Father (this example is one of many reasons).</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Is it possible that over and over God teaches us to call him Father so that we\'d remember that even when we\'re confused, hurt, and asking <em>why,</em> we\'d remember that he is older, knows more, and his character is unchanging?</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Being able to call God <em>Father</em> is relational glue when arguments and reasoning don\'t work and we\'re so caught up in <em>those</em> moments.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Life stuff happens. Hard stuff. And while <strong>it will pass</strong>, it can often feel like forever. So the next time you find yourself <em>there, </em>right in middle of it, remember that God is your Father and that he’s <em>for</em> you. The Scriptures say he\'s a good father and that if he didn’t even withhold his only Son from us then why would he hold back any other good thing? He\'ll meet our needs, you can take that to the bank, it\'s a promise.</p>\n\n<h3 style=\"color: #000000;\">May we learn the art of...</h3>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Grieving well and living fully in the reality that God is with us.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Learning to be still in pain, trusting that God knows more.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">And of allowing the Healer to heal us even when we don\'t understand.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #000000;\">Jude sums it up so well when he says, “…keep yourselves in the love of the God…” (1:21). Let’s be a people who are constantly reminding ourselves and those around us about the love our Father has for us. For it’s when we begin to grasp his love that everything changes. Especially when we’re in <em>those </em>places.</p>','God, why is this happening?','','trash','closed','closed','','god-why-is-this-happening__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:30:11','2016-07-19 06:30:11','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=498',0,'post','',0),(2431,21,'2014-10-03 09:00:35','2014-10-03 16:00:35','It’s been a hard few months. Not just for me, but for the people that I love. It’s a weird thing, pain. It’s unpredictable and wild. It makes us sad and mad all at the same time. It can lay dormant for years and yet in a single moment blaze like a wild fire. For better or worse, it seems that pain always has a way of giving birth to something else. It’s impatient and impertinent, demanding a response and never being satisfied with the answer.\r\n\r\nThese past few months have been laced with encounters of loss, pain, and grief. Though not my own, they are still more than I care to recount. Pain is funny that way, it never affects <em>one</em> person alone. It’s like dominos. You can’t hit one without hitting them all. It can be a disorienting thing; listening to the frustration, pain, and petitions of my friends that search for relief, only to find more heartache and disappointment. I try desperately, searching my heart and mind, to find adequate words, scriptures, and promises that could and should bring comfort, only to hear myself blurt out cliché sayings found on the doilies and plaques at the Christian Book Store. Insult to injury.\r\n\r\nThere is only one word to describe all that I’ve been experiencing; one word that I felt I could attach to every tear shed, every harsh word revealed. It seems that with every coffee shared, every phone call received, I could feel it rise up through my chest and into my mouth. I felt like I could almost taste it.\r\n\r\n“Mara.”\r\n\r\nMara is a word that occurs only once in the whole of the Scriptures. It’s a word Naomi—a key character found in the book of Ruth—called herself after she lost both her husband and two sons. I’ve never particularly been drawn to Naomi in years past. I understood why she called herself this strange word in the most generic way, but I always thought it was a bit dramatic. Until recently.\r\n\r\nThe Hebrew word, “mara” means “bitter,” which allows you to appreciate why I thought Naomi was being dramatic. After further study, I learned something new; something that changed my view on Naomi and her pain, as well as the pain of the people around me.\r\n\r\nBuried deep within its definition, \"mara” carries with it the implication of<em> strength</em>. Strength? Out of bitterness? The two seem to contradict each other. We see it growing in Naomi as her story is told, only to be completely revealed in the final chapter of the book, when she, surrounded by all who once saw her pain, is now blessed and affirmed as a woman of strength and valor. No longer marked by bitterness for she has been rescued and redeemed.\r\n\r\nAnd so, as I lean in close to those friends immersed—some even drenched—in the mara of the season, I too find something more. For some of my dear friends, the pain of this season has given birth to bitterness, but it has also given birth to something else; something more. It has given birth to s<em>trength</em>. I’ve learned a lot in the past few months, but the biggest lesson learned is that pain doesn\'t have to be <em>just</em> pain. It can be something more, though when you’re in the thick of it; it’s hard to believe that.\r\n\r\n<em>So for those that can’t believe during that season,</em> <em>it’s our job to believe for them.</em>\r\n\r\nAs followers of Jesus, we are told to “strengthen the feeble hands, (to) steady the knees that give way; (to) say to those with fearful hearts, \'Be strong, do not fear; your God will come, He will come with vengeance; with divine retribution He will come to save you.\'” (Is. 35:3-4). And so for those of us who today, are free from mara, may we be faithful to believe God for more, on behalf of our friends and family.  And for those who find themselves in the midst of the pain, may the bitterness of this season give way to the strength of the next.','Mara: Strength from bitterness.','','publish','closed','closed','','mara-strength-from-bitterness','','','2016-07-19 05:48:53','2016-07-19 13:48:53','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=505',0,'post','',0),(2432,22,'2014-10-23 14:29:04','2014-10-23 21:29:04','<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">I really didn\'t know what I was getting myself into when I kissed my husband goodbye at the airport then left to spend a week in Jacmel, Haiti. I was going with a team of eleven people from Westside Church, working with an organization called Restore Haiti. I hadn\'t met any of the other team members prior to signing up for the trip, and had never been on an international mission trip before. I only knew that I felt a tug on my heart to go to Haiti, and I hoped for the best.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">Landing in Port-au-Prince, Haiti\'s capital, brought on sensory overload. The city is still recovering from the devastating earthquake that struck in 2010, and the poverty and despair among the people made my stomach turn. Our team traveled three hours by van over the mountains to the town of Jacmel, a more rural area that\'s been heavily influenced by Christian missionaries. Our team had an instant sense of peace and hope as we pulled into town. We were greeted warmly by dozens of children who ran to the road waving and smiling as we drove by. We were struck by the joy of the people. Many of them were living in small homes without running water or electricity, and yet they seemed so much more content than your average American.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">During the week, we spent our mornings working at two different construction sites. At one site, team members built the foundation for the addition of a second story on a school. Over the course of three days, the project was nearly completed, and it was very rewarding to see the progress that was made. The other work site was a new home that was being built for a local family. In Jacmel, resources are limited, and all materials are truly made from scratch. We sifted dirt to remove all of the stones, and used the stones as fill where the floor of the home would be. We sifted the dirt again to separate the sand from the coarse dirt so that the materials could be used to make concrete and stucco. The home was not on a main road, so construction vehicles couldn\'t access the site; all materials were transported using shovels and buckets. It felt good to get our hands dirty and work hard, and the tasks were simple enough that everyone could be involved regardless of their background (or lack thereof) in construction. It was eye-opening to see how much Americans take for granted in terms of having resources and equipment readily available.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">Each afternoon we served at Restore Haiti\'s feeding program. Every day, <i>hundreds</i> of sponsored children arrive at the church for a hot meal, clean water, and vitamins. For many of them, this was their one meal for the day. On our last day, the team purchased a special meal of chicken legs and milk for the kids (to compliment their typical meal of rice and beans). This was a big hit, and it was awesome to see the smiles on their faces. During the week, our team helped with meal preparation, washing children\'s hands, serving the meal, washing dishes, and, of course, playing with and loving on the kids. The kids are so fearless and so happy! They showed us instant and unconditional love by holding our hands, sitting on our laps, playing with our hair, and inviting us to play with them. For many of us, this was the most rewarding part of the trip. The children showed us that our language barrier was irrelevant when you communicate with smiles, laughter, and hugs.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">In between projects and meals, we took every opportunity to “do life” with the Haitians (playing soccer, visiting their homes, taking them to the beach, including them in our evening devotion time, etc.). Many of the older children have learned to speak English in school and enjoyed conversing and interacting with our team. Giving them our time was such a simple way to show them Jesus\' love, and in return we were able to experience their culture and form friendships.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">The evenings were such a sweet time for our team, when we gathered together on the roof of our hotel for worship and bonding. The nights are so quiet and peaceful in Jacmel, and the night sky was so bright and beautiful. We would share our “highs and lows” from the day, and pray for and encourage each other. It was amazing to see how a group of total strangers with different backgrounds and life experiences could become like family in just eight days. It was exciting to watch each person grow and thrive over the course of the week.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">Returning home was as overwhelming and surreal as my arrival to Haiti. I was grateful for the wave of e-mails, text messages, and pictures that came from my team members as we supported each other through the transition, and for the enthusiasm of family members and friends  who wanted to hear about my trip. I am so thankful for the opportunity that I had to travel to Jacmel and serve with Restore Haiti.</p>\r\n<p class=\"Standard\" style=\"line-height: 150%;\">I went to serve and to bless only to find that <i>I</i> was the one who had been blessed.</p>','Hear The Cry: Haiti','','publish','closed','closed','','hear-the-cry-haiti','','','2016-07-19 05:38:38','2016-07-19 13:38:38','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=604',0,'post','',0),(2433,6,'2014-11-13 16:33:48','2014-11-14 00:33:48','<em>On November 12th, Bridgetown Church hosted the lecture, </em>Sweatshops, Justice, and the Way of Jesus<em>, given by Dr. Gerry Breshears and Josh Porter. <a href=\"http://bridgetown.ajesuschurch.org/teaching/sweatshops-justice/sweatshops-justice-and-the-way-of-jesus/\">The lecture is now available via the Bridgetown podcast</a>.</em>\r\n\r\nToday is a mere two weeks before the appropriately named “Black Friday.” Long before the Friday in question actually begins in the literal sense, consumers will have pitched tents outside of major retailers, enduring the rain and cold for days in the romantic hope of saving a few bucks on an Xbox. The sacrifice… The endurance… Chasing after that impossible dream. Black Friday is like the Olympics in that way.\r\n\r\nThese retailers will open their doors and institute elaborate systems—tickets, subcategorized lines, rain checks—to keep people from <em>dying</em>. Because the rabid fervor birthed from Black Friday anticipation actually leads to stampedes. Honest-to-God stampedes. Innocent shoppers being trampled to death. <em>Shootings</em>. People die on black Friday.\r\n\r\n‘Tis the shopping season.\r\n\r\nBut not all of us bring guns to Best Buy or are even remotely willing to walk over another human being in order to get our hands on a television. Even so, chances are, most of us will shop in the coming months. Most of us will shop more than usual.\r\n\r\nAnd if we manage to avoid the retail hamster wheel of the holiday season, we will, at some point, buy <em>something</em>. Food, entertainment… clothes. And as most of us—dare I say, <em>all</em> of us—do indeed shop, very few of us are privy to a glance behind the curtain in front of which these products sit.\r\n\r\nWhere did it come from? How did it get here? What does my purchase support?\r\n\r\nBut it isn’t with complete ignorance that we forego a peek behind the curtain. We’ve heard about injustice in the labor industry: stories about sweatshops in which children are forced to work grueling hours in deplorable conditions under the awful mastery of slave drivers. Factories that collapse and kill hundreds. Women that are trafficked into slavery in front of a sewing machine.\r\n\r\nBut we’ve heard other things as well. \"This company is bad, that company is good.\" \"It’s not as bad as it sounds.\" \"It’s better than no job at all.\" \"The industry is inherently flawed. No one can shop without <em>some </em>blood on their hands.\"\r\n\r\nAnd how much can we actually know? Do we even have reasonable access to a glance behind the curtain, or is it all hearsay? And if we <em>do</em> acquire any real data, then what? Can or should that information actually affect or change where and how we shop?\r\n\r\nFor those of us that are disciples of Jesus of Nazareth, <em>the</em> fundamental precept of our apprenticeship to Jesus is that we live out the way of Jesus. That we learn his teachings, that we make the way he thinks and sees the way that we think and see. That we become like Jesus. That we carry on his work in the world.\r\n\r\nAnd this is the presupposition out of which we’re working in this discussion. If our lives are indeed surrendered in their entirety to Jesus of Nazareth, this includes our choices as consumers. The church has been making better strides to speak out against the horrific plague of materialism here in America as it pertains to the way we handle our money, greed, excess, injustice. We’ve got a long, long way to go, but we’ve begun the conversation.\r\n\r\nA conversation we’ve yet to really broach is what goes on behind our purchases in terms of where it came from and how, and how we, as followers of Jesus, do or do not adjust the way we shop in light of this information.\r\n\r\nWith this in mind, Dr. Gerry Breshears and I set out to discuss a biblical paradigm for labor ethics, and how we might apply these principles to the way we shop today.\r\n\r\nListen to the lecture now on <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/podcast/midweek-lecture-sweatshops/id84246334?i=324985740&amp;mt=2\">iTunes</a> or <a href=\"http://bridgetown.ajesuschurch.org/teaching/sweatshops-justice/sweatshops-justice-and-the-way-of-jesus/\">Bridgetown Church teachings</a>.','Sweatshops, Justice, and the Way of Jesus','','publish','closed','closed','','sweatshops-justice-and-the-way-of-jesus','','','2016-07-19 04:50:58','2016-07-19 12:50:58','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=675',0,'post','',0),(2434,26,'2014-11-17 15:12:48','2014-11-17 23:12:48','<span style=\"color: #222222;\">We believe worship is a response to who God is. Yahweh has revealed himself in the person of Jesus, and has given us his Spirit to guide us through our lives. His Spirit has been stirring in our church in many new and exciting ways, and <em>Carry Your Name</em> is simply a response to the journey he has been taking us on in the Jesus Church Family over the last few years. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #222222;\">The songs on this record reflect what this church has been learning and walking in. Some of them come from personal experiences in life, and some come from where our church has been learning how to be disciples of Jesus. Ultimately, our greatest desire is to know Jesus, be known by Jesus, and make Jesus known to world. </span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #222222;\">We are called to carry His name to the ends of the earth, and these songs were written with that in mind.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #222222;\">When we first released <em>Carry Your Name </em>a year ago, our dream was and still is to create music that celebrates the goodness of Jesus. To further his fame while coloring with the unique shades of his involvement in our particular story. In a way, <em>Carry Your Name </em>represents the first fruits of that dream coming true.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #222222;\">\"Promoting\" a worship album is a funny thing. Certainly, there is no reason to celebrate our music or artistic endeavors over and against any other church. What we hope, quite simple, is that you might enjoy this album. If God uses these lyrics and arrangements to bless or speak to you in some way, well, that wouldn\'t be so bad either.</span>\r\n<p>\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; height: auto; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'http://www.youtube.com/embed/RcH9uDNuEm4\' frameborder=\'0\' allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\r\n</p><p>\r\nPurchase <em>Carry Your Name</em> from <a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/carry-your-name/id777133884#\" target=\"_blank\">iTunes</a> | <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00H6E9G62/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=B00H6E9G62&linkCode=as2&tag=joshdiescom-20&linkId=P24VJJMTPZGM7XTN\" target=\"_blank\">Amazon mp3</a> | or download the <a href=\"http://noisetrade.com/ajesuschurch/carry-your-name-ep\" target=\"_blank\">Noisetrade EP</a> for free.\r\n</p><p></p>','Carry Your Name','','publish','closed','closed','','carry-your-name','','','2016-07-19 04:51:13','2016-07-19 12:51:13','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=686',0,'post','',0),(2435,27,'2014-11-20 15:36:58','2014-11-20 23:36:58','Whether it\'s cliché or not, it seems clear from the beginning of time that God was in favor of <em>community</em> and <em>mission</em>. When Adam walked the earth in intimacy with God, what was God’s reply? He said that Adam was \"alone.\" From square one, God wanted humans to be in community. Then, after God made woman, he told the cute couple to cultivate the land, to take it somewhere, to bless the world. That was <em>mission</em>. It doesn’t matter what you call it, God wants community and he wants mission.\r\n\r\nSounds simple enough, right?\r\n\r\nThe reality is, while the <em>idea</em> may be simple, the <em>activity</em> is tough. It’s messy business dying to your self in order to follow Jesus in mission. It’s challenging reaching a place of vulnerability with other Jesus followers so that you can actually call them “brothers and sisters” because they know you so well. The process of what some call “missional community” is far from easy, especially when we hold our community in comparison to the mythical “ideal community.”\r\n\r\nI am 25. I long for the day when my wife and I have bought a home and settled in a neighborhood. Then we’ll make family of our fellow Jesus-loving neighbors and look to bless everyone in our cul-de-sac. That’s a couple years out though. At least.\r\n\r\nI am 25. I long for a missional community that includes a baby who cries, and half a dozen people over the age of 40 who could offer wisdom they’ve accumulated over the years. But that’s not happening no matter how hard I try.\r\n\r\nI am 25. That means I’m smack-dab in the middle of a generation that is, stereotypically, entitled (we want what’s best), and discontent (we don’t get what’s best). Even when it comes to following Jesus in community, we <em>compare</em>. I want the diversity of Todd’s community, the intimacy of Nate’s community, and the mission of Jake’s.\r\n\r\nForget how blessed I am, there’s always better.\r\n\r\nI\'m learning that. If we can’t find older folks to join our family, then we’ll have to begin without them. If we aren’t sure of a mission to join, then we’ll find one together. It may not all line up now, but it will eventually. That\'s the hope.\r\n\r\nThat\'s what others have done. I know of four different missional communities that have begun with exactly zero adults over 30. Zero ideas of a mission in mind. Few even had an obvious place to meet.\r\n\r\nWho cares? We’ll learn, right?\r\n\r\nAnd we have. We’ve come to find that the most important thing to a missional community is a family that loves one another. We’ve learned that mission isn’t always about what’s most important to <em>you</em>, but about seizing the opportunities that God lays in front of you (even if cleaning rooms at a DHS office isn’t something you’re “passionate” about).  We’ve seen that there’s something missing without generational diversity, but that doesn\'t mean our missional communities aren\'t incredible.\r\n\r\nI\'ve come to learn that we can always learn what the “ideal” is as it pertains to a missional community, but we may never achieve that ideal anyway. You can hint that we’re incomplete because nobody in our family wears diapers or is a grandparent. We can be questioned because we don’t all live in the same neighborhood, but we’re all going to move apartments in the next year anyway. At the end of the day, we’ll come right back to where we started. Jesus wants community and mission, no matter how “ideal” it is.\r\n\r\nCan a single-demographic group bless others? Yes.\r\n\r\nCan a group of 20 year-olds be a family? Yes. I’ll prove it to you. Come to my place this Monday at 7pm.','Are missional communities an impossible ideal?','','publish','closed','closed','','missional-community-the-impossible-ideal','','','2016-07-19 04:51:21','2016-07-19 12:51:21','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=713',0,'post','',0),(2436,22,'2014-12-11 10:42:44','2014-12-11 18:42:44','<em><span style=\"color: #525252;\">This year for our Hear the Cry giving catalogue we are putting a huge focus on child/student sponsorship. Throughout the Christmas season we’ll be highlighting each organization we work with here on the blog throughout the holiday season. Each blog will feature practical ways to get involved and to contribute financially. <a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/blog/christmas-justice/\" target=\"_blank\">For more information read Mike McDonald\'s letter and learn about Hear the Cry\'s work supporting children around the world.</a></span></em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/DSC_3749-e1418323287732.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-819\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/DSC_3749-e1418323287732.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_3749\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Remember Nhu’s</strong> mission is ending child sex slavery through prevention. Hear the Cry has Homes in both Myanmar and Thailand, and one of the best ways to partner in the work we do is to sponsor one of our kids. We also take teams each year to both countries so that sponsors can visit the kids they support.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://remembernhu.org/give.html\" target=\"_blank\">Find out more about Remember Nhu and how to sponsor a child</a>. </strong>\r\n\r\nPlease be sure to enter “A Jesus Church” under the Designate your gift information. This way someone from Remember Nhu will pair you up with one of our homes in Myanmar or Thailand.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/DSC_3899-e1418323218209.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-820\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/DSC_3899-e1418323218209.jpg\" alt=\"DSC_3899\" width=\"600\" height=\"400\" /></a>\r\n\r\n_________________\r\n<strong>Visit each of Hear The Cry\'s partnering organizations:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.thesenumbers.org/impact-circle\" target=\"_blank\">These Numbers Have Faces</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://remembernhu.org/give.html\" target=\"_blank\">Remember Nhu</a></strong> <strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">International: Girls Safe House</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engagesomalia/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Engage Somalia</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/restore-iraq-refugee-support/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Regufe Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engageiraq/\" target=\"_blank\">Sponsor a Child in Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://indiahappyhome.org/sponsor-a-child/\" target=\"_blank\">Happy Home for the Handicapped</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.lovingheartsbabies.com/#/home\" target=\"_blank\">Loving Hearts Baby Home</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://flyfishingcollaborative.org/give/\" target=\"_blank\">Nicaragua Fish Farm</a></strong>','Hear the Cry: Sponsor a Child Through Remember Nhu','','publish','closed','closed','','hear-the-cry-sponsor-a-child-through-remember-nhu','','','2016-07-19 04:18:15','2016-07-19 12:18:15','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=817',0,'post','',0),(2437,22,'2014-12-15 09:00:20','2014-12-15 17:00:20','<em><span style=\"color: #525252;\">This year for our Hear the Cry giving catalogue we are putting a huge focus on child/student sponsorship. Throughout the Christmas season we’ll be highlighting each organization we work with here on the blog throughout the holiday season. Each blog will feature practical ways to get involved and to contribute financially. <a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/blog/christmas-justice/\" target=\"_blank\">For more information read Mike McDonald\'s letter and learn about Hear the Cry\'s work supporting children around the world.</a></span></em>\r\n\r\nWe partner with <strong>Restore International</strong> to operate two safe houses in Kampala, Uganda for sexually exploited girls. The home is for them to come and live, find safety, as well as receive medical attention, counseling, and therapy. Here, they become part of a family. We help them get back in school, pay their school fees, and work to re-build their future.\r\n\r\nWe opened these homes to care for abused and sexually exploited underage girls. The goal is to provide a safe, caring environment for them to leave the sex trade—or other dangerous environments—and get care, counseling and safety. Additionally, our goal is to re-acclimate these girls into a structured, healthy lifestyle where they may heal from physical and emotional trauma and learn to take ownership of their lives, futures, educations, and vocational opportunities.\r\n\r\nThe home is staffed with mentors and counselors who visit the surrounding neighborhoods and identify minors being sexually exploited or otherwise abused. The mentors then approaches the minors and offers them a place to live. The girls enter the home voluntarily and are free to leave if they choose.\r\n\r\nEach home houses about 15-20 girls. Daily activities include responsibilities and chores, group meetings, crafts and hobbies, homework, therapy, and discussions. We take teams each year to Uganda to visit these homes.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">Find out more about the many of ways to give to the work being done there. </a>\r\n\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; height: auto; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'https://player.vimeo.com/video/55317712\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\n_________________\r\n<strong>Visit each of Hear The Cry\'s partnering organizations:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.thesenumbers.org/impact-circle\" target=\"_blank\">These Numbers Have Faces</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://remembernhu.org/give.html\" target=\"_blank\">Remember Nhu</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Girls Safe House</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engagesomalia/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Engage Somalia</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/restore-iraq-refugee-support/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Refugee Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engageiraq/\" target=\"_blank\">Sponsor a Child in Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://indiahappyhome.org/sponsor-a-child/\" target=\"_blank\">Happy Home for the Handicapped</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.lovingheartsbabies.com/#/home\" target=\"_blank\">Loving Hearts Baby Home</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://flyfishingcollaborative.org/give/\" target=\"_blank\">Nicaragua Fish Farm</a> </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Hear the Cry: Uganda Girls Safe House','','publish','closed','closed','','hear-the-cry-uganda-girls-safe-house','','','2016-07-19 04:02:16','2016-07-19 12:02:16','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=824',0,'post','',0),(2438,22,'2014-12-17 09:00:19','2014-12-17 17:00:19','<em><span style=\"color: #525252;\">This year for our Hear the Cry giving catalogue we are putting a huge focus on child/student sponsorship. Throughout the Christmas season we’ll be highlighting each organization we work with here on the blog throughout the holiday season. Each blog will feature practical ways to get involved and to contribute financially. <a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/blog/christmas-justice/\" target=\"_blank\">For more information read Mike McDonald\'s letter and learn about Hear the Cry\'s work supporting children around the world.</a></span></em>\r\n\r\nWe recently started working with <strong>Restore International in Somalia</strong> to improve human rights and education opportunities. If you\'d like to help make a huge difference in a child’s life in Mogadishu, sign up for a monthly pledge to support the education of a little girl from one of the many refugee camps.\r\n\r\nWe’re starting with the basics: food and education. $33 each month will go a long way in providing these necessities for the kids.\r\n\r\nRestore recently received a generous grant from Project 7 and 7-UP to ensure an education for these 100 girls, but our need now is to provide food for these kids and their classmates as well. Providing meals for the girls helps keep them in the classroom and off the streets. There are 400 students at the school and we’d love to provide each of them with breakfast and lunch each day if possible.\r\n\r\nThe cost per child to provide breakfast and lunch each day is $1.75, and since the children are in school on average 20 days each month, the cost per child about $35 each month for meals.\r\n\r\nSign up for a monthly pledge or a year’s cost of meals and we’ll match you with one of these amazing kids so you’ll know where your funds are going. Engage Somalia isn’t as easy for us to facilitate writing letters back and forth at this point but we hope to be able to provide you with periodic updates throughout the year on the students.\r\n\r\nWe’re incredibly grateful for your support as we begin this new venture! Somalia is a place with enormous needs, and the best we can do is to start somewhere and move forward. We’d be honored if you\'d join us!\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engagesomalia/\" target=\"_blank\">Learn more about giving to Engage Somalia or become a sponsor today!</a> </strong>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/somalia.smiling.girls_-e1418325902937.png\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-832\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/somalia.smiling.girls_-e1418325902937.png\" alt=\"somalia.smiling.girls_\" width=\"600\" height=\"336\" /></a>\r\n\r\n_________________\r\n<strong>Visit each of Hear The Cry\'s partnering organizations:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.thesenumbers.org/impact-circle\" target=\"_blank\">These Numbers Have Faces</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://remembernhu.org/give.html\" target=\"_blank\">Remember Nhu</a></strong> <strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">International: Girls Safe House</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engagesomalia/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Engage Somalia</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/restore-iraq-refugee-support/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Regufe Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engageiraq/\" target=\"_blank\">Sponsor a Child in Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://indiahappyhome.org/sponsor-a-child/\" target=\"_blank\">Happy Home for the Handicapped</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.lovingheartsbabies.com/#/home\" target=\"_blank\">Loving Hearts Baby Home</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://flyfishingcollaborative.org/give/\" target=\"_blank\">Nicaragua Fish Farm</a></strong>','Hear the Cry: Engage Somalia','','publish','closed','closed','','hear-the-cry-engage-somalia','','','2016-07-19 03:45:30','2016-07-19 11:45:30','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=830',0,'post','',0),(2439,22,'2014-12-19 12:00:09','2014-12-19 20:00:09','Want to make a huge impact on the kids in Iraq? Engage one of the students at our school and sponsor the cost of their education. This will allow us to continue providing a safe, caring environment in which each child can learn. We currently have 90 students and hope to grow to 600 based on the needs in the area.\r\n\r\nOur Engage program provides for the needs of our students throughout the entire year. This covers costs of textbooks, paper, pens and other school supplies, teacher funding, school rent, and special course materials. After signing up, you’ll receive a picture of a student who has benefited from our school programs in Iraq this year.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engageiraq/\" target=\"_blank\">Learn how to give to a student in Iraq</a>.\r\n_________________\r\n<strong>Visit each of Hear The Cry\'s partnering organizations:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.thesenumbers.org/impact-circle\" target=\"_blank\">These Numbers Have Faces</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://remembernhu.org/give.html\" target=\"_blank\">Remember Nhu</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Girls Safe House</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engagesomalia/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Engage Somalia</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/restore-iraq-refugee-support/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Refugee Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engageiraq/\" target=\"_blank\">Sponsor a Child in Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://indiahappyhome.org/sponsor-a-child/\" target=\"_blank\">Happy Home for the Handicapped</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.lovingheartsbabies.com/#/home\" target=\"_blank\">Loving Hearts Baby Home</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://flyfishingcollaborative.org/give/\" target=\"_blank\">Nicaragua Fish Farm</a> </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Hear the Cry: Sponsor a Child in Iraq','','publish','closed','closed','','hear-the-cry-sponsor-a-child-in-iraq','','','2016-07-19 03:42:26','2016-07-19 11:42:26','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=849',0,'post','',0),(2440,22,'2014-12-23 03:00:23','2014-12-23 11:00:23','<em><span style=\"color: #525252\">This year for our Hear the Cry giving catalogue we are putting a huge focus on child/student sponsorship. Throughout the Christmas season we’ll be highlighting each organization we work with here on the blog throughout the holiday season. Each blog will feature practical ways to get involved and to contribute financially. <a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/blog/christmas-justice/\" target=\"_blank\">For more information read Mike McDonald\'s letter and learn about Hear the Cry\'s work supporting children around the world.</a></span></em>\r\n\r\nLoving Hearts Babies Home exists to restore orphaned/abandoned babies into permanent families through Loving Hearts Babies Home initiatives, Churches, and other partnerships to strengthen and empower agents of change for future generations. A couple of families from Bridgetown and Westside have adopted children from Uganda through this incredible home.\r\n\r\nLoving Hearts is currently in a rented facility. By the end of 2014, our plan is to purchase land and build a permanent home in Munyonyo, Uganda.\r\n\r\nPlease consider giving a financial gift to help make this possible.  Not only does a permanent location cut down on rental costs, but it also provides more stability to our babies and gives them a home that is custom made to the specific needs of a facility carrying for a large infant population. Our new home will also expand our capacity and help us care for more babies than we do now! This is exciting, knowing that we will be able to help provide more Jesus-loving homes to the babies who so desperately need them.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.lovingheartsbabies.com/#/home\" target=\"_blank\">Find out more about Loving Hearts baby home</a>.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://www.denarionline.com/DONORSERVICES/TEMPLATEPAGE.ASPX?COMP_REF=_ARM&amp;SID=tksafmzm2tk2jmrrosfe4o45&amp;CONTENT=GIVINGOPTION&amp;DS_GO_REF=8F7EF5F936\" target=\"_blank\">Learn how to contribute to this project</a>.\r\n\r\n_________________\r\n\r\n<strong>Visit each of Hear The Cry\'s partnering organizations:</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.thesenumbers.org/impact-circle\" target=\"_blank\">These Numbers Have Faces</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://remembernhu.org/give.html\" target=\"_blank\">Remember Nhu</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/ugandasafehouse/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Girls Safe House</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engagesomalia/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Engage Somalia</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/restore-iraq-refugee-support/\" target=\"_blank\">Restore International: Refugee Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"https://restoreinternational.org/shop/products/engageiraq/\" target=\"_blank\">Sponsor a Child in Iraq</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://indiahappyhome.org/sponsor-a-child/\" target=\"_blank\">Happy Home for the Handicapped</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://www.lovingheartsbabies.com/#/home\" target=\"_blank\">Loving Hearts Baby Home</a></strong>\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://flyfishingcollaborative.org/give/\" target=\"_blank\">Nicaragua Fish Farm</a> </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Hear the Cry: Loving Hearts Babies Home','','publish','closed','closed','','hear-the-cry-loving-hearts-babies-home','','','2016-07-19 03:10:55','2016-07-19 11:10:55','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=857',0,'post','',0),(2441,30,'2015-01-12 15:19:23','2015-01-12 23:19:23','<div style=\"color: #222222;\">As I sit here thinking about how to write my seminary statement, “What is the Church?” I realize that one important thing to lay out is why the Church matters in the first place.</div>\n<p>\n<div style=\"color: #222222;\">\n<div></div>\n<div><strong>1. Jesus instated it, assuming it would be a part of his disciple’s lives (Mat. <span class=\"aBn\" tabindex=\"0\" data-term=\"goog_775292002\"><span class=\"aQJ\">16:18</span></span>, <span class=\"aBn\" tabindex=\"0\" data-term=\"goog_775292003\"><span class=\"aQJ\">18:17</span></span>).</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n<div>The only recordings we have of Jesus using the word <i>ecclesia</i> (which is translated, \"church\") are in these two passages. In them, Jesus gives a framework for how \'an assembly of <em>called out</em> people’ (what <i>ecclesia </i>means) is to order itself, and how it should deal with internal problems. Jesus assumed that after his ascension, his disciples would carry on his work corporately, not individually. They would accomplish his goals in groups, in assemblies, in churches. Jesus didn’t tell Peter to find one other guy to whom he\'d pass the message, Jesus told 11, who turned into 3,000, who turned into the millions of disciples today, who make up the church.</div>\n<div></div>\n<p>\n<div><strong>2. Early disciples of Jesus organized themselves into churches (Acts 2:41-47,<span class=\"aBn\" tabindex=\"0\" data-term=\"goog_775292004\"><span class=\"aQJ\">14:23</span></span>).</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div>Not only did Jesus assume his disciples would go and make more disciples—continuing life in community—but the disciples <em>actually did just that</em>. We see a compelling picture of what church could be like in Acts 2:41-47.</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>3. Authentic community is good for us.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div>I use the word “authentic,” because there are plenty of examples of inauthentic community out there—in schools, in neighborhoods, in families, and yes, in churches. What we as followers of Jesus need is <em>authentic</em> community. Community where we are <em>known</em>, we are cared for, where we know and care for others. We need community where we serve, where we are served, and where we hold “everything in common.” That authentic community transforms us because we receive the teachings of God, we interact with him through prayer and worship, and we share that experience with others, welcoming them into the family.</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>4. I can’t sing alone.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div>Anyone who has stood next to me while I’m singing will tell you, “it\'s true, he <em>can\'t</em> sing.” What I mean by that statement is that there is something about joining together in corporate worship that is good for the soul. It\'s good for my transformation to become more like Jesus. I realize in coming together with the church that while I might be a toe, others are feet, others are fingers, others are ears or noses. We are all different parts of one body and we need each other (1 Cor. <span class=\"aBn\" tabindex=\"0\" data-term=\"goog_775292005\"><span class=\"aQJ\">12:12</span></span>).</div>\n</p><p>\n<h2>I am not an island unto myself, and I cannot follow Jesus alone. Neither can you.</h2>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>5. We’re going to spend eternity together anyway, might as well get used to it.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div>I say that tongue-in-cheek, but with an underlying truth. In the age to come, we are going to be invited in as part of the “Bride of Christ,” which is Jesus’ church, and there is going to be a celebration and a feast. I am not the only one invited, but I\'m invited in as one member of the party, because I have been adopted into God’s <em>family.</em> I’ve been accepted by him and transformed by the Spirit, to now be a part of his church—Jesus\' \"bride\" (Eph. 5:22-23). Now, from where I sit, I sometimes feel uncomfortable with the imagery of being a bride—because I’m a dude and I played football—but the imagery is more important than the fact that a bride in my mind is a woman dressed in white. The imagery is powerful because it means Jesus <em>loves</em> his church, and he is coming to gather His church to himself.</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div>One day we, as his people, all together, will get to sit down at the feast table with him and celebrate.</div>\n</p></div></p>','Why does church matter?','','trash','closed','closed','','why-does-church-matter__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=910',0,'post','',0),(2442,20,'2015-01-19 11:59:46','2015-01-19 19:59:46','Nichole slows her words down and her eyes grow big.  “I gave my first tithe yesterday,” she says, choking back tears.  “That is the first time I’ve ever been able to do that.  It is a huge thing for me.  I finally feel like I can give back.”\r\n\r\nA year ago, the thought of giving to others was far from Nichole Hoffman’s mind.  A single mom, overwhelmed with completing a teaching degree and providing for her four-year-old son, she felt like there was nothing more to give.  The dark porch, cold and empty, offered no comfort.  With a glass of wine in one hand and a cigarette in the other, Nichole, cried silently in the darkness.  The rent, the surmounting school debt, child care, unemployment - the hopelessness of it all clung to her throat as she tried to swallow it away with a third glass. Then a fourth.\r\n\r\nHow many glasses had it been?\r\n\r\nHer tear-stained cigarette trembled.\r\n\r\nHeadlights from an approaching car sliced through the dark porch.  Nichole watched as Kate, her neighbor, emerged from the parked vehicle, and headed toward the four-plex. Instead of going to her own doorstep, she approached Nichole’s porch.  In the hopelessness of the situation, Kate began to describe Jesus, and Nichole was open to it.\r\n\r\n“I finally said okay,” recalls Nichole.  “I wanted that peace and forgiveness with God.  The moment she led me to Jesus, I got instantly sober.  It was like an opiate, the sense of peace and comfort that rushed through me.”\r\n\r\nA few months later, sitting in a circle among the newly developed missional community, Nichole felt comfortable for the first time, comfortable enough to ask for prayer.  The group listened intently while Nichole explained that she was sick with pneumonia.  When Nichole had finished, Kate, not able to hold back, interjected, “Not to mention you can’t eat and have been on a liquid diet for two months!”\r\n\r\nImmediately, the truth in its entirety came out.\r\n\r\nNichole’s teeth were deteriorating from multiple exposed fillings and painful tooth decay.  For months, she had survived on a liquid diet, and now the malnourishment and weight loss had deteriorated her health to the point of pneumonia.\r\n\r\n“The next day I started getting all these emails from people interested in helping provide dental insurance for this gal,” recalls Kristy Colvin and her husband Chris, their missional community\'s leaders.  “In four days, through numerous people, we were making arrangements for her to be seen by a doctor.”\r\n\r\n“It was phenomenal how our Missional Community came together,” says Chris. “It blew my mind that so many people cared about a stranger,” says Nichole.  “It was on their heart, and it was very hard for me to accept that because I’ve had to survive for so long.”\r\n\r\nSurrounded by the love and support of her new church family, Nichole began to volunteer with the kids at Westside: A Jesus Church, and she immersed herself in the missional community and their outreach to foster children.  Things were going well until summer came, and Nichole’s subbing position at the school ended, along with her source of income.  On the verge of eviction, she asked for help.\r\n\r\n“I didn’t want to ask.  They already helped me so much,” says Nichole.\r\n\r\nYet, people from the missional community stepped in to meet the practical needs.  Stay-at-home mothers opened their homes and babysat Lukas while Nichole interviewed for jobs, eliminating her childcare bill for a few months.  Two couples with a knack for finances helped her create a budget. Then Nichole had an idea.\r\n\r\n“I had this epiphany and decided to ask the missional community for donations for a yard sale.  It was part of my plan to help raise money,” explains Nichole.\r\n\r\nOn a Saturday morning in her front yard, Nichole and few unexpected hands put on a yard sale to help raise money for her rent expenses.  “For the first time, I met neighbors and I started talking to these people,” says Nichole.  “I was able to bless people for the first time… it was pretty frickin\' awesome.”\r\n\r\nEven though the sale only generated a few hundred dollars, Nichole came away from the experience with a new enthusiasm and heart for her neighbors.  “People were meeting each other because I had this thing going on.  I started getting excited.  I can share Jesus and I can do that right here.”\r\n\r\nTwo months later, Nichole found a job in Hillsboro as a half-day, dual-language teacher and continues to have a contagious passion to give to others.\r\n\r\n\"Missional Community has taught me how to bless others, to be humble, and to receive help.  I have this family that I didn’t have before and it is the best family I’ve ever had.  Why wouldn’t you give it a chance?\"','A Contagious Hope','','publish','closed','closed','','a-contagious-hope','','','2016-07-19 03:00:37','2016-07-19 11:00:37','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=934',0,'post','',0),(2443,30,'2015-01-26 11:36:15','2015-01-26 19:36:15','Throughout Scripture we see the practice of “meditation” as something celebrated and commended. When Joshua was in the process of taking over leadership for the nation of Israel, he is told to “Keep this Book of the Law always on your lips; <b>meditate</b> on it day and night, so that you may be careful to do everything written in it. Then you will be prosperous and successful” (Josh. 1v8). At the opening of the Book of Psalms, the “blessed man” is one “whose delight is in the law of the Lord, and who <b>meditates</b> on his law day and night” (Ps. 1v2).\n<div style=\"color: #222222;\">\n<p>\n<div>Theres a repeated theme here:<b> meditation on God’s words day and night is <i>essential</i>.</b> Inevitably, because of the world we live in, the word “mediation” conjures up images of eastern spirituality, chanting, and “emptying the mind.”  These competing visions of contemplation shouldn\'t scare us away from attempting to utilize the <em>biblical</em> practice of meditation. Since the Bible celebrates and commends meditation, we should at least discuss what Biblical meditation is, and then <i>how</i> we might do it.</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><b>What it is: </b>When the Bible talks about meditation it talks about reciting something over and over, whispering it, musing over it, imagining about it, studying it intensely and reflecting on it. To meditate on Scripture is to recite it quietly, read into its undertones, ponder it and give it serious consideration. Meditation proposed today is often about psychological manipulation, some eastern meditation is about detaching one\'s self from the world. Biblical mediation however, is about engagement with the world God has created and how God has revealed himself in the world. Biblical meditation is about filling the mind with the way of Jesus, his truth, and about submitting our ways to Jesus to be transformed by him. <i>How</i> do we meditate biblically then?</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><b>How to do it: </b>Here are a couple methods for biblical meditation that come from Joseph Hall’s <i><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1589603621/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1589603621&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=joshdiescom-20&amp;linkId=GQZOFATYPM6Q52MY\" target=\"_blank\">The Art of Divine Meditation</a> </i>(1606) and are adapted by Donald Whitney in <i><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1615216170/ref=as_li_qf_sp_asin_il_tl?ie=UTF8&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=1615216170&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;tag=joshdiescom-20&amp;linkId=IKL2H2KDZAGVRBSD\" target=\"_blank\">Spiritual Disciplines for the Christian Life</a>. </i>If you\'re not into reading 17th century theologians I\'d happily recommend Whitney\'s book.</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>1. Emphasize different words in a text</strong></div>\n<div>E.g., If you’re reading Psalm 25:1 you could read…</div>\n<div><i>In</i> you, Lord my God, I put my trust.</div>\n<div>In <i>you</i>, Lord my God, I put my trust.</div>\n<div>In you, <i>Lord</i> my God, I put my trust.</div>\n<div>In you, Lord <i>my God</i>, I put my trust.</div>\n<div>And so on.</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>2. Rewrite the text in your own words</strong></div>\n<div>E.g., How would you say this same thing, but in your own ordinary, everyday language?</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>3. Ask of the text, \"What does it teach?”</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>4. Ask of the text, \"What <em>image</em> best illustrates it?”</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>5. Ask where the text fits in relation to Jesus, and to the Gospel.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>6.  In reading the text, ask what questions are answered? What problem is solved?</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>7. Pray through the text..</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>8. Memorize the text.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>9.  Create an artistic interpretation of the text.</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>10. Ask questions of the text modeled after Phillippians 4:8.</strong></div>\n<div>E.g., What is <i>right </i>about this text? What is <i>noble</i> about it? What is <i>true </i>in it? What is <i>lovely, admirable,</i> and so on?</div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>11. Set a minimum number of insights to draw out of the text</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>12. Look for a common thread or theme through the several sentences, paragraphs or sections you’re reading</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n</p><p>\n<div><strong>13. Ask how the text speaks to your current issue or situation</strong></div>\n</p></div>\n<div style=\"color: #222222;\"></div>\n<div style=\"color: #222222;\">Whenever you engage with Scripture you should be ready to engage with God, to submit your life and your ways to him and allow him to shape who you are moving forward. Meditation puts us in a place to have all of that happen. As we practice biblical meditation, we can hopefully guard  ourselves from being the type of people who constantly hear and read and yet are never actually changed. When words never become action.</div>\n<div style=\"color: #222222;\"></div>\n<p>\n<div style=\"color: #222222;\">By meditation on God\'s words and God\'s truth we can be better prepared to follow Jesus and learn to live like him.</div>\n</p><p></p>','Meditation?','','trash','closed','closed','','meditation__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=943',0,'post','',0),(2444,30,'2015-01-28 09:00:46','2015-01-28 17:00:46','Sunset Church is celebrating stories of faithfulness to Jesus\' call to be baptized. Leading up to each monthly Baptism Sunday, we\'re sharing stories from folks in our own family—how they came to follow Jesus in baptism, and how they\'d encourage others who have yet to do so.\n\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'http://www.youtube.com/embed//pWy7L_NF5Qs\' frameborder=\'0\' allowfullscreen></iframe></div>\n\n<br />','Baptism Stories','','trash','closed','closed','','baptism-stories__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:29:31','2016-07-19 06:29:31','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=952',0,'post','',0),(2445,25,'2015-05-17 13:06:56','2015-05-17 20:06:56','Jesus, we are so fortunate to live in such an amazing city. Each district has its own unique charm and culture.\r\n\r\nWe pray for Southeast Portland.\r\n\r\nIt is exciting to see this corner of the city continue to develop and prosper. Thank you for our very own Salt &amp; Straw that always has a shorter line than the one in Northwest.\r\n\r\nThere is a huge diversity of people. From the hipsters at Broder Cafe, to the hippies fire dancing at Colonel Summers Park, to the young families raising children, and the older generation living in Ladd’s Addition,\r\n\r\nwe ask that they would discover the Kingdom of God.\r\n\r\nOn the streets of Southeast there are amazing restaurants but there is also a darkness. People are suffering. They are searching for truth. They are searching for enlightenment from alternative spirituality. Or escape through substance abuse. Others maintain an attitude of apathy and indifference to avoid the harsh realities of life.\r\n\r\nWe ask that through the many different Missional Communities, the people of Southeast Portland would be introduced to a new hope.\r\n\r\nThat the people who are broken would be made whole.\r\n\r\nThank you that we get to be a part of a neighborhood that raises chickens and grows gardens out of every crack in the sidewalk.\r\n\r\nThe people in this city value sustainability and cultivation of your creation. We pray that you would be ultimately recognized as The Creator of all things and that you would use us to our fullest potentials to point people to you.\r\n\r\nThank you that this corner of Portland so values uniqueness and creativity. However, we know that with this can come unique versions of pain, self-medication, and apathy. We ask that you would show us how to love those around us the way you do.\r\n\r\nHoly Spirit, break into the darkest, farthest reaches of Southeast Portland and set people free.\r\n\r\nWe ask that God’s will be done in Southeast Portland as it is in Heaven.\r\n\r\nAmen.','A Prayer for Southeast Portland','','publish','closed','closed','','a-prayer-for-southeast-portland','','','2016-07-19 02:26:13','2016-07-19 10:26:13','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1340',0,'post','',0),(2446,41,'2015-05-26 13:25:41','2015-05-26 20:25:41','As a church, we have always been strongly focused on making disciples of Jesus and maturing in spiritual growth. This, of course, is vital to the life of the church.\r\n\r\nHowever, we have recently discovered that we have basically ignored our emotional and relational growth.\r\n\r\nThis has left us unbalanced.\r\n\r\nWhy are there so many of us in the church who are following Jesus, clearly gifted, trained in the Bible, yet acting like children or teenagers emotionally? Why are there so many of us who struggle with feelings of insecurity, frustration, or emotional fatigue?\r\n\r\nWhen we are emotionally unhealthy the symptoms will appear in many ways:\r\n\r\nIf you can never say “I was wrong” or “ I am sorry.”\r\n\r\nIf you are constantly criticizing others.\r\n\r\nIf you feel as though God is always disappointed in you, and you are always living in fear that the “other shoe is going to drop.”\r\n\r\nIf you feel like the love you have in your life is never enough and people in relationships always disappoint you.\r\n\r\nIf who take every critique as a personal attack.\r\n\r\nWhy do so many of us, when we are hurt, turn to whining, complaining, distancing ourselves, blaming, or using sarcasm? Often times, if we are honest, we just act like little children who aren’t getting their way.\r\n\r\nPhil 2v12-13 says, “Therefore, my dear friends, as you have always obeyed—not only in my presence, but now much more in my absence—continue to work out your salvation with fear and trembling, for it is God who works in you to will and to act in order to fulfill his good purpose.”\r\n\r\nThis can also be read, “At conversion believers receive a new identity, a new heart, and the indwelling of the Holy Spirit. Then, life is lived by the power of the Holy Spirit, <i>progressively maturing into the likeness of Christ.</i>”\r\n\r\nHere are 8 principles for growing in emotional and relational health:\r\n<h1><b>1. Emotions Are Important </b></h1>\r\nOne of the first words we think of when it comes to emotional health is “emotion.”\r\n\r\nEmotions are often the indicators that give us insight to the present state of our heart. They reveal both areas of need and strength, such as crying or anger. These are emotions we see from Jesus and his disciples.\r\n\r\nOur emotions are something to pay attention to because they ultimately become the dictator of our behavior. We can safely assume that something is wrong.\r\n\r\nSo a question we would ask is where are you on the scale? Are you aware of your feelings and emotions? Or is it time to slow down, and listen?\r\n<h1><b>2. Look Beneath The Surface </b></h1>\r\nOnce we recognize our emotions are an important thing, we have to ask ourselves if there’s more going on underneath. Our lives are like an iceberg, most of what is happening exists beneath the surface. Emotions are just the tip.\r\n\r\nLooking beneath the surface isn’t easy to do for lots of reasons. It takes time, or we are afraid of what’s there, but it’s the key to understanding what areas of our lives need growth and healing.\r\n\r\nI am the type of person who is not usually aware of my emotions. I’m an extrovert… But this is something in which God wanted me to grow. I think I was often afraid to be quiet in solitude and listen to God. I was afraid of being condemned. But, pushing thru that fear, spending time in solitude listening to God, what I found was love!\r\n\r\nKnowing we are deeply loved and accepted by the Father allows us to explore dark aspects of who we are.\r\n\r\nKnowing God’s limitless grace gives us the courage to face the painful truth about ourselves.\r\n\r\nKnowing what Jesus has done for me allows me to be myself because there is nothing left to prove.\r\n\r\nBegin to recognize God’s unwavering love for you, and look beneath the surface.\r\n<h1><b>3. Break The Power of The Past</b></h1>\r\nAnother component to moving forward has to do with our past.\r\n\r\nOur past is effected by romantic relationships but it also includes our family history. This involves addictions, abuse, mental illness, the kind of home in which we were raised, and generational sins. These past experiences will directly affect our present ability to love Jesus and others.\r\n\r\nMemories can haunt us.\r\n\r\nWe must allow God to take us back so he can heal our wounds. He wants to help us grieve and release us from pain.\r\n\r\nAcknowledge the past, so that God could teach you how to live more faithfully in the present.\r\n\r\nThis can feel scary and overwhelming. As people who follow Jesus, we never go back to these memories alone. By the Spirit, the person of Jesus is with you. And because he is with you, you don’t have to be afraid. See yourself through his eyes and that will change everything.\r\n<h1><b>4. Know Your Limits</b></h1>\r\nEmotional health comes from knowing your limits. Basically, we must learn to say “no.”\r\n\r\nJesus lived within his limits. He didn\'t perform miracles until age 30.\r\n\r\nIn the journey towards emotional health and Christ-likeness, this is one that has profoundly impacted me. I have come to learn that I don’t have to do everything that is asked of me by others. Not everything others think I should do is actually what God has for me.\r\n\r\nI am learning to ask, “Has God given me grace for this?” This has changed so much about my emotional health and my ability to be present and effective in the things that I am clearly called to.\r\n\r\nOften times I know I am off balance when I am: anxious, rushing and hurrying, not sleeping well, doing too many things and doing them poorly, restless and my mind is racing, not fully present with people, distracted, irritable in normal things like traffic or in line, and skimming on time with God.\r\n\r\nSound familiar? If that’s you, it’s a good indicator that you may need to re-evaluate the things to which you are saying, “Yes.”\r\n\r\nThe danger comes when we say <i>yes</i> but God has said <i>no</i>.\r\n<h1><b>5. Embrace Grieving and Loss</b></h1>\r\nThese last few things are some of the hardest.\r\n\r\nWe all know that grief and loss are an unfortunate part of everyday life. And the scope of both are vast. Whether we’re talking about difficult transitions in life, unexpected loss, tragedy, or death most of us find that it’s easier to bury it, ignore it, or medicate, rather than embrace the feelings confronting us.\r\n\r\nEmbracing grief and loss at its core level is about paying attention to our pain.\r\n\r\nWe must be willing to confront it and wait for God to bring freedom, comfort, and relief.\r\n\r\nThis often feels overwhelming, if not impossible. But even Jesus needed to express the grief and loss in is own life. Jesus wept. Which means it’s possible and also necessary for us.\r\n\r\nLearning to embrace grief and loss as a normal practice in our lives will move us to a place of greater emotional margin, and a place of honest and healthy vulnerability with Jesus and others.\r\n<h1><b>6. Live in Brokenness and Vulnerability </b></h1>\r\nBrokenness and vulnerability are often hindered by the lie that if we don’t appear to have our life in order we will somehow be too much for people; too messy or too broken.\r\n\r\nOr we believe that we won’t measure up in comparison to others. That by letting people in, and sharing honestly, we will appear to be an imposition or burden on those around us.\r\n\r\nThis can lead to anxiety and a curated version of ourselves.\r\n\r\nMost of us deal with our brokenness in 3 ways:\r\n\r\n1. We try to hide the pain, covering up all the cracks and frailty.\r\n\r\n2. We become angry and bitter at ourselves or others.\r\n\r\n3. Or like the majority of America, we run from it and medicate ourselves.\r\n\r\nLook, the world says living in brokenness and vulnerability is weak and virtually impossible, but Jesus and his kingdom say the opposite.\r\n\r\nJesus has, and will always, call imperfect, broken people to live out of their weakness so that through their vulnerability and honesty, the world might see him.\r\n<h1><b>7. Celebrate</b></h1>\r\nNot every step is heavy, dark, and depressing.\r\n\r\nThere is also a time to celebrate!\r\n\r\nAll throughout the scriptures there were parties and celebrations. From the yearly celebration of passover, to the wedding party in Cana, we see that not only was this a part of Jesus’ life, but we learn that it is central to the life and health of God’s people.\r\n\r\nThis means we’ve got to practice celebrating. Even the little things.\r\n\r\nCelebrate babies, and birthdays, anniversaries, and Fridays. Celebration cultivates gratitude and thankfulness. It reminds us of our good gifts, and from where those gifts come.\r\n<h1><b>8. Live Incarnationally</b></h1>\r\nThe whole purpose of emotional health is to give us ways to continue to become more like Jesus. To live life as he lived.\r\n\r\nJesus is our example.\r\n\r\nJesus showed us incarnational living. God took on the flesh of humanity and sat with people, listened to people, and loved people. In the same way we want to be the kind of people who are not always talking about ourselves but have the emotional health to truly care and listen to others.\r\n\r\nIn the words of Scriptures “weep with those who are weeping and rejoice with those who are rejoicing.”\r\n\r\nThese 8 principles for growing in emotional and relational health are a process.\r\n\r\nI am still working on this stuff. I am still trying to stay within my limits. I am still working to regularly take time in the morning in solitude, looking beneath the surface, and listening to God.\r\n\r\nAllow Jesus to help you discover emotional health.\r\n\r\n–\r\n\r\nThese principles are based on the book <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Emotionally-Healthy-Church-Expanded-Discipleship/dp/0310293359/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1431990253&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=the+emotionally+healthy+church\" target=\"_blank\">The Emotionally Healthy Church</a> by Peter Scazzero\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','8 Principles for Emotional Health','','publish','closed','closed','','8-principles-for-emotional-health','','','2016-07-19 02:24:40','2016-07-19 10:24:40','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1346',0,'post','',0),(2447,25,'2015-08-03 15:37:03','2015-08-03 22:37:03','Jesus,\r\n\r\nThank you for the beautiful neighborhoods of Northwest Portland, also known as the Alphabet District. As long as you know your ABCs you can never get lost.\r\n\r\nThank you for the parks on every other block that remind us of your creative power. From Forest Park to the Japanese Gardens, the beauty of nature is at our doorstep.\r\n\r\nThank you that our neighborhood is growing and becoming an even more fun and vibrant part of the larger city of Portland.\r\n\r\nThere are many types of people within a wide range of socio-economic status. Yet we all walk the same streets. Our kids go to the same schools. We all stand in the same line at Salt &amp; Straw.\r\n\r\nWe are connected in so many ways.\r\n\r\nSo we ask that Northwest Portland be a place to build community and introduce people to Jesus.\r\n\r\nIt\'s easy to look past the overt poverty that is scattered throughout the Alphabet District, but would you open our eyes to see the people around us and to love the way you do.\r\n\r\nHelp us recognize the people that are suffering.\r\n\r\nJesus, don\'t let us be distracted by the pleasures and delights of the Alphabet District, but see through the filter of happiness and to the heart cry of people who need to know you.\r\n\r\nTeach us to love the way you loved us; selflessly, deeply, and with no guarantee of return.\r\n\r\nWe ask that God\'s will would be done in Northwest Portland as it is in Heaven.\r\n\r\nAmen.','A Prayer for Northwest Portland','','publish','closed','closed','','a-prayer-for-northwest-portland','','','2016-07-19 00:23:46','2016-07-19 08:23:46','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1374',0,'post','',0),(2448,43,'2015-05-28 11:57:15','2015-05-28 18:57:15','I had never seen innocent children so terribly abused, neglected, and forgotten.\r\n\r\nI grew up in a home that followed Jesus. I went to Sunday School and Awanas, and as I began high school I traveled the world on different mission trips. Over the course of five years I worked with different orphanages across Russia and my heart broke.\r\n\r\nChildren were hurting.\r\n\r\nI soon recognized this problem was not unique to foreign countries. The very same issues were going on, seemingly unnoticed, in our own back yard.\r\n\r\nHundreds of thousands of kids are in foster care right here in America and their stories are no different than that of the kids I met in Russia.\r\n\r\nThey are neglected.\r\n\r\nThey are abused.\r\n\r\nThey are locked in closets and used as ashtrays.\r\n\r\nThey are told they are mistakes, worthless, and too hard to love. They grow up believing these lies and continue the heartbreaking cycle of abuse.\r\n\r\nBut Jesus has a different message for these forgotten children. He says they are wanted. They are loved. They are worth everything!\r\n\r\nAs followers of Jesus, we must show these hurting kids that there is hope.\r\n<h1>Royal Family Kids Camp</h1>\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1424\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/05/ajc_blog_rfkc_3.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_rfkc_3\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nEvery summer, we invite kids from the foster care system to experience the best week of their life. Kids who have been neglected and forgotten are treated like royalty. They are given only one responsibility, have fun. They are free to act like children, to laugh, to run, and play.\r\n\r\nEven if just for a moment, they are able to forget the pain they have suffered.\r\n\r\nWe fill their week with parties, games, food, field trips, and as much laughter as they can muster. In the beautiful cathedral of nature, amongst the laughing and the playing, they hear the good news about a real, true Father who loves them. During this week Jesus gets to redefine what true, fatherly love is and so many of these kids go away with an entirely new view of themselves.\r\n\r\nThey come to camp with walls so thick around their hearts that it seems impossible to break through. Year after year Jesus reminds us that we don’t need to break through, we just need to love them and he will do the rest. And year after year we watch these kids allow their guard to drop and dare to believe that they really are lovable and valuable. It is without a doubt the most beautiful transformation you will ever see!\r\n\r\nThere are many ways for you to help:\r\n<h4><strong>Birthday Boxes</strong></h4>\r\nMany of these kids have never had a birthday party, so we throw the biggest party we can. We have a carnival and fill their day with games, piñatas, cupcakes, singing, and birthday presents. If you or your missional community want to put together birthday boxes, we have a list of toys to ensure that everyone gets the same presents. These birthday boxes come to about $75 per box.\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=rfkc@ajesuschurch.org]Sign-up for Birthday boxes[/email][/page_actions]\r\n<h4><strong>Prayer Partners</strong></h4>\r\nPrayer is an effective means of support. Our prayer partners will receive a bracelet to wear during the week of camp and a specific list of prayers that a staff member has requested. To become a prayer partner, visit the Westside Church annex on June 7 &amp; 14.\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=rfkc@ajesuschurch.org]More Partnership Information[/email][/page_actions]\r\n<h4><strong>Kids Camp Leader</strong></h4>\r\nEach year, Royal Family Kids Camp hosts dozens of kids in need of care and attention. This requires a lot of work. To become a Kids Camp Leader, you must complete an application, background check, and interview.\r\n\r\n[page_actions][email address=rfkc@ajesuschurch.org]Request Leader Application[/email][/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1425\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_rfkc_2.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_rfkc_2\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1435\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_rfkc_4.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_rfkc_4\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1433\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_rfkc_11.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_rfkc_1\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\r\n\r\nLearn more about the story behind Royal Family Kids Camp and discover other opportunities to get involved.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://royalfamilykids.org\" target=\"_blank\">Royal Family Kids Camp</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','A Hope for Abused Children','','publish','closed','closed','','royal-family-kids-camp','','','2016-07-19 02:14:36','2016-07-19 10:14:36','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1396',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2449,18,'2015-06-01 15:23:40','2015-06-01 22:23:40','The church is meant to thrive.\r\n\r\nIt should be filled with life and vitality and animation and Spirit.\r\n\r\nConsidering the Corinthian church, they had all sorts of problems and issues, but they were a church where the Holy Spirit had free reign to move in power.\r\n\r\nThey would regularly come together as family, everybody had a part to play, they were ready to operate in the Spirit, and they were prepared to participate.\r\n\r\nThey functioned in a way that allowed the Holy Spirit to lead them efficiently and effectively.\r\n\r\nFor the people of God to become this kind of church, we have to confront two dangers head on:\r\n<h2>1. Consumerism</h2>\r\n2015, Portland, Oregon.\r\n\r\nWe eat, sleep, and breathe consumerism.\r\n\r\nIn the United States, our entire economy is built upon consumerism. Following the attacks on Sept. 11, what did the President tell the American people? Go shopping. And because consumerism is the air we breathe, we are blind to how heinous it is.\r\n\r\nWe bring this heart posture over into the church.\r\n\r\nGenerally speaking, most people don’t attend a church gathering to give, but to receive.\r\n\r\nThink of the Christianize phrase, “I’m fed here.” Why do you go to church there? I’m fed. Why did you leave the last church? I wasn’t fed.\r\n\r\nI still can’t exactly figure out what people even mean by that. It’s clearly a metaphor. It has something to do with the teaching. I think it just means they do or do not like it.\r\n\r\nThe gatherings are designed to equip the people of God, but I don’t want you to go away from church “fed,” I want you to go away hungry! And thirsty! For more. To live the kingdom of God in community in your neighborhood.\r\n\r\nThis is why we do Missional Communities, because they are a full frontal assault on the gods of American culture.\r\n\r\nCommunity takes on individualism.\r\n\r\nMission takes on consumerism.\r\n\r\nGive your life away for the good for your neighborhood. Doing that in community is the antithesis of American culture. It’s the way of Jesus.\r\n\r\nThink of the language of “church services.” We call the weekends “gatherings,” not “services,” and that’s on purpose. Because this isn’t a store where you come every Sunday for religious goods and services.\r\n\r\nThe Church is a people. It’s a family that you gather with.\r\n\r\nDon’t think of church as the spiritual equivalent of a donut shop. Some people like Pip’s Donuts in Northeast, while others are into Voodoo Donuts. Personally, I prefer Blue Star Donuts, so I go there. That’s fine, but don’t think of church that way.\r\n\r\nThink of the Church as your family. Hopefully you like it, maybe you don’t! Either way, you’re in.\r\n\r\nFor so many of us, this just isn’t how we think about church. And because of that, church often has very little effect on us.\r\n\r\nMark Sayers, who is a writer and pastor in Melbourne, Australia, has this to say in his book <em>The Vertical Self:</em>\r\n\r\n“The elephant in the living room of contemporary Christianity is people’s ability to simply sit in church, to consume the experience the way one would a great sporting event, a thrilling movie, or an exciting theme park ride, and then to dispose of it, totally unchanged at the soul level, as they leave the sanctuary. Sure, they might feel challenged, encouraged, or even moved, but the horizontal self simply ‘feels’ the experience and moves on.”\r\n\r\nHe goes on to write that in a consumer based church, this is what happens:\r\n\r\nWorship service becomes a pseudo media event.\r\n\r\nChurch building becomes a theme park.\r\n\r\nChristian leader becomes a Christian celebrity.\r\n\r\nTeaching becomes entertainment.\r\n\r\nSalvation becomes self-help.\r\n\r\nDiscipleship becomes lifestyle enhancement.\r\n\r\nSoul becomes self.\r\n\r\nChurch becomes brand.\r\n\r\nGospel becomes slogan.\r\n\r\nAnd so if we want to become the kind of church Jesus had in mind, consumerism has to die. There has to be a tectonic shift in how we approach church.\r\n\r\nThe church must become collaborative and participatory and interactive.\r\nCome ready to give, not just receive.\r\n<h2>2. The American Obsession with Order</h2>\r\nA problem with the church in Corinth was too much spontaneity, and not enough order. It was wild and spasmodic and out of control.\r\n\r\nWe have the exact opposite problem; too much order, and not enough spontaneity.\r\n\r\nWe have planned each church gathering down to the last detail.\r\n\r\nIt’s borderline formulaic:\r\n\r\nSong.\r\n\r\nSong.\r\n\r\nPrayer.\r\n\r\nFour Minute Greeting (awkward).\r\n\r\nAnnouncements.\r\n\r\nTeaching.\r\n\r\nSong.\r\n\r\nSong.\r\n\r\nCommunion.\r\n\r\nSong.\r\n\r\nGoodnight!\r\n\r\nWe script it. I literally have an app on my phone calling “Planning Center.” It has the worship set, and the announcements, and the times of everything happening. And that’s not all bad. There are hundreds of people here so an open mic would be a disaster.\r\n\r\nI’m sure Paul would have very different ideas for a church of 700 in Portland, Oregon than a church of 70 in an open air Mediterranean courtyard.\r\n\r\nBut still, I think we can agree, we take order to the extreme.\r\n\r\nAnd I like it that way! I’m a (recovering) perfectionist, OCD, control freak. I hate weird church stuff. I prefer the intellectual over the emotional. But at the same time, I crave an experience with the Spirit of God. And the Spirit isn’t controllable. When he comes, he’s like the wind. He can be messy and chaotic and out of left field.\r\n\r\nI’m not saying that we want things to get weird or spooky or uncomfortable. One of the things we’re really passionate about as leadership is going after all the Holy Spirit stuff – prophecy and healing and the rest – in a down to earth, normal kind of way.\r\n\r\nWhat I’m saying is that we want more of the Spirit of God.\r\n\r\nSermons and songs are not enough. We want the Spirit to come and erupt in our church. We want prophecy to become a normal, ordinary, everyday thing. We want to regularly see healing of the sick. We want to see people set free from the demonic. And above all, we want God’s presence.\r\n\r\nSo the Church must be more than willing to go off script.\r\n\r\nWe usually end the teaching now with listening prayer. Myself and the leaders circle up and do our best to follow the Spirit’s leading for worship.\r\n\r\nWe want the pneuma, the wind, the Spirit.\r\n\r\nConsumerism and the obsession with order can quickly kill the church.\r\n\r\nTo move forward, we need to shift these ideas from theology to practice, and from practice to culture.\r\n\r\nAllow generosity and the direction of the Spirit to become the new normal.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAdapted from the teaching \"Loose Ends\" by John Mark Comer.\r\n\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/teaching/receive-the-holy-spirit/loose-ends/\">Listen to \"Loose Ends\"</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Two Dangers To The Church','','publish','closed','closed','','two-dangers-to-the-church','','','2016-07-19 00:36:39','2016-07-19 08:36:39','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1438',0,'post','',0),(2450,44,'2015-11-09 14:09:14','2015-11-09 22:09:14','You might have heard rumors about EPIK Project, an anti-sex trafficking organization that lives up to its name, determined to dissolve the commercial sex industry by aiming straight at the source—demand.\n\nOur partnership with EPIK started as a pilot group and Missional Community out of Westside and is now a movement that’s expanding into cities across the country, raising up teams of men willing to fight against demand for sexually trafficked women. The organization posts fake online ads in order to establish communication with local sex buyers. The partners and volunteers on these regular “cyber patrols,” which happen seven times per month, then educate men about what they’re contributing to and assist them in getting help.\n\n“It’s all about love,” says John Patton, one of the partners behind EPIK. “It’s firm love, but it’s love. These guys need Jesus and they need to feel accepted and loved.”\n\nThe truth is, many men who call to buy sex don’t understand the cruel reality of the industry—that no woman is in it by choice, that they’re being controlled and coerced, that a common age for girls to get caught in the industry is age 13. Sadly, some men also know exactly what they’re buying. Either way, every man calling to buy sex is fueling demand for an industry that keeps young girls and women in slavery. EPIK’s goal is to stop sex trafficking in its tracks by raising up a team of men willing to fight against demand in the sex trade.\n\n“Some of these guys are doing it because they want to get caught—it’s a relief when they get caught,” John says. “They don’t think they can stop without help.”\n\nTo date, EPIK has had about 16,000 communications and contact with 3,500 unique individuals attempting to buy sex, and has directly contributed to four arrests, including a teacher calling from his own classroom. Some men hang up immediately, and others stay on the phone for a conversation. Rather than seeking arrests, the vision is that one conversation at a time, men stop buying sex and demand is reduced to zero. These efforts have made a documented disruptive impact on the Portland sex market and led to a wealth of data on the local industry.\n\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/epik-graph.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-1768 size-full\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/epik-graph.jpg\" alt=\"epik graph\" width=\"599\" height=\"429\" /></a>\n\nSex trafficking is an estimated $60 million industry in Portland alone. Hundreds of thousands of young women, many of them underage, are forced or coerced into selling their bodies for the profit of their oppressors. Many great organizations throughout the city are doing something to fight it, often by caring for girls who have survived the commercial sex industry, and helping them heal and transition into a new lifestyle. Understandably, the staff and volunteers with these organizations are commonly women because broken relationships with men in the past have made new relationships with men very sensitive.\n\nA few years ago, a man named Tom Perez had a vision. He invited men to partner in redeeming their communities by stopping the very demand for sex trafficking. EPIK Project is an avenue for men to get deeply involved in the fight. There’s still a lot of work to do to end this form of slavery that plagues cities all around the world.\n<h3>Sex Trafficking Prevention Training</h3>\n<strong>Nov 19 at 6:30 PM, Imago Dei Community, Room 101</strong>\n<strong><span style=\"color: #222222;\">1302 SE Ankeny St, Portland, OR 97214</span></strong>\n\nAny men, over 18 years old, with no criminal background, interested in joining the cause are invited to a meeting, where they will be educated on the nature of the sex trafficking industry, what happens to people when they’re arrested, and, of course, psychological training for the phone patrols in which volunteers will be communicating with men who are calling to buy sex.\n\n“If men would stop buying, this would stop happening,” John says. If there’s no demand to buy sex, then the industry ceases to exist. The abuse stops, the slavery stops.\n\n[page_actions]<a title=\"EPIK Project Home\" href=\"http://www.epikproject.org/#/the-story/the-story\" target=\"_blank\">EPIKProject.org</a>[/page_actions]\n\n&nbsp;','Ending Sex Trafficking with EPIK Project','','trash','closed','closed','','ending-sex-trafficking-with-epik-project__trashed','','','2016-07-18 22:28:40','2016-07-19 06:28:40','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1767',0,'post','',0),(2451,19,'2015-11-16 14:18:33','2015-11-16 22:18:33','On an unassuming night over two thousand years ago, God appeared; not as a heavenly warrior, or an intangible spirit, or a terrifying force of nature, but as a baby. A small, frail, human baby born to two teenagers in a cave. Through this child, the unknown God became known. The invisible God became visible. These songs are a celebration of that story.\r\n[page_actions]<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/christ-is-born-ep/id1053951293\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase on iTunes</a>[/page_actions]\r\n\r\n<style>.embed-container { position: relative; padding-bottom: 56.25%; height: 0; overflow: hidden; max-width: 100%; } .embed-container iframe, .embed-container object, .embed-container embed { position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; height: 100%; }</style><div class=\'embed-container\'><iframe src=\'https://player.vimeo.com/video/112950972\' frameborder=\'0\' webkitAllowFullScreen mozallowfullscreen allowFullScreen></iframe></div>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<hr />\r\n<h3>Credits</h3>\r\n<font size=\"3\">Evan Wickham: Vocals, Acoustic Guitars, Piano\r\nEric Lemiere: Drums, Guitars, Bass, Keys\r\nMichael Watson: Vocals\r\nWhitney DePaoli: Vocals\r\nMatthew Zigenis: Vocals, Guitars\r\nSandy Wickham: Vocals\r\nMadison Cunningham: Vocals\r\nKevin Kostanko: Drums\r\nAllison Bote: Piano\r\nPeter Hong: Guitars\r\nNick DePartee: Guitars\r\nHoratiu Titerlea: Guitars\r\nBen Peterson: Bass\r\nAnthony Maerz: Drums\r\n\r\nProducer: Eric Lemiere\r\n\r\nMixed / Mastered: Chris Greely\r\n\r\nSongs: Christ is Born and Realms of Glory written by Evan Wickham & Eric Lemiere.\r\n\r\nVideo Production: Josh Porter\r\nCameras: Garrett Holmes, Patrick Porter, Abi Porter\r\n\r\nGraphic Design: Tyler Hanns\r\n</font>','Christ is Born EP','','publish','closed','closed','','christ-is-born-ep','','','2016-07-18 23:10:08','2016-07-19 07:10:08','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=1824',0,'post','',0),(2452,50,'2016-07-18 22:15:39','2016-07-19 06:15:39','','Blog','','publish','closed','closed','','blog','','','2016-07-18 22:15:39','2016-07-19 06:15:39','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?page_id=2452',8,'page','',0),(2453,50,'2016-07-18 22:55:42','2016-07-19 06:55:42','','ajc_blog_image','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_image','','','2016-07-18 22:55:42','2016-07-19 06:55:42','',1995,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/ajc_blog_image.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2454,50,'2016-07-18 22:56:26','2016-07-19 06:56:26','Truly knowing your Bible through the practice of reading has become a lost art, and it seems we are becoming illiterate toward the narrative of God. In 2016, participate with us in the “Year of Biblical Literacy.” Follow the Bible Reading Plan and work through the entire biblical narrative one day at a time. Along with the Bible, the following books have been tremendously influential in shaping the series:\n&nbsp;\n\n<h5>Eat This Book by Eugene Peterson</h5>\nEat This Book challenges us to read the Scriptures on their own terms, as God’s revelation, and to live them as we read them. With warmth and wisdom Peterson offers greatly needed, down-to-earth counsel on spiritual reading. In these pages he draws readers into a fascinating conversation on the nature of language, the ancient practice of lectio divina, and the role of Scripture translations\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Eat-This-Book-Conversation-Spiritual/dp/0802864902\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase \"Eat this Book\"</a>[/page_actions]\n&nbsp;\n\n<h5>Read the Bible for a Change by Ray Lubeck</h5>\nWhich Bible passages are for us today and which only apply to the first audience of ancient readers? Can we just pick and choose the verses we think fit our situation? Who gets to decide? In Read the Bible for a Change, Dr. Ray Lubeck helps readers correctly understand and relate the Bible to their lives.\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Read-Bible-Change-Followers-Responding/dp/1932805362\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase \"Read the Bible for a Change\"</a>[/page_actions]\n&nbsp;\n\n<h5>Unbreakable by Andrew Wilson</h5>\nThe book you are looking at is unique. It stands out because unlike most other books on the Bible, it doesn t start with a bunch of objections that people have to the scriptures. Nor does it begin with information about the Bible\'s authors or the historical contexts they were writing into. Instead, this book uses Jesus as the starting point!\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Unbreakable-What-Said-About-Word/dp/1909611867/ref=sr_1_fkmr0_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1452621103&sr=8-1-fkmr0&keywords=Unbreakable”+by+Andrew+Wilson\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase \"Unbreakable\"</a>[/page_actions]\n&nbsp;\n\n<h5>The Books of the Bible (NIV)</h5>\nReturn to the Bible as it was before chapters and verses. The Books of the Bible, NIV is a revolutionary new presentation of Scripture that strips away centuries of artificial formatting, leaving behind nothing but pure Bible text. The result is a hardcover Bible unlike any other available today—and more like the original Scriptures.\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.christianbook.com/the-books-of-the-bible-niv/9780310400578/pd/400578?event=AAI\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase \"The Books of the Bible\"</a>[/page_actions]\n&nbsp;\n\n<h5>NIV Study Bible by Don Carson</h5>\nThe NIV Study Bible is built on the truth of Scripture and centered on the gospel message. An ambitious and comprehensive undertaking, over 60 contributors from a wide range of evangelical denominations and perspectives, crafted all-new study notes and other study tools to present a biblical theology of God’s special revelation in the Scriptures.\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Zondervan-Study-Bible-Hardcover-Digital/dp/0310438330/ref=pd_sim_14_1?ie=UTF8&amp;dpID=41RVOe8eJ5L&amp;dpSrc=sims&amp;preST=_AC_UL160_SR108%2C160_&amp;refRID=07ZSJGSRYBY0DHXWH4PN\" target=\"_blank\">Purchase \"NIV Study Bible\"</a>[/page_actions]\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\nLearn more about the Year of Biblical Literacy and follow along with the Bible Reading Plan and teachings.\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bible/\">Year of Biblical Literacy</a>[/page_actions]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','Year of Biblical Literacy: Recommended Reading','','inherit','closed','closed','','1995-autosave-v1','','','2016-07-18 22:56:26','2016-07-19 06:56:26','',1995,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/1995-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2455,50,'2016-07-18 22:58:47','2016-07-19 06:58:47','','ajc_blog_8vocation','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_8vocation','','','2016-07-18 22:58:47','2016-07-19 06:58:47','',1794,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/ajc_blog_8vocation.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2456,50,'2016-07-18 22:59:48','2016-07-19 06:59:48','When it comes to vocation, as a church, we’re all over the map.\n\nSome of us know exactly who we are and what we’re called to do. Others of us have no clue. You’re trackless, visionless, lost and confused. But you would give anything to know. And a lot of you are somewhere in the middle – you have a vague sense, but it’s not clear yet.\n\nWherever you’re at, one of the best ways to discover your vocation is to ask questions.\n\nLots of questions.\n\nHere are eight questions to help you discover your vocation:\n<h3>1. What do you love (or hate)?</h3>\nPut another way, what are you passionate about? What makes you light up with joy? Or what makes you sad and angry? What keeps you up at night?\n\nStart there.\n\nGerry Breshears said it best for young people: \"Figure out what you love, and then see if you can make a living at it.\"\n\n<span style=\"color: #525252;\">My favorite question for people is, if you could do anything, what would it be?</span>\n\nAll the realists are thinking, come on, it’s not that easy. You’re right. It’s not. But it’s crazy that more people don’t pursue what’s in their heart. Honestly, the number one reason is fear. If you’re a follower of Jesus, the last thing that should determine your future is fear.\n\nWhat’s in your heart? Go after it.\n<h3>2. What are you good at (and bad at)?</h3>\nWe all know people who really want to be a singer or a designer or whatever, but they just are not very good at it.\n\nGrowing up, I was really into basketball, and I wanted to play in the NBA. I would practice for hours in the driveway. There was just one thing – I was so bad. I don’t have an athletic bone in my body. So eventually, after years of embarrassment, I gave it up.\n\nBut then I found music. I was pretty good at music. My band ended up getting signed to a record label.\n\nBut then I found teaching. And it hit me, I think this could be my thing.\n\nWe all want to get to the point where we’re really good at something. Now, it takes years to even figure out what you’re good and bad at, and decades longer to become a maestro in your field. So experiment. You’ll do some things and come alive and people all around you will say, \"Wow, you’re amazing at that.\"\n\nAnd you’ll do other things and hate every minute of it and people all around you will say, \"Yeah, maybe you should do something else with your life…\"\n\nThat’s okay. Celebrate it.\n\nSometimes failure means you just need to take another run at it, and not give up; but other times, it means you just took another step forward in learning what you’re not called to. That’s a gift. Because with each success, and with each so-called failure, you’re getting a clearer and clearer sense of your vocation.\n<h3>3. What does the world need?</h3>\nWhen you look at the world – at your city, your nation, your generation – what is missing? What is it that the world needs more of? Or less of?\n\nWhen you look out at the world, what do you see and think to yourself, \"Somebody needs to fix that?\" Maybe that somebody is you.\n\nThe novelist Frederick Buechner put it this way, \"Work is the place where your gladness meets the world’s deep need.” That’s what you’re looking for – the intersection between what you love, what you’re good at, and what the world needs.\n<h3>4. Does it make the world a more Garden-like place?</h3>\nWe are not just called to any kind of work. We’re called to make a Garden-like world where image bearers can flourish and thrive.\n\nWhat about your work?\n\nIs it good work? Good for the earth, for the economy, for the developing world? Does it reshape the raw materials of planet earth into an environment where human beings can live with God?\n\nMost importantly, is it something that God smiles on?\n\nAfter all, his opinion on your work matters more than anybody else. After a hard day’s work, can you hear God whisper in your ear, “Well done”?\n\nThere are some kinds of work that cannot be a vocation, or a calling from God, like using your body in a pornographic or sexualized way, or siphoning the natural resources of the developing world so the 1% can live just a little bit better. The only jobs that can be a calling from God are those that harmonize with Jesus’ vision of the kingdom.\n\nWhat about your job or career or college major or dream for the future? Does it make the world a more Garden-like place?\n<h3>5. What are people who know you saying?</h3>\nSometimes people close to us – family, friends, our missional community – have a unique vantage point to see our life from the outside in. Ask those people what they think you should do with your life.\n\nWhat do you see in me?\n\nLet’s say you want to start a food cart. Does your community support your desire and affirm it? Or do they caution you against it? Obviously, opinion and bias come in here and people aren’t God, but, a wise man or woman will ask people what they think, and then listen.\n<h3>6. What are the open doors in your life?</h3>\nWhat’s right in front of you?\n\nWhat’s happening? What’s not happening?\n\nYou gotta be careful with that second question, because sometimes a closed door is just a timing thing, or it means you need to go knock a little bit louder, or maybe even throw your shoulder into it – but hopefully you get what I’m saying. Sometimes a calling is staring us in the face, we just need to make eye contact.\n<h3>7. Is there anything that God is blessing?</h3>\nMaybe there’s an area in your life that God just keeps blessing. You’re good and getting better at it. Open doors keep coming your way, and it’s doing a lot of good in the world. Keep moving in that direction.\n\nAll by itself, this question could mislead you. But in the lineup of all these other questions, maybe something becomes apparent. It’s almost like, in that area, everything you touch turns to gold. It could be God’s way of saying, \"This is your vocation.\"\n<h3>8. What is the Spirit stirring in your heart?</h3>\nThis is similar to the first question, but different because sometimes the Spirit will call us to do stuff we don’t want to do.\n\nHonestly, I swore I would never become a pastor. And here I am.\n\nIs there anything that the Spirit is stirring deep inside you? Some sense of destiny you just can’t shake? Something you feel like you have to do as an act of obedience and submission to God?\n\nThere are all sorts of things that sound fun to me, and I could hopefully make a living doing any number of them – but teaching the Scriptures is the thing I feel like I have to do. Maybe that’s a bad example because it’s spiritual sounding. But it could just as well be designing homes, or writing Young Adult Sci-Fi books, or opening a taco stand.\n\nMaybe the answer to this question is no, there’s nothing. That’s cool, keep searching.\n\nBut maybe there is something, and you carry a healthy, sober fear of God about it. If so, whatever that is, go do it…\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<hr />\n\n&nbsp;\n\nExcerpt from a teaching by John Mark Comer as part of the Garden City teaching series.\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/series/garden-city/\">Listen to Teachings</a>[/page_actions]\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;','8 Questions to Help Discover Your Vocation','','inherit','closed','closed','','1794-autosave-v1','','','2016-07-18 22:59:48','2016-07-19 06:59:48','',1794,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/1794-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2457,50,'2016-07-18 23:04:47','2016-07-19 07:04:47',' ','','','publish','closed','closed','','2457','','','2016-07-26 17:16:43','2016-07-27 01:16:43','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/?p=2457',7,'nav_menu_item','',0),(2458,50,'2016-07-18 23:09:54','2016-07-19 07:09:54','','ajc_album_christisborn_blog','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_album_christisborn_blog','','','2016-07-18 23:09:54','2016-07-19 07:09:54','',2451,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/ajc_album_christisborn_blog.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(2459,50,'2016-07-18 23:13:16','2016-07-19 07:13:16','','ajc_gardencity_blog_image','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_gardencity_blog_image','','','2016-07-18 23:13:16','2016-07-19 07:13:16','',1775,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/ajc_gardencity_blog_image.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2460,50,'2016-07-18 23:27:42','2016-07-19 07:27:42','','ajc_blog_refugeee_5','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_refugeee_5','','','2016-07-18 23:27:42','2016-07-19 07:27:42','',1745,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ajc_blog_refugeee_5.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2461,50,'2016-07-18 23:28:30','2016-07-19 07:28:30','','ajc_blog_refugee_1','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_refugee_1','','','2016-07-18 23:28:30','2016-07-19 07:28:30','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugee_1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2462,50,'2016-07-18 23:28:34','2016-07-19 07:28:34','','ajc_blog_refugeee_2_','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_refugeee_2_','','','2016-07-18 23:28:34','2016-07-19 07:28:34','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugeee_2_.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2463,50,'2016-07-18 23:28:38','2016-07-19 07:28:38','','ajc_blog_refugeee_3','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_refugeee_3','','','2016-07-18 23:28:38','2016-07-19 07:28:38','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugeee_3.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2464,50,'2016-07-18 23:28:41','2016-07-19 07:28:41','','ajc_blog_refugeee_4','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_refugeee_4','','','2016-07-18 23:28:41','2016-07-19 07:28:41','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugeee_4.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2465,50,'2016-07-18 23:29:37','2016-07-19 07:29:37','The current refugee crisis has forced millions of people around the world to flee their homes, and the number grows daily. The quota for refugees entering the United States started over on October 1, so there will be around 1,300 refugees coming to Portland within the next year.\n\nRefugee families arrive to the U.S., usually with just a garbage bag of clothes or a couple suitcases. They’re set up in a small apartment, but they lack all of the household items needed to begin their lives again. Restart Kits provide these items that are desperately needed upon arrival.\n\nRestart Kits are a tangible way of showing God’s love to people that have faced devastating circumstances. We want refugees to know that they’re welcome here, and that we\'re excited and honored to have them in Portland.\n\nThere are six different types of Restart Kits: personal care kit, kitchen kit, bathroom kit, cleaning kit, baby kit, and a welcome kit, which include toiletries, dishes and silverware, bath towels, laundry detergent, baby diapers, and other essential items.\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://www.hearthecry.org/site/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/Restart.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Restart Kit Item Lists</a> [/page_actions]\n<h1>Refugee Care Collection Day</h1>\n<strong>Saturday, Oct 24, between 12 – 5 PM</strong>\n<strong>10160 SW Nimbus Ave, Suite F-3, Portland, OR, 97223</strong>\n\nWe’re collecting Restart Kits and new or gently used winter jackets during the Refugee Care Collection Day. There’s a huge need with hundreds of refugees coming to Portland in the next few months. So the invitation is to look at the Refugee Restart Kit List, and build a Restart Kit or bring a couple winter jackets. Thanks for helping us welcome refugees to Portland!\n\n[page_actions][email address=Megan@HearTheCry.org]Contact for more information[/email][/page_actions]\n\n<hr />\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1746\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugee_1.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugee_1\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\n\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1747\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_refugeee_2_.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugeee_2_\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\n\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1748\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ajc_blog_refugeee_3.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugeee_3\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />\n\n\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1749\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/ajc_blog_refugeee_4.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_blog_refugeee_4\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" />','Care for Refugees in Portland','','inherit','closed','closed','','1745-autosave-v1','','','2016-07-18 23:29:37','2016-07-19 07:29:37','',1745,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/1745-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2466,50,'2016-07-19 00:02:18','2016-07-19 08:02:18','','ajc_blog_spokane','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_spokane','','','2016-07-19 00:02:18','2016-07-19 08:02:18','',1637,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_blog_spokane.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2467,50,'2016-07-19 00:04:01','2016-07-19 08:04:01','','ajc_spokane_diesen','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_spokane_diesen','','','2016-07-19 00:04:01','2016-07-19 08:04:01','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_spokane_diesen.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2468,50,'2016-07-19 00:05:19','2016-07-19 08:05:19','','ajc_spokane_karsh','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_spokane_karsh','','','2016-07-19 00:05:19','2016-07-19 08:05:19','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_spokane_karsh.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2469,50,'2016-07-19 00:05:44','2016-07-19 08:05:44','The vision for Spokane started about six years ago on a bus. God spoke to Matt Karsh as he was riding through the city, and said “There is going to be a church here.” And from this simple beginning, the church began to grow.\n\nOver the last six years the vision has continued to gain momentum, and eventually we decided to go and visit the city. Immediately, we could see God at work there. The Holy Spirit is calling people to be a part of this church plant. We were encountering people hungry for something new, who are eager to see a fresh expression of church in their city. So we started to dream.\n\nAfter doing some research, we have come to learn that Spokane is filled with over 400,000 people who don’t know Jesus. Each of those individuals is what motivates us to plant a new church in Spokane. At the same time, our family of churches have become increasingly aware of the story being written in their midst, recognizing a strong call to continue planting churches in the Northwest and beyond. For the last few years we have been praying about what it would look like to plant a church in the city of Spokane, and we invite you to be a part of the work.\n<h1>Matt &amp; Abby Deisen</h1>\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_spokane_diesen.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1627\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_spokane_diesen.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_spokane_diesen\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe Spokane church plant will be co-pastored. Matt Deisen was an attorney who gave up practicing law when God called him into vocational ministry. He has served on the staff at Westside: A Jesus Church for the last two years as an embedded church planter. Abby has been serving as a leader at Westside for nearly a decade and is currently devoted to raising their son Moses.\n<h1>Matt &amp; Jenna Karsh</h1>\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_spokane_karsh.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1628\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_spokane_karsh.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_spokane_karsh\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nMatt Karsh recently graduated from Western Seminary and has worked on staff at Sunset: A Jesus Church for the last three years. Jenna works in the school district and is studying to become a school counselor. Matt and Jenna are already living and working in the city of Spokane, getting to know the city and its people.\n<h1>Contact</h1>\nContact us if you have any questions about the Spokane Church Plant or would like to get involved.\n\n[page_actions][email address=mkarsh@ajesuschurch.org]Spokane Contact[/email][email address=mattd@ajesuschurch.org]Portland Contact[/email][/page_actions]\n<h1>Spokane Church Plant</h1>\n<span style=\"color: #525252;\">For all the information about the Spokane Church Plant, including giving and a schedule for prayer meetings, visit their website.</span>\n\n[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/spokane/\">Spokane Church Plant</a>[/page_actions]\n\n&nbsp;','Spokane Church Plant','','inherit','closed','closed','','1637-autosave-v1','','','2016-07-19 00:05:44','2016-07-19 08:05:44','',1637,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/1637-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2470,50,'2016-07-19 00:08:58','2016-07-19 08:08:58','','ajc_blog_bend','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_bend','','','2016-07-19 00:08:58','2016-07-19 08:08:58','',1644,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_blog_bend.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2471,50,'2016-07-19 00:09:17','2016-07-19 08:09:17','','ajc_bend_rothrock','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_bend_rothrock','','','2016-07-19 00:09:17','2016-07-19 08:09:17','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_bend_rothrock.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2472,50,'2016-07-19 00:09:37','2016-07-19 08:09:37','<p style=\"color: #525252;\">Bend is all about a lifestyle. It’s about year-round outdoor adventure. It’s about cuisine and beer and coffee. Therefore, Bend is attracting a wave of millennials who want to experience a piece of Heaven on Earth. Over the last year, the leadership has been seeking God in prayer about what it might look like to plant A Jesus Church in Bend.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">According to a 2010 census, 74% of residents in Deschutes County do not adhere to a “religious” system of belief. Only 11% of residents identify themselves as Evangelical Protestant. But because of the rapid influx of Millennials (who are less likely to be connected to a faith community) moving into the heart of Bend, we believe the statistics today in west Bend are even more drastic.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">So, how is God calling the A Jesus Church Family to respond? Simply stated: to be the Church in Bend. God is calling us to be the family of God, on the mission of God, making disciples of Jesus in the heart of Bend. Our vision is to see an unified collection of Missional Communities who identify the pocket of Bend they are uniquely suited to share the Gospel of Jesus with, and who live together on mission there.</p>\n\n<h1>Andrew &amp; Grace Rothrock</h1>\n<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_bend_rothrock.jpg\"><img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-1630\" src=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/09/ajc_bend_rothrock.jpg\" alt=\"ajc_bend_rothrock\" width=\"1200\" height=\"691\" /></a>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nAndrew is an outdoor enthusiast and lifelong resident of Oregon with a deep love for the beauty and adventure in the Pacific Northwest. Grace grew up all over the states and abroad in a missionary family, and as an adult, landed in Portland with our family of churches back when we were called Solid Rock. Their pursuit of  becoming more like Jesus is what brought them together six years ago. They have a three year-old daughter named Isabel.\n\nAndrew and Grace are avid students of the Scripture and love to share life with other followers of Jesus. They are relocating from Central Oregon to Portland for a season to become embedded church planters at Westside, to train with the leadership, and build a team to join them in planting in April 2017.\n<h1>Contact</h1>\nIf you have questions or to learn more about how you can be involved in the Bend Church Plant, connect with Andrew Rothrock.\n\n[page_actions][email address=andrew.rothrock@ajesuschurch.org]Contact Andrew Rothrock[/email][/page_actions]\n<h1 style=\"color: #030303;\">Bend Church Website</h1>\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">For all the information about the Bend Church Plant, including giving and a schedule for prayer meetings, visit their website.</p>\n<p style=\"color: #525252;\">[page_actions]<a href=\"http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/bend/\">Bend Church Plant</a>[/page_actions]</p>\n&nbsp;','Bend Church Plant','','inherit','closed','closed','','1644-autosave-v1','','','2016-07-19 00:09:37','2016-07-19 08:09:37','',1644,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/1644-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(2473,50,'2016-07-19 00:12:19','2016-07-19 08:12:19','','ajc_blog_bt_reading','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_bt_reading','','','2016-07-19 00:12:19','2016-07-19 08:12:19','',0,'http://bridgetown.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/ajc_blog_bt_reading.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2474,50,'2016-07-19 00:16:02','2016-07-19 08:16:02','','ajc_blog_unknown','','inherit','open','closed','','ajc_blog_unknown','',